WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.960
[Amit Varma]: If there is one thing in our lives that is unseen, it is the role of the state. There

00:00:07.960 --> 00:00:12.000
[Amit Varma]: is nothing quite as oppressive as a modern state, the apparatus of government and all

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:17.000
[Amit Varma]: its agencies. And yet, we have normalized that oppression. Now, the state has a monopoly

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:22.440
[Amit Varma]: on violence, and you could argue that it needs to, because that is how it protects our rights.

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:26.160
[Amit Varma]: That is the one legitimate purpose of the state, right? To protect our rights, to serve

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:32.840
[Amit Varma]: us for we are the masters. In theory. In reality, we are less citizens than subjects. When India

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:37.440
[Amit Varma]: gained independence in 1947, we got rid of the British, but we did not get freedom from

00:00:37.440 --> 00:00:42.340
[Amit Varma]: oppression. That same state apparatus that was used to control us in colonial times was

00:00:42.340 --> 00:00:47.760
[Amit Varma]: maintained by our new brown-skinned masters. If anything, it became more brutal and more

00:00:47.760 --> 00:00:52.880
[Amit Varma]: sophisticated. And yeah, sure, we have elections, but democracy is not just about voting. You

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:59.160
[Amit Varma]: also need mechanisms to safeguard the rights of citizens and to hold the state accountable.

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:05.200
[Amit Varma]: Those mechanisms don't exist. Every election is basically a competition between rival mafias

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:10.280
[Amit Varma]: to see who can rule the people and extract all that they can for whatever time they have

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:31.320
[Amit Varma]: in power. The rewards are great, and they are enabled by the security state.

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:35.840
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Josie Joseph, a pioneering investigative

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:40.800
[Amit Varma]: journalist who's written an excellent book named The Silent Coup, A History of India's

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:45.960
[Amit Varma]: Deep State. In this book, he examines and exposes how India's security state has so

00:01:45.960 --> 00:01:51.200
[Amit Varma]: many unseen layers to it and how it rules our lives and is damaging our society. We

00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:55.280
[Amit Varma]: have seen different aspects of the security state in play. We know the corrupt rent-seeking

00:01:55.280 --> 00:01:59.440
[Amit Varma]: police, though most of us thankfully don't have to deal with them beyond bribes or traffic

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:05.360
[Amit Varma]: signals. The rule of law is absent in India, but the police is all-powerful. So is a taxman

00:02:05.360 --> 00:02:10.560
[Amit Varma]: often used by the political class as a tool to subjugate those who don't toe the line.

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:15.640
[Amit Varma]: And there are a range of other investigative agencies whose incentives are tailored only

00:02:15.640 --> 00:02:20.320
[Amit Varma]: towards pleasing their political masters. And what they get up to with the unbridled

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:25.000
[Amit Varma]: power that they have is staggering. The Silent Coup is a book you must read for that reason.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:29.080
[Amit Varma]: And I enjoyed my conversation with Josie. Before we get to it, though, let's take a

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:36.600
[Amit Varma]: quick commercial break. Long before I was a podcaster, I was a writer. In fact, chances

00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:41.280
[Amit Varma]: are that many of you first heard of me because of my blog, India Uncut, which was active

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:46.600
[Amit Varma]: between 2003 and 2009 and became somewhat popular at the time. I love the freedom the

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:52.320
[Amit Varma]: form gave me, and I feel I was shaped by it in many ways. I exercise my writing muscle

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:56.800
[Amit Varma]: every day and was forced to think about many different things because I wrote about many

00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:01.720
[Amit Varma]: different things. Well, that phase in my life ended for various reasons. And now it is time

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:07.040
[Amit Varma]: to revive it. Only now I'm doing it through a newsletter. I have started the India Uncut

00:03:07.040 --> 00:03:13.280
[Amit Varma]: newsletter at indiancut.substack.com where I will write regularly about whatever catches

00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:18.760
[Amit Varma]: my fancy. I'll write about some of the themes I cover in this podcast and about much else.

00:03:18.760 --> 00:03:25.120
[Amit Varma]: So please do head on over to indiancut.substack.com and subscribe. It is free. Once you sign up,

00:03:25.120 --> 00:03:29.360
[Amit Varma]: each new installment that I write will land up in your email inbox. You don't need to

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:37.040
[Amit Varma]: go anywhere. So subscribe now for free. The India Uncut newsletter at indiancut.substack.com.

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:38.040
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:40.960
[Amit Varma]: Josie, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:43.080
[Guest]: Thank you, Amit. It's a great privilege.

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:47.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I've been waiting for a long time to ask you actually, I think we met at the Bangalore

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:50.940
[Amit Varma]: Lit Fest a couple of years ago. And I said, Hey, come on sometime and we'll discuss Feast

00:03:50.940 --> 00:03:56.240
[Amit Varma]: of Vultures. But now we finally get to talk when your new excellent book is out, which

00:03:56.240 --> 00:04:00.660
[Amit Varma]: everyone should read. And I hear that the first print run is also sold out. So congratulations

00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:05.040
[Amit Varma]: for that. Before we sort of start talking about the book per se, I'd love to know a

00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:10.000
[Amit Varma]: little bit more about your life. We are actually I think born in the same year 1973. I heard

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.760
[Amit Varma]: you reveal your year in this TEDx talk you gave. So tell me a little bit about where

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:20.800
[Amit Varma]: you grew up, what your early years were like that journey until you eventually became a

00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:21.800
[Amit Varma]: journalist.

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:28.920
[Guest]: Amit, I was born in a very lower middle class family by the backwaters in Alleppey. My father

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:35.520
[Guest]: was an accountant, a local tax consultant. I always saw this great debate at home about

00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:42.280
[Guest]: my dad's wild ambition for education and children and obsession with education. My mother was

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:46.680
[Guest]: more like, you know, saying that, look, pursuit of happiness is being happy for today, right?

00:04:46.680 --> 00:04:51.720
[Guest]: So I always saw this great debate of pursuit of happiness between the two of them. But

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:57.600
[Guest]: together they ensured that. And we are four siblings. And, you know, my dad, when he heard

00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:02.200
[Guest]: about Saini schools, someone from my village went and became a teacher in Saini school

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:07.720
[Guest]: in Trivandrum. So my father got obsessed with it. And he tried with my elder brothers who

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:12.080
[Guest]: couldn't. First one was overage, second one was underage, whatever. Anyway, I became the

00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:17.920
[Guest]: guinea pig and after my first five years in schooling, I landed in Saini school, Trivandrum.

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:23.920
[Guest]: It's thanks to that socialist India, the government subsidized public school education that I

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:29.320
[Guest]: could speak English. I could learn English. Until then, I was in a Malayalam medium school.

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:35.720
[Guest]: I'm very acutely aware of the privileges of state subsidy that has done and the impact

00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:41.120
[Guest]: it has on people like us. And I'm very proud of the fact that, you know, despite it's being

00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:44.760
[Guest]: called a Saini school, I think it's a great public school for the poor and middle class

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:50.560
[Guest]: bright kids. And schools, Saini schools across India continues to produce hundreds of very

00:05:50.560 --> 00:05:55.800
[Guest]: outstanding, in fact, thousands of outstanding professionals into military and outside. And

00:05:55.800 --> 00:06:03.080
[Guest]: I think a lot of values are shared. And it is not overstating a fact to say that you

00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:08.800
[Guest]: take a sample of Saini school products and you'll find them unusually high on integrity,

00:06:08.800 --> 00:06:14.520
[Guest]: on morals, commitment to nationalism, etc, etc. So, I went to Saini school till 12th.

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:19.760
[Guest]: I came back home. My parents, my mother especially wanted, I told you the pursuit of happiness

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:25.520
[Guest]: debates. Mother wanted me to be home. So, I went to study BSc in mathematics. I was

00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:31.360
[Guest]: quite a good student in mathematics. But after two years of doing well in mathematics, I

00:06:31.360 --> 00:06:36.040
[Guest]: realized that my heart lies in writing and other things. Anyway, I completed mathematics

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:43.680
[Guest]: BSc and came to Delhi in the hope of becoming a civil servant. And I did the usual rounds

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:50.320
[Guest]: of civil service training institutes. And I think I paid money at Rao's academy also

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:58.600
[Guest]: to enroll. But one of those days happenstance happened and I landed up in Delhi midday office.

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:03.160
[Guest]: John Dale used to be the editor. A common acquaintance had introduced me to him. I went

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:10.520
[Guest]: to meet him. So, when I was there, he said Rajan Pillai, the biscuit tycoon who was running

00:07:10.520 --> 00:07:16.680
[Guest]: Britannia and who was in a big legal corporate war. He had just disappeared from Singapore

00:07:16.680 --> 00:07:21.160
[Guest]: and there was a manhunt for him, etc. So, he asked me to write a profile of Rajan Pillai

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:29.960
[Guest]: and I wrote that. And that changed my life. I never sat for civil service exam. I never

00:07:29.960 --> 00:07:36.240
[Guest]: wanted to be one again because of the kick of writing, the fun of it all just hooked

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:42.080
[Guest]: me and the first article got me a lot of attention, a lot of local attention. So, I've been a

00:07:42.080 --> 00:07:48.920
[Guest]: journalist since then. To satisfy parents that I'm studying, I did an evening course

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:55.400
[Guest]: in PG Diploma in Journalism in YMCA, where one of the teachers couldn't even… So, even

00:07:55.400 --> 00:07:58.880
[Guest]: despite I topping his paper, he couldn't recognize me because I would very hardly go

00:07:58.880 --> 00:08:05.640
[Guest]: to classes. I was busy in my practical journalism. That's how I became a journalist. So, there

00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:11.840
[Guest]: is no other fancy story to it. It's a very average Indian story of this above average

00:08:11.840 --> 00:08:18.920
[Guest]: student from an ordinary or a poor family managing to get to the city with education

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:25.000
[Guest]: and starting off with the limited options available to us in those days. I'm talking

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:31.080
[Guest]: about the early 90s. That's it. Liberalization was just happening around, but the benefits

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:37.400
[Guest]: were to raise the media houses. Journalism salaries were very low. Yeah, that's all.

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:41.760
[Amit Varma]: That's not all. There's a lot there that leads me to think of future questions. Firstly,

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:46.760
[Amit Varma]: I'm intrigued by the values you mentioned at Sainik School. So, what were those kind

00:08:46.760 --> 00:08:51.000
[Amit Varma]: of values in the sense that you say that today you meet, you know, anybody from Sainik School,

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:56.080
[Amit Varma]: you can sort of that integrity is always there and so on. So, tell me a little bit more about

00:08:56.080 --> 00:09:01.720
[Amit Varma]: that. And then when you encounter people outside of that environment, when you first did, did

00:09:01.720 --> 00:09:06.600
[Amit Varma]: that difference become stark? Was there an awareness that there is one way that we have

00:09:06.600 --> 00:09:11.920
[Amit Varma]: been taught to or that we have imbibed in terms of how we think about the world and

00:09:11.920 --> 00:09:15.800
[Amit Varma]: what is actually happening out there, which in a sense, you spend the rest of your life

00:09:15.800 --> 00:09:20.200
[Amit Varma]: uncovering what is actually happening out there is something totally different. Tell

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:26.360
[Amit Varma]: me a little bit about these sort of clash of values. And you know what that was like?

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:29.560
[Guest]: I don't know, Amit, if you went to a boarding school.

00:09:29.560 --> 00:09:36.200
[Amit Varma]: I was for a while a day scholar in a school that was also a boarding school. So yeah.

00:09:36.200 --> 00:09:41.640
[Guest]: So if you go to a boarding school, you are forever, you are a student, you know, and

00:09:41.640 --> 00:09:45.640
[Guest]: they're your brothers. So I think one of the things that boarding schools does to you is

00:09:45.640 --> 00:09:51.240
[Guest]: that it becomes a very close knit community. And so you are almost naked before them for

00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:55.800
[Guest]: a lifetime. So I think there's a lot of, you know, if I may put it in a positive way, peer

00:09:55.800 --> 00:10:02.080
[Guest]: pressure to be good and to do good. This is one of my theories about, I got several theories

00:10:02.080 --> 00:10:07.400
[Guest]: about boarding school. One of it is this. Second is that on every Sunday morning, boarding

00:10:07.400 --> 00:10:12.920
[Guest]: school boys have to rub their bathrooms instead of going to church. I like to do that. So

00:10:12.920 --> 00:10:18.680
[Guest]: I think the bonding that you create in boarding schools have a very positive impact. But there

00:10:18.680 --> 00:10:24.040
[Guest]: is another aspect, which is where Indian military and military ethos come in. We can criticize

00:10:24.040 --> 00:10:28.920
[Guest]: the military for a lot of things, but I think Indian military, luckily for India, has built

00:10:28.920 --> 00:10:35.640
[Guest]: a very strong moralistic framework. It's not 100% perfect. There are problems with it.

00:10:35.640 --> 00:10:39.800
[Guest]: So because the senior schools are run by the military officers, they bring in a certain

00:10:39.800 --> 00:10:47.800
[Guest]: kind of idealism, which is quite naive in many ways, but it helps. And there is a strong

00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:56.000
[Guest]: foundation to it. And I think the third factor to add to it is that, you know, between all

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:02.400
[Guest]: of us, the boarding school gang, we are almost every day talking to each other, right? The

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:07.560
[Guest]: conversations, the concerns we share are the same. The appreciations I receive from them,

00:11:07.560 --> 00:11:14.320
[Guest]: they're my biggest fans and supporters. So it all comes together. And then when I came

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:19.560
[Guest]: out into the public life, and even today, very honestly, despite doing all the so-called

00:11:19.560 --> 00:11:23.880
[Guest]: journalism and all that, I still get fooled by a lot of people. A lot of people take me

00:11:23.880 --> 00:11:29.760
[Guest]: for a ride and I find it, sometimes I feel, and I know, I know that somebody is taking

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:34.040
[Guest]: me for a ride, even when it takes me a lot of time to turn around and tell that person,

00:11:34.040 --> 00:11:39.920
[Guest]: boss, enough is enough, you know. So, but that's, that's part of the personality too,

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:46.320
[Guest]: I suppose. But yeah, it is very stark. So I think Indian society, per se, at large,

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:53.240
[Guest]: we are an amoral society, not even immoral. We can't, you know, when I'm in New Delhi,

00:11:53.240 --> 00:12:01.200
[Guest]: when I meet with certain kind of people, I think that they can't even make the difference

00:12:01.200 --> 00:12:09.480
[Guest]: between immoral and moral. They're so blinded by the pursuit of wealth and power, which

00:12:09.480 --> 00:12:14.440
[Guest]: we see all around. And to me, it is amusing and it agitates me. And maybe that agitation

00:12:14.440 --> 00:12:21.760
[Guest]: is what helps me to do some stories that I've done or continue to do stories that I do.

00:12:21.760 --> 00:12:28.800
[Guest]: Because all of their greed of the politicians or the bureaucrat or corporates, that greed

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:36.000
[Guest]: comes at the cost of people like us. People like us, meaning the poor, ordinary Indians,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:43.440
[Guest]: you know, the ones who go to bed hungry with their stomachs turning. So it comes at a cost.

00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:48.480
[Guest]: That angers me. And a lot of my journalism comes out of it. And that anger is something

00:12:48.480 --> 00:12:56.520
[Guest]: that it continues to boil in me. And despite I being in my late 40s, it hasn't gone down.

00:12:56.520 --> 00:12:59.280
[Guest]: If anything, my anger has only gone up.

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:04.720
[Amit Varma]: So I'm struck by the use of the word immoral in what you just said. And that leads me to

00:13:04.720 --> 00:13:10.920
[Amit Varma]: a slightly sideways pondering, which is that, you know, one could argue that morality is,

00:13:10.920 --> 00:13:15.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, the luxury of those who don't have an empty stomach. And otherwise, in a really

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.280
[Amit Varma]: poor country, when you're desperate, when you're scrambling, you know, do you really

00:13:18.280 --> 00:13:23.640
[Amit Varma]: have the luxury to be moral and it you know, everything comes down to that circumstance.

00:13:23.640 --> 00:13:29.760
[Amit Varma]: And also, many of our values are in fact, shaped by the institutions around us and by

00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:34.080
[Amit Varma]: what is actually happening in our society. Like one of the musings and one of the questions

00:13:34.080 --> 00:13:39.480
[Amit Varma]: that I frequently asked people on the show, including economists, but you know, you might

00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:44.400
[Amit Varma]: have a thought on it. So I'll air it as well. It refers to this whole Jagdish Bhagwati observation

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:49.240
[Amit Varma]: about how Indians tend to be rent seeking while Chinese seek to be profit seeking. Profit

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:52.620
[Amit Varma]: seeking meaning obviously that the only way they can make a profit is by making someone

00:13:52.620 --> 00:13:56.640
[Amit Varma]: else better off and it's a positive sum game and blah, blah, blah. And I don't know enough

00:13:56.640 --> 00:14:00.360
[Amit Varma]: about China to know how true that is. But Indians certainly are rent seeking in the

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:05.880
[Amit Varma]: sense that even today in 2021, a lot of people when they think of starting a business, it's

00:14:05.880 --> 00:14:11.760
[Amit Varma]: the thinking is how do I con somebody? Isko, you know, chootiya kaise banao, if I might

00:14:11.760 --> 00:14:15.720
[Amit Varma]: use unparliamentary language, and that's kind of how it is. And my theory always was that

00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:21.360
[Amit Varma]: the reason we are rent seeking is not something fundamentally wrong with our culture, but

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:25.920
[Amit Varma]: it's partly a result of the institutions we've had since independence, when the state had

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:31.240
[Amit Varma]: such a domineering role and private enterprise was so suppressed, that the only way to really

00:14:31.240 --> 00:14:36.800
[Amit Varma]: get ahead and to make money and all of that was through in some way or the other, using

00:14:36.800 --> 00:14:41.720
[Amit Varma]: the state to make yourself better off or using that power to make yourself better off, which

00:14:41.720 --> 00:14:46.680
[Amit Varma]: is why so many successful capitalists were really crony capitalists not functioning in

00:14:46.680 --> 00:14:52.120
[Amit Varma]: a free market, but with the hand of the state, helping them and so on. Now, a significant

00:14:52.120 --> 00:14:57.880
[Amit Varma]: part of your book also demonstrates how people everywhere are responding to incentives, people

00:14:57.880 --> 00:15:02.840
[Amit Varma]: within the security establishment, bureaucrats, politicians, whatever. And indeed, when you

00:15:02.840 --> 00:15:06.200
[Amit Varma]: were saying you were studying for the civil services, I just wondered for a moment that

00:15:06.200 --> 00:15:11.400
[Amit Varma]: had you joined the civil servants, you know, who knows, maybe you would have turned into

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:15.840
[Amit Varma]: one of them, but maybe your Sanic school values would have shaped you. So you have a comment

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:22.400
[Guest]: to make on this? See, I think we are not reading the Indian society right when we, if we were

00:15:22.400 --> 00:15:28.800
[Guest]: to say that we are rent seekers, for a moment, look at history in the broad sense. So I don't

00:15:28.800 --> 00:15:33.920
[Guest]: know if you know this book called, it's called Geography of Geniuses. What is that book?

00:15:33.920 --> 00:15:41.120
[Guest]: So there is this book where, I have it somewhere here, where he argues that geniuses usually

00:15:41.120 --> 00:15:48.360
[Guest]: you find them in clusters in ancient Greek or in Calcutta during the century ago, etc.

00:15:48.360 --> 00:15:55.720
[Guest]: But if you look at India of the 19, last century's first part, some of the geniuses of our times

00:15:55.720 --> 00:16:02.720
[Guest]: were born or lived from Gandhi to Ambedkar. And today when you read their debates, their

00:16:02.720 --> 00:16:10.120
[Guest]: papers, their books, you realize that probably they were an unusual moment in history, even

00:16:10.120 --> 00:16:16.120
[Guest]: unusually gifted, great people came together and they just disappeared. And those who followed

00:16:16.120 --> 00:16:25.200
[Guest]: them did not have the vision or the capability to sustain what they created for us. Now,

00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:28.440
[Guest]: even today, when we talk about rent seekers, we also have people like the prime G's of

00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:32.760
[Guest]: the world who are doing fantastic work without any compromise. And I think, I think there

00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:39.160
[Guest]: are, we can find a lot of businessmen out there who are doing things without being rent

00:16:39.160 --> 00:16:46.680
[Guest]: seekers, who are doing admirable work. So, I don't know what exactly Dindesh Bhagawati's

00:16:46.680 --> 00:16:52.440
[Guest]: argument is, and I'm not qualified to challenge or critique him because he is such a brilliant

00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:59.080
[Guest]: academic. My theory is that the democratic degeneration that has been happening is spreading

00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:04.520
[Guest]: and degeneration has two things that happens. One is what you said, which is that when it

00:17:04.520 --> 00:17:10.080
[Guest]: is degenerating, and because we are frustrated with the state controls, etc., but in a degenerated

00:17:10.080 --> 00:17:17.320
[Guest]: society, we take the path of least resistance, most of us. So, you are in a degenerated state

00:17:17.320 --> 00:17:23.840
[Guest]: and you become one of them. Otherwise, standing up to it is not a great idea. It's not good

00:17:23.840 --> 00:17:33.600
[Guest]: for your health. The other thing is when moved, when India moved from the socialist state,

00:17:33.600 --> 00:17:39.640
[Guest]: the import substitution policies, etc., into a liberalized economy, we did not make a clean

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:44.800
[Guest]: migration into a clean marketplace. We just shifted all the crap of that old days into

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:51.200
[Guest]: the new marketplace and said, oh, our economy is going to boom. What boom was it? You look

00:17:51.200 --> 00:17:59.880
[Guest]: at corridors like Bundelkhand to Delhi, Bihar to Bombay, etc. These are modern day slaves.

00:17:59.880 --> 00:18:03.240
[Guest]: Millions are coming to your cities and they're building your infrastructure. Your economic

00:18:03.240 --> 00:18:11.560
[Guest]: boom is mostly on construction of apartments, roads, airports, etc. So, we haven't actually

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:19.160
[Guest]: created an entrepreneurial marketplace, which would actually reform and improve democracy,

00:18:19.160 --> 00:18:23.000
[Guest]: as you know, except in Singapore. All over the world, when you have entrepreneurial class

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:27.280
[Guest]: emerging, they demand better accountability, etc. Except for Bangalore city, I don't know

00:18:27.280 --> 00:18:33.360
[Guest]: how many citizens is dominated, economy is dominated by entrepreneurship and innovations,

00:18:33.360 --> 00:18:37.800
[Guest]: etc. So, what I'm saying is that one is that many of the people who would actually want

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:46.960
[Guest]: to be good in life are forced to do the immoral acts because they want a good night's sleep.

00:18:46.960 --> 00:18:50.040
[Guest]: They want their family to be safe. They don't want to be threatened. They don't want to

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:58.600
[Guest]: face legal challenges, etc. The second is, over the years, from that Gandhi and Nehruvian

00:18:58.600 --> 00:19:07.360
[Guest]: Ambedkarite values of unbelievable intellect, we have come to a stage where you have leaders

00:19:07.360 --> 00:19:14.960
[Guest]: who ridicule higher education, who ridicule scientific temperament and make all kinds

00:19:14.960 --> 00:19:21.560
[Guest]: of rubbish claims. And you have given power away to criminals. The state has been virtually

00:19:21.560 --> 00:19:27.200
[Guest]: captured by criminal elements at various levels. You might call them political families or

00:19:27.200 --> 00:19:32.440
[Guest]: political stars or whatever it is. But the reality is that if you really look at them,

00:19:32.440 --> 00:19:37.160
[Guest]: remove all the aura around them, remove the constitutional positions around them, and

00:19:37.160 --> 00:19:45.720
[Guest]: who are they? Murder accused, riot accused, cheats. So, we are not just rent seekers.

00:19:45.720 --> 00:19:50.800
[Guest]: I'm saying there is a good India which is not being allowed to come up and speak. That

00:19:50.800 --> 00:19:56.280
[Guest]: India is only allowed to speak and act in conversations with Amit or in some literary

00:19:56.280 --> 00:20:02.920
[Guest]: festivals or in some small groups or on Signal or WhatsApp these days. The marketplace and

00:20:02.920 --> 00:20:09.400
[Guest]: the mainstream of Indian democracy has been taken over by criminals, by rent seekers etc.

00:20:09.400 --> 00:20:14.720
[Guest]: But that doesn't mean that we Indians are all rent seekers. You and I are not.

00:20:14.720 --> 00:20:19.760
[Amit Varma]: I think what Bhagwati kind of meant was exactly what you're saying, that this is, you know,

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:26.160
[Amit Varma]: what the system has created. You've incentivized rent seekers. My brief bunch of responses

00:20:26.160 --> 00:20:31.480
[Amit Varma]: to what you said. One is, of course, I agree about the quality of the leaders that emerged

00:20:31.480 --> 00:20:35.640
[Amit Varma]: in the first part of the last century. And I, in fact, wrote a column also once addressing

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:40.480
[Amit Varma]: this popular question that why were our freedom fighters of such high caliber, where our leaders

00:20:40.480 --> 00:20:45.640
[Amit Varma]: today are not of the high caliber. And my argument was that you just have to look at

00:20:45.640 --> 00:20:50.240
[Amit Varma]: the incentives, that the people who came up then, they had no power to lust for, there

00:20:50.240 --> 00:20:53.760
[Amit Varma]: were no riches or power at the end of the line for them. They were animated purely by

00:20:53.760 --> 00:20:59.760
[Amit Varma]: principles, perhaps even the kind of principles that sanic school students would approve of.

00:20:59.760 --> 00:21:03.480
[Amit Varma]: And they were willing to sacrifice a lot for that. So obviously, you get a certain caliber

00:21:03.480 --> 00:21:08.160
[Amit Varma]: there. So there's a self selection there. Anyone who is devoting their life to that

00:21:08.160 --> 00:21:12.960
[Amit Varma]: kind of work is obviously going to be a higher quality of person. Whereas post independence,

00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:19.160
[Amit Varma]: what we designed at independence was essentially a predatory state. Therefore, you'll get leaders

00:21:19.160 --> 00:21:23.880
[Amit Varma]: then like that who are attracted by the lust for power, which doesn't carry with it safeguards

00:21:23.880 --> 00:21:28.280
[Amit Varma]: or accountability or any of that, where we are a democracy without really being a republic

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:33.560
[Amit Varma]: in the true sense. I think that's kind of been an issue there. And I also agree that,

00:21:33.560 --> 00:21:38.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, 1991, I would say we didn't liberalize enough, we didn't do enough to unleash the

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:43.240
[Amit Varma]: entrepreneurial spirits of our people. I think it did a lot of good, it got your 300 million

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:47.400
[Amit Varma]: people out of poverty and all of that. But the point is, it was very far from a magic

00:21:47.400 --> 00:21:51.600
[Amit Varma]: pill, obviously, look at the state of the country. And if, if anything, we've gone backwards

00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:58.440
[Amit Varma]: in the last 10 years, so it's pretty dire. But we'll kind of come to more, you know,

00:21:58.440 --> 00:22:02.680
[Amit Varma]: details of that direness when we speak about your book, I want to go a little back into

00:22:02.680 --> 00:22:07.680
[Amit Varma]: your past life. I do want to talk about your journalistic years. But even before that,

00:22:07.680 --> 00:22:11.840
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned that, you know, you did the BSc in math, because you had started doing

00:22:11.840 --> 00:22:15.640
[Amit Varma]: it and you said, Okay, I'll finish it. But you were more interested in writing, which

00:22:15.640 --> 00:22:20.280
[Amit Varma]: obviously means that you were reading a lot, because that's how you one becomes interested

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:25.360
[Amit Varma]: in writing. So tell me about the books you read, and you know, who influenced you? You

00:22:25.360 --> 00:22:29.640
[Amit Varma]: know, who were the writers you used to look up to during that period? Give me some sense

00:22:29.640 --> 00:22:34.080
[Amit Varma]: of that. And when you said you wanted to write, what kind of writing did you want to do? Take

00:22:34.080 --> 00:22:37.760
[Amit Varma]: me into the mind of the teenager, Josie.

00:22:37.760 --> 00:22:46.080
[Guest]: I feel very embarrassed talking about myself too much. So, you know, when we were 25 years

00:22:46.080 --> 00:22:51.840
[Guest]: after we were out of boarding school, friends were talking about each other, there was some

00:22:51.840 --> 00:22:56.920
[Guest]: kind of recall about who we were as children. And I was surprised to know that when I was

00:22:56.920 --> 00:23:02.560
[Guest]: 11, 12, I used to tell my friends that I want to be a journalist. I didn't know I couldn't

00:23:02.560 --> 00:23:07.240
[Guest]: recall those, but everyone else recalled the fact that I always was. I was always fond

00:23:07.240 --> 00:23:13.760
[Guest]: of and yeah, I mean, I was, I think I was a voracious reader. And I think my reading

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:21.800
[Guest]: has now come down to more specific reading. But yeah, I mean, like any good Mallu, you

00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:29.800
[Guest]: finish Kafka and Kamyu by the age of 11, sorry, 16 and 17. And you are wrapping up Marquez

00:23:29.800 --> 00:23:35.480
[Guest]: and others. So, you know, they are all brothers for us, right? For all the Mallus and Bongs.

00:23:35.480 --> 00:23:42.000
[Guest]: So yeah, I mean, you know, like we read a lot of Soviet, the communist literature. So

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:47.680
[Guest]: I've read all of the Indian Hindu classics, Mahabharata, Ramayana. In fact, I know more

00:23:47.680 --> 00:23:54.600
[Guest]: of Ramayana, Mahabharata than Bible. And so classics, of course, and then I switched to

00:23:54.600 --> 00:24:01.240
[Guest]: very serious reading of the modern and postmodern writers. When I was, as I was moving into

00:24:01.240 --> 00:24:05.600
[Guest]: my teenage years and we had a network in school where we all shared. I don't know, there are

00:24:05.600 --> 00:24:09.560
[Guest]: some books, you don't know for what reason it remains with you. For example, there was

00:24:09.560 --> 00:24:14.680
[Guest]: a book by James Michener called On Poland, if I'm not wrong. So it stuck with me about

00:24:14.680 --> 00:24:18.520
[Guest]: this little country, which is like the, you know, everyone who comes to Soviet Union,

00:24:18.520 --> 00:24:24.160
[Guest]: goes back, everybody walks over Poland, right? So those kinds of things stuck with me. And

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:29.960
[Guest]: for a long time in my college years, I was very deeply into serious literature, reading

00:24:29.960 --> 00:24:35.480
[Guest]: and magical realism and classics, etc. And I think that influences a lot of my writing.

00:24:35.480 --> 00:24:45.160
[Guest]: If you see, I make this very foolish attempts to ape certain creative writing in my nonfiction.

00:24:45.160 --> 00:24:51.680
[Guest]: So yeah, then after that phase, after I came to Delhi, and when I hit kind of a plateau

00:24:51.680 --> 00:24:56.600
[Guest]: reading fiction, and I couldn't, I wasn't very happy with the new fiction stuff that

00:24:56.600 --> 00:25:03.400
[Guest]: was coming out. And because of journalism, I shifted to reading nonfiction. And I don't

00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:10.200
[Guest]: know what it was, I started reading a lot of history and biographies. And I love large

00:25:10.200 --> 00:25:14.940
[Guest]: events. I like to read about, you know, so I you'll see a lot of those kind of books

00:25:14.940 --> 00:25:21.320
[Guest]: behind me. Now I read so for the last 20-25 years, except for a few fiction books, I have

00:25:21.320 --> 00:25:28.800
[Guest]: only read nonfiction and nonfiction very seriously. And but when you're writing a book, as you

00:25:28.800 --> 00:25:32.120
[Guest]: know, you're reading mostly stuff related to writing because you need to be in that

00:25:32.120 --> 00:25:37.600
[Guest]: world, right? So, you know, I was rereading Basharat Peer and Rahul Pantipa, etc. for

00:25:37.600 --> 00:25:43.200
[Guest]: the book. And now I am reading Transfer of Power Papers and a lot of the history books

00:25:43.200 --> 00:25:48.200
[Guest]: of 4740 because I'm working on something new with my team. So yeah, now the readings are

00:25:48.200 --> 00:25:53.400
[Guest]: much more focused. Unless cumbered, I don't read fiction anymore. But yeah, I've read

00:25:53.400 --> 00:26:00.960
[Guest]: enough fiction to hold a conversation on Latch America or African writers.

00:26:00.960 --> 00:26:04.040
[Amit Varma]: It's also evident in your writing because I just thought that, you know, reading your

00:26:04.040 --> 00:26:08.400
[Amit Varma]: latest book, the storytelling was excellent in it, you know, which is something narrative

00:26:08.400 --> 00:26:13.640
[Amit Varma]: nonfiction writers over the last 40-50 years have certainly picked up from fiction writing

00:26:13.640 --> 00:26:17.800
[Amit Varma]: using novelistic techniques, the way you build a story, the way you structure it, all of

00:26:17.800 --> 00:26:23.240
[Amit Varma]: it was there, it was very interesting. It's not linear, there are interesting things happening,

00:26:23.240 --> 00:26:27.600
[Amit Varma]: there are back and forths and all of that, which I really enjoyed. So, you know, when

00:26:27.600 --> 00:26:33.760
[Amit Varma]: you joined journalism, what was your notion of what makes for an ideal journalist? In

00:26:33.760 --> 00:26:39.960
[Amit Varma]: the sense that I remember back in the 90s, as I reached adulthood and all of that, you

00:26:39.960 --> 00:26:43.280
[Amit Varma]: know, today, the internet is ubiquitous, we take it for granted, we can read journalism

00:26:43.280 --> 00:26:47.200
[Amit Varma]: from all over the world. That was obviously not the case, then we just had the handful

00:26:47.200 --> 00:26:52.040
[Amit Varma]: of Indian newspapers and those weekly news magazines like India Today and Sunday and

00:26:52.040 --> 00:26:58.800
[Amit Varma]: all to look at. So how does one form a model of journalism when you say you when your friends

00:26:58.800 --> 00:27:03.360
[Amit Varma]: say you wanted to be a journalist before that, what was your conception of it? What excited

00:27:03.360 --> 00:27:10.440
[Amit Varma]: you about journalism per se? And as you got into it, how did your notion of journalism

00:27:10.440 --> 00:27:16.200
[Amit Varma]: evolve in a sense? Like, where do you begin to anchor yourself in terms of the values

00:27:16.200 --> 00:27:20.720
[Amit Varma]: that journalism should have? And which is an especially relevant question for me to

00:27:20.720 --> 00:27:25.440
[Amit Varma]: ask you, because when I look around the journalistic landscape today, you seem a little bit of

00:27:25.440 --> 00:27:29.480
[Amit Varma]: an outlier, which of course, I mean, entirely as a compliment.

00:27:29.480 --> 00:27:33.280
[Guest]: It's interesting that you're asking me this, because you know, the first thing I did, I

00:27:33.280 --> 00:27:37.720
[Guest]: after I landed in Delhi, because I signed a school, we had a well stocked library, not

00:27:37.720 --> 00:27:44.160
[Guest]: the greatest library. Then I came home, where the local college where I did my graduation

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:50.920
[Guest]: had a very ordinary library, very poor library. And I would buy those Malayalam magazines.

00:27:50.920 --> 00:27:55.360
[Guest]: Because my Malayalam was poor, so I re-read to improve my language. When I came to Delhi,

00:27:55.360 --> 00:27:59.680
[Guest]: the first thing that I did was my brother, who is an army officer, I asked him to take

00:27:59.680 --> 00:28:03.960
[Guest]: me to all the major libraries and we took membership in every one of them. So the American

00:28:03.960 --> 00:28:09.840
[Guest]: Center, the British Library, Saithya Academy Library, even Municipal Library in Sarojiniwar,

00:28:09.840 --> 00:28:15.440
[Guest]: and for several months before I became a full-time journalist, my job was to go to, I was just

00:28:15.440 --> 00:28:19.800
[Guest]: in and out of libraries. I would go spend days, read up, bring books, go back, you know

00:28:19.800 --> 00:28:24.400
[Guest]: what I'm saying, you know how it is to be. And I came to Delhi sometime in November,

00:28:24.400 --> 00:28:31.680
[Guest]: by the summer of next summer, I was into mid-day full-time job. Now, again, with a lot of this

00:28:31.680 --> 00:28:38.600
[Guest]: pseudo intellectual impressions and ambitions, I go into a newsroom, and my very first feature

00:28:38.600 --> 00:28:44.560
[Guest]: has this slight, you know, impresses the crowd around. And then I'm writing things about

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:52.960
[Guest]: films, I'm comparing Schindler's List and Maniratnam's Bombay, and people are appreciating.

00:28:52.960 --> 00:28:56.720
[Guest]: And one day, you know, my editor tells me, listen, there is a press conference by Madanlal

00:28:56.720 --> 00:29:00.920
[Guest]: Khurana, the Chief Minister of Delhi, go and attend it. I'm a sub-editor on the desk, I'm

00:29:00.920 --> 00:29:07.240
[Guest]: not a reporter. So I go with the reporter to attend, and he's speaking in Punjabi. I

00:29:07.240 --> 00:29:12.040
[Guest]: couldn't understand a word of it. So I came back and told the editor, sir, you know, I

00:29:12.040 --> 00:29:17.880
[Guest]: can't be a reporter in the city, I don't understand, I hardly understand Hindi and Punjabi, especially.

00:29:17.880 --> 00:29:22.640
[Guest]: So he said, precisely because you don't understand language, you should become a reporter. Because

00:29:22.640 --> 00:29:28.720
[Guest]: languages do not matter. You should be able and capable and confident to report anywhere

00:29:28.720 --> 00:29:33.520
[Guest]: in the world. You will need an interpreter at best, right? And a lot of things are said,

00:29:33.520 --> 00:29:39.040
[Guest]: and a lot of things that the most crucial observations are not based on words. And he

00:29:39.040 --> 00:29:45.840
[Guest]: pushed me into reporting. And I started reporting on the ground. And that is when I woke up

00:29:45.840 --> 00:29:54.080
[Guest]: to the reality that despite all my family's financial issues or struggles, I came from

00:29:54.080 --> 00:30:04.280
[Guest]: a very cocooned, privileged, democratic society in Kerala, where it was a stark contrast here.

00:30:04.280 --> 00:30:10.200
[Guest]: Here I was out there in hospitals where children are being stolen. I was going to police stations

00:30:10.200 --> 00:30:16.240
[Guest]: where torture is like a daily routine. I was going into government offices and getting

00:30:16.240 --> 00:30:21.880
[Guest]: these, you know, I mean, they're bargaining in front of you, the bribes, etc. The life

00:30:21.880 --> 00:30:27.280
[Guest]: was different. So, I mean, for me, the wake up happened during those days. And I abandoned

00:30:27.280 --> 00:30:31.720
[Guest]: all my intellectual pretensions. And I said, this is the India that I should report and

00:30:31.720 --> 00:30:37.640
[Guest]: write about. And I became a reporter. And I became a reporter in a very aggressive manner.

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:44.580
[Guest]: And since then, I'm very happy to say that till date, I may have not carried stories,

00:30:44.580 --> 00:30:50.760
[Guest]: but I have not dropped a story because someone could influence me. I refuse to be compromised.

00:30:50.760 --> 00:30:56.880
[Guest]: I refuse to give in to any threats, intimidations, legal cases, because it's, it makes me angry

00:30:56.880 --> 00:31:04.960
[Guest]: because we are a very rich country of too many corrupt and poor people. That's it. Sometime

00:31:04.960 --> 00:31:09.800
[Guest]: in around that time, I stopped reading fiction. I started getting into understanding what's

00:31:09.800 --> 00:31:15.960
[Guest]: here and now. And years later, as I was, later I became a defense correspondent, and I was

00:31:15.960 --> 00:31:19.560
[Guest]: bringing a lot of defense scams and stories. But then I realized that defense is a very

00:31:19.560 --> 00:31:23.640
[Guest]: small part of the society. So that's when I decided to do a master's where I could learn

00:31:23.640 --> 00:31:31.480
[Guest]: more subjects and develop more frameworks. And I'm very clear that if our voices don't

00:31:31.480 --> 00:31:36.240
[Guest]: echo and resonate here and now, it has no value in the future. I don't want to be a

00:31:36.240 --> 00:31:41.440
[Guest]: Franz Kafka. You know that I've become famous after my death with my novels. It doesn't

00:31:41.440 --> 00:31:47.640
[Guest]: matter. I want to be, I mean, I need to be doing my bit to make the society better for

00:31:47.640 --> 00:31:54.120
[Guest]: my daughter and her generation. So that's a wake up that I had in my 20s.

00:31:54.120 --> 00:31:58.480
[Amit Varma]: I was chatting with a good friend of mine who happens to be an old colleague of yours,

00:31:58.480 --> 00:32:02.520
[Amit Varma]: Prem Panikkar. So I called him this morning and I said, tell me a little bit about Josie.

00:32:02.520 --> 00:32:07.320
[Amit Varma]: And Prem was full of nothing but praise. And one of the first things he said, which struck

00:32:07.320 --> 00:32:11.920
[Amit Varma]: me was that Josie was a quintessential beat journalist. And he said that there are no

00:32:11.920 --> 00:32:16.880
[Amit Varma]: beat journalists anymore. And obviously, in those early years, your beat was security.

00:32:16.880 --> 00:32:21.280
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, the security establishment you've written about in this new book. So a couple

00:32:21.280 --> 00:32:27.640
[Amit Varma]: of questions there. One, what made you sort of choose that beat? Was it a kind of serendipity

00:32:27.640 --> 00:32:32.160
[Amit Varma]: that those are the kind of stories you started doing and you just kind of stuck with it?

00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:36.240
[Amit Varma]: And two, the other thing is that, you know, typically, you imagine a beat reporter is

00:32:36.240 --> 00:32:40.240
[Amit Varma]: someone who, you know, your editor tells you, okay, this is your beat, you're covering housing

00:32:40.240 --> 00:32:43.760
[Amit Varma]: or you're covering crime or you're covering whatever. And the beat reporter does that

00:32:43.760 --> 00:32:48.720
[Amit Varma]: till they get moved on to the next beat. But it seems to me that your commitment to your

00:32:48.720 --> 00:32:53.960
[Amit Varma]: beat also comes out of the kind of conviction that you just articulated, that it was important

00:32:53.960 --> 00:32:57.960
[Amit Varma]: to do this work, that you were animated by that also, it is not just a job, I have been

00:32:57.960 --> 00:33:04.440
[Amit Varma]: told to do this, and so on. So take me a little bit through, you know, your mindset, why this

00:33:04.440 --> 00:33:07.320
[Amit Varma]: beat? What drove you about it?

00:33:07.320 --> 00:33:14.840
[Guest]: So I'm in midday and by 95, I become a full time reporter reporting municipal issues,

00:33:14.840 --> 00:33:22.400
[Guest]: local government, whatever. And I get hired by Asian Edge, MJ Akbar hires me, Seema Musaf

00:33:22.400 --> 00:33:26.800
[Guest]: as my boss, because he's launching Delhi Edge, which is a local reporting section of the

00:33:26.800 --> 00:33:31.440
[Guest]: paper. I'm the chief reporter there. I mean, I'm like overseeing the reporting. And I'm

00:33:31.440 --> 00:33:36.700
[Guest]: doing well. And I try to do some national stories occasionally. And I broke a few stories

00:33:36.700 --> 00:33:40.320
[Guest]: in the first NDA government. I don't know if you recall, there was a proposal to make

00:33:40.320 --> 00:33:46.840
[Guest]: Sanskrit compulsory in schools. And they also wanted to teach kitchen hack habits to girls.

00:33:46.840 --> 00:33:51.880
[Guest]: So I broke all the stories. And you know, so I was taking a like, you know, I mean,

00:33:51.880 --> 00:33:56.880
[Guest]: I was doing stories. So one of those days, Admiral Vishnu Bhagat was dismissed as a Navy

00:33:56.880 --> 00:34:03.000
[Guest]: chief. And the reporting was largely controlled by the government. And that's when Akbar

00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:09.760
[Guest]: told me to start reporting on defense. And I got into, so because of that, I from day

00:34:09.760 --> 00:34:15.080
[Guest]: one, besides my science school background and my acquaintance with a lot of good officers,

00:34:15.080 --> 00:34:21.880
[Guest]: I got right into the heart of the little degeneration in the military-civilian relationship. And

00:34:21.880 --> 00:34:26.560
[Guest]: Kargil happened. So you're sucked in. So beat reporting is, you know, you can't decide these

00:34:26.560 --> 00:34:31.640
[Guest]: things. So Kargil happened. And I broke a few of the early stories about patrols going

00:34:31.640 --> 00:34:37.640
[Guest]: missing. And one day when the war is happening, I wrote about Brigadier Surendra Singh, who

00:34:37.640 --> 00:34:43.360
[Guest]: was then the brigade commander of Kargil, being removed from command. And also his boss

00:34:43.360 --> 00:34:48.680
[Guest]: being removed from command. Next day, military intelligence chief himself, MI chief himself

00:34:48.680 --> 00:34:54.240
[Guest]: writes a letter to MJ Akbar saying that, I have been fooled by an ISI module. And they've

00:34:54.240 --> 00:34:59.640
[Guest]: detected 26 ISI modules, which are trying to demoralize the military at, you know, a

00:34:59.640 --> 00:35:06.320
[Guest]: nation at war. I was immediately taken off the defense beat by my editor. And then articles

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:10.600
[Guest]: came out. Luckily, I didn't get arrested or anything. But 10 days later, I was proved

00:35:10.600 --> 00:35:14.680
[Guest]: right when army admitted that the transfer actually had happened. So I was getting into

00:35:14.680 --> 00:35:20.160
[Guest]: the defense and parallelly the intelligence apparatus, because that completes the, and

00:35:20.160 --> 00:35:24.520
[Guest]: the white collar agencies, right. So I was getting into that segment. And I was breaking

00:35:24.520 --> 00:35:29.080
[Guest]: stories and especially because I was doing stories which were anti-establishment, I got

00:35:29.080 --> 00:35:36.480
[Guest]: a lot more attention. And that's when Rediff called me. As the Kargil war entered, I left

00:35:36.480 --> 00:35:42.200
[Guest]: because I couldn't stay there because, you know, I was virtually left hanging, hung to

00:35:42.200 --> 00:35:48.680
[Guest]: dry because of a story I brought about Surendra Singh's transfer, when my editors couldn't

00:35:48.680 --> 00:35:54.000
[Guest]: stand with me. So the moment Rediff offer came, I left. I left actually, I think on

00:35:54.000 --> 00:36:01.480
[Guest]: the day of the ceasefire declaration, I left, resigned. Went to Rediff and there also, Rediff

00:36:01.480 --> 00:36:06.880
[Guest]: was those days one of the greatest journalism, I think. I haven't worked in a more idealistic

00:36:06.880 --> 00:36:12.640
[Guest]: newsroom than Rediff of those days. We had Nikhil Laxman, Prem Panicker, Sai, Sheila

00:36:12.640 --> 00:36:17.800
[Guest]: Budletter. So what happened was that because Rediff was then well funded and all that,

00:36:17.800 --> 00:36:21.720
[Guest]: you know, there was much more travel budget. And I did my own Padmashis there, you know,

00:36:21.720 --> 00:36:27.320
[Guest]: so I would go to Kashmir, stay in a rented house, go and try and interview militants,

00:36:27.320 --> 00:36:34.160
[Guest]: go to Nepal, all that. But what it did was because I was not a jingoistic guy, because

00:36:34.160 --> 00:36:39.400
[Guest]: I was not enamored by military or intelligence. And because I was not taken up by these, you

00:36:39.400 --> 00:36:45.080
[Guest]: know, crazy stories, some of these chaps would try to spin around you. I was always clear

00:36:45.080 --> 00:36:52.480
[Guest]: headed. So, you know, like, sometime I wrote something against army and the army's PRO,

00:36:52.480 --> 00:36:57.720
[Guest]: not PRO, the ADGP, the senior chap called me and said, we are going to blacklist you.

00:36:57.720 --> 00:37:02.680
[Guest]: So I said, so the liquor will be sent home. So he said, meaning what? I mean, he was a

00:37:02.680 --> 00:37:07.040
[Guest]: stiff infantry officer. I said, sir, you're putting me on some list, you said, right?

00:37:07.040 --> 00:37:13.720
[Guest]: So is it a privilege list where you send liquor home or what is it? He said, don't you understand

00:37:13.720 --> 00:37:17.720
[Guest]: I'm going to blacklist you. So I said, sir, who bothers? It's a democracy, right? You

00:37:17.720 --> 00:37:21.680
[Guest]: blacklist, brownlist, whatever you want to do it, I'll do my job. But if I'm factually

00:37:21.680 --> 00:37:25.480
[Guest]: wrong, you should tell me. I still believe that journalism, especially if you're covering

00:37:25.480 --> 00:37:32.840
[Guest]: security establishment, it cannot be for popularity. And in fact, most of the bosses in agencies

00:37:32.840 --> 00:37:38.680
[Guest]: want you to do propaganda, not journalism. And I've had repeated experience with chiefs

00:37:38.680 --> 00:37:43.200
[Guest]: of agencies, organizations who have been very fond of me. But at the most crucial moment,

00:37:43.200 --> 00:37:49.520
[Guest]: they will try to mislead you. So I have always been very clear headed about it. And mind

00:37:49.520 --> 00:37:55.920
[Guest]: you, somewhere in my mind, I'm a Gandhian, I hate violence, I hate wars. So it became

00:37:55.920 --> 00:38:02.440
[Guest]: a very contradictory life. On the one side, I did not like this idea of nation states,

00:38:02.440 --> 00:38:07.200
[Guest]: you know, guarding the borders, the security dilemmas it create for each other. On the

00:38:07.200 --> 00:38:11.960
[Guest]: other side, I was getting sucked more and more into the security apparatus of the world

00:38:11.960 --> 00:38:17.880
[Guest]: of the country and the region. This went on. And I was in, then I, from Rediff I went back

00:38:17.880 --> 00:38:22.800
[Guest]: to Times, Times of India, then I came back to launch DNA with Ayyaz Mehman and Pradeep

00:38:22.800 --> 00:38:29.240
[Guest]: Go and all that. It was while in DNA that I decided that enough of writing about defense

00:38:29.240 --> 00:38:34.480
[Guest]: and intelligence alone, I need to understand India better. And I decided to do a part time

00:38:34.480 --> 00:38:41.220
[Guest]: master's where I went on to study 12-13 subjects from economics to international trade and

00:38:41.220 --> 00:38:45.720
[Guest]: policy to negotiations, etc. That is when I, when I was called back by Times of India,

00:38:45.720 --> 00:38:50.200
[Guest]: Jojo asked me to come back to Times of India. I told him that I don't want to be a defense

00:38:50.200 --> 00:38:54.600
[Guest]: reporter. I don't want to waste, I can. So I became editor of special projects doing

00:38:54.600 --> 00:38:59.600
[Guest]: only special investigative stories. And Jojo gave me a free hand for some, a lot of, I

00:38:59.600 --> 00:39:04.120
[Guest]: mean, I had a lot of free hand in Times for a long time. So my investigations expanded.

00:39:04.120 --> 00:39:10.600
[Guest]: But at the same time, I continued to do stories on the intelligence, defense, security establishment.

00:39:10.600 --> 00:39:14.640
[Amit Varma]: One of the interesting strands that you've spoken about in your book is how the security

00:39:14.640 --> 00:39:18.840
[Amit Varma]: establishment tries to control the narrative. And you've spoken about how, in fact, they

00:39:18.840 --> 00:39:22.400
[Amit Varma]: tried to co-opt you at different points in time. They said they'll pay for your master's

00:39:22.400 --> 00:39:27.280
[Amit Varma]: when you go abroad and so on. And you, of course, refused because, hey, Sanik school

00:39:27.280 --> 00:39:33.560
[Amit Varma]: values. But my question here is that then when you get into that beat, obviously, the

00:39:33.560 --> 00:39:37.920
[Amit Varma]: key commodity, which is important for you is information. And you get information from

00:39:37.920 --> 00:39:43.120
[Amit Varma]: sources. And yet, if many of your sources are insiders within the establishment, when

00:39:43.120 --> 00:39:48.040
[Amit Varma]: they know that you are not someone who will swallow the narrative necessarily, you know,

00:39:48.040 --> 00:39:52.720
[Amit Varma]: and when it may not be in their interest for to speak to you, how do you go about cultivating

00:39:52.720 --> 00:39:57.280
[Amit Varma]: sources and given that so much is smoke and mirrors, you don't know whether a single thing

00:39:57.280 --> 00:40:02.120
[Amit Varma]: that is being told to you is necessarily true. And it must be at some point in time hard

00:40:02.120 --> 00:40:07.560
[Amit Varma]: to corroborate things which are being told to you. So how did you navigate all of that?

00:40:07.560 --> 00:40:11.400
[Amit Varma]: Like, were there times where you think you made a mistake that you'd followed a certain

00:40:11.400 --> 00:40:15.600
[Amit Varma]: narrative or whatever, and it wasn't the case? And also over a period of time, how do you

00:40:15.600 --> 00:40:20.320
[Amit Varma]: build your you know, your bullshit detection radar as it were, and this cultivation of

00:40:20.320 --> 00:40:24.800
[Amit Varma]: sources especially in a field like this? How does it happen? Because you know, being a

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:29.560
[Amit Varma]: cricket journalist for a while, and it's worse today, it was better than but if you got to

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:34.400
[Amit Varma]: a critical of cricketers, you would just lose access, or the BCCI would just drop access

00:40:34.400 --> 00:40:38.600
[Amit Varma]: if you messed with them, which was always fine for me, because I was more of big picture

00:40:38.600 --> 00:40:42.800
[Amit Varma]: kind of guy, I didn't do so much reporting, and I didn't really care about the access.

00:40:42.800 --> 00:40:46.680
[Amit Varma]: But for those who actually have to write about what's going on inside the dressing room,

00:40:46.680 --> 00:40:52.640
[Amit Varma]: I can't imagine getting that information without access. So take me through the life of a beat

00:40:52.640 --> 00:40:56.720
[Amit Varma]: journalist in that regard, and so on and so forth.

00:40:56.720 --> 00:41:02.360
[Guest]: Yeah, so I mean, that's where I want to go back to that, the rent seeking behavior we

00:41:02.360 --> 00:41:07.280
[Guest]: said, so there are, there are great Indians, there are great people out there in every

00:41:07.280 --> 00:41:12.320
[Guest]: agency, every organization, they may not be the most famous. But if you get to the right

00:41:12.320 --> 00:41:18.080
[Guest]: people, you don't need too many sources, I don't need 100 sources to scoop the stories,

00:41:18.080 --> 00:41:23.520
[Guest]: I only need five of them, right? They need to trust you. And they should have the courage

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:29.080
[Guest]: to tell you the truth and reach out to you, right? So everything else is smoke and screen,

00:41:29.080 --> 00:41:35.280
[Guest]: everything else is bullshit. So I would be spending an entire day with people who are

00:41:35.280 --> 00:41:39.440
[Guest]: trying to mislead me. But I won't take a word from I'll go back. So if something doesn't

00:41:39.440 --> 00:41:45.920
[Guest]: appear to my common sense, I usually drop it. I got my own criterias about accepting

00:41:45.920 --> 00:41:49.880
[Guest]: information, accessing documents, etc, which I've developed over the years, which is not

00:41:49.880 --> 00:41:54.640
[Guest]: foolproof. But I think many of it works. For example, if somebody were to give you a document,

00:41:54.640 --> 00:42:01.200
[Guest]: and that person is not the first, the primary source handling the document, I will not use

00:42:01.200 --> 00:42:07.560
[Guest]: it unless I can verify it. So if you give me a file, and if you are handling that file,

00:42:07.560 --> 00:42:13.120
[Guest]: I will trust you, my trust on you will be much higher. But if you are not handling the

00:42:13.120 --> 00:42:16.960
[Guest]: file, you are giving somebody else's file to me, I would not use it unless I can verify

00:42:16.960 --> 00:42:21.800
[Guest]: it. But a lot of reporters run with files sensitive, especially if it's interesting.

00:42:21.800 --> 00:42:26.600
[Guest]: So in all agencies, there are great human beings out there, fantastic people, courageous

00:42:26.600 --> 00:42:30.440
[Guest]: people, people who are more courageous than all of us, at least people like you and me

00:42:30.440 --> 00:42:36.720
[Guest]: get recognition, right? We sell books, people make movies on us. People listen to us. But

00:42:36.720 --> 00:42:41.680
[Guest]: those are our real heroes, the ones in the organization. So quietly sit there. And when

00:42:41.680 --> 00:42:46.120
[Guest]: they see something going wrong, they would reach out to people like me and tell us that,

00:42:46.120 --> 00:42:52.440
[Guest]: listen, this is what's happening, you need to write about it. That loose network of whistleblowers

00:42:52.440 --> 00:42:58.280
[Guest]: in many ways, who are around me are enabling me to do this work. So I'm not a James Bond

00:42:58.280 --> 00:43:04.280
[Guest]: or anything. These people provide information. That's one part. The second part, which is

00:43:04.280 --> 00:43:10.120
[Guest]: to me very interesting is in the agencies, there are various kinds of people. Then the

00:43:10.120 --> 00:43:16.840
[Guest]: second kind of one, I told you, these courageous ones are the foundations for great journalism.

00:43:16.840 --> 00:43:22.760
[Guest]: Second are the kind of people who are careerists, who will bribe journalists, whatever they

00:43:22.760 --> 00:43:26.840
[Guest]: want. But many of them have a good quality, which is that once they know that you are

00:43:26.840 --> 00:43:33.040
[Guest]: not a bullshitter and you should not be bullshitted around, they usually withdraw. They will give

00:43:33.040 --> 00:43:38.260
[Guest]: you a respect and space, but they may not entertain you too much. But if you ask a question,

00:43:38.260 --> 00:43:42.720
[Guest]: they will not go quiet. They know that this fellow has to be answered to, even if you

00:43:42.720 --> 00:43:50.240
[Guest]: don't tell the truth. There is a third kind, which is the, you can't do anything to them.

00:43:50.240 --> 00:43:55.400
[Guest]: They are in their fantasy world, they'll bribe, kick, whatever shit. So you just ignore them.

00:43:55.400 --> 00:44:01.160
[Guest]: So there are people, I don't want to take names, who have held very, very powerful positions

00:44:01.160 --> 00:44:07.560
[Guest]: in this country, who have wanted to meet me, they refuse to meet them. Very powerful people.

00:44:07.560 --> 00:44:13.360
[Guest]: I said, no, I know he wants to meet me because he wants to plant some information and use

00:44:13.360 --> 00:44:18.400
[Guest]: my byline to bring credibility to him. I'm not going to, my byline is not on rent. It's

00:44:18.400 --> 00:44:24.320
[Guest]: not on sale for you. I know very clearly. So I refuse to meet some people. The consequences

00:44:24.320 --> 00:44:28.440
[Guest]: are there, you pay for it, but that's okay. So between these three, I think my life has

00:44:28.440 --> 00:44:34.560
[Guest]: been very good. I've been able to do enough stories to get attention from people like

00:44:34.560 --> 00:44:41.480
[Amit Varma]: you. So yeah, get attention from people like me. You're pushing it now. And I hope people

00:44:41.480 --> 00:44:45.160
[Amit Varma]: make films on your life, but nobody's going to make a film on mine. So you know, in your

00:44:45.160 --> 00:44:49.080
[Amit Varma]: book, you mentioned the carrot, which we've just spoken about, that they tried to co-opt

00:44:49.080 --> 00:44:53.720
[Amit Varma]: you, and you know, somebody spoke to you about a monthly retainer, and to fund your studies

00:44:53.720 --> 00:44:58.040
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. What about the stick, which is not something that you mentioned in this

00:44:58.040 --> 00:45:03.480
[Amit Varma]: book, and which I assume must be there, because one of the things that struck me while reading

00:45:03.480 --> 00:45:10.720
[Amit Varma]: this book was the way that you speak of people who are still extremely, you know, prominent

00:45:10.720 --> 00:45:16.120
[Amit Varma]: today in the police in Delhi, for example, who's active in Gujarat under Mr. Modi, you

00:45:16.120 --> 00:45:20.320
[Amit Varma]: know, and even people like Amit Shah, for example, I mean, these are incredibly powerful

00:45:20.320 --> 00:45:25.800
[Amit Varma]: people, you have not put any filters out there, you're basically just laying it out all out

00:45:25.800 --> 00:45:30.840
[Amit Varma]: on the page for everyone to read, of course, and for your last book, you were sued for

00:45:30.840 --> 00:45:37.080
[Amit Varma]: enormous amounts of money, which you cannot possibly possess with your sanic school values.

00:45:37.080 --> 00:45:41.480
[Amit Varma]: So tell me a little bit about how you then deal with the stick, you know, and I imagine

00:45:41.480 --> 00:45:46.240
[Amit Varma]: that when you're single is probably easier, but when you have a family, two practical

00:45:46.240 --> 00:45:52.400
[Amit Varma]: considerations, then come into mind, how does that kind of work? I'm presuming you must

00:45:52.400 --> 00:45:55.800
[Amit Varma]: have been threatened, there must have been intimidation, take me through that.

00:45:55.800 --> 00:46:01.000
[Guest]: So that this is where the script goes off the track. Because you ask a question like

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:06.720
[Guest]: this to a journalist, and then he becomes a hero of the story. Then he said, then he

00:46:06.720 --> 00:46:12.680
[Guest]: said boasting, you know, and I keep saying this to people that, you know, if the reporter

00:46:12.680 --> 00:46:16.360
[Guest]: tries to be the hero of the story, you will end up being one story wonder.

00:46:16.360 --> 00:46:20.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but you know something, you're not writing this story. This is my story. If I want to

00:46:20.040 --> 00:46:23.640
[Guest]: make you the hero, I'll make you the hero.

00:46:23.640 --> 00:46:27.720
[Guest]: So you know, there are some ground I'll tell you. So other day, you know, last week morning

00:46:27.720 --> 00:46:31.480
[Guest]: context, some reporter called me and was talking about surveillance. He was doing an article.

00:46:31.480 --> 00:46:37.400
[Guest]: So he asked me, sir, how did you take protection? So I passingly told him an anecdote from my

00:46:37.400 --> 00:46:43.240
[Guest]: life, which then I can see so many people are sharing, which was about, you know, like,

00:46:43.240 --> 00:46:48.560
[Guest]: so I've been I mean, ever since I've been a reporter, I've been aware that for most

00:46:48.560 --> 00:46:53.280
[Guest]: part of my career, I've been trailed by some agency or the other. So once I broke Naval

00:46:53.280 --> 00:46:56.920
[Guest]: War Room leak case in DNA and I was being trailed by the Naval Intelligence people,

00:46:56.920 --> 00:47:01.480
[Guest]: I think, or IB. So, you know, every day I would drive back in the evening and routine

00:47:01.480 --> 00:47:07.840
[Guest]: I'll come in, park my car inside. And there is a Maruti van, which used to follow me.

00:47:07.840 --> 00:47:12.000
[Guest]: And they will be parked outside the apartment complex. And I detected it. And after two

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:16.920
[Guest]: days, I told my wife, you know, we'll so she's also a journalist, Priya is, you know, we

00:47:16.920 --> 00:47:22.080
[Guest]: are for this. So it was easy to talk to her about this thing. And my daughter Supriya

00:47:22.080 --> 00:47:27.040
[Guest]: was very small. So we started switching off the light early in our apartment. So the moment

00:47:27.040 --> 00:47:32.400
[Guest]: you switch off the light, they are babus, they go back, right? There are no James Bonds

00:47:32.400 --> 00:47:37.320
[Guest]: in this country. Let's be honest, if somebody pretends to be James Bond, he's bullshitting.

00:47:37.320 --> 00:47:43.000
[Guest]: There are people who are doing professional work, good work, but no James Bonds. So they

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:45.840
[Guest]: would go back and then I would come out and take my car and go and meet my source and

00:47:45.840 --> 00:47:53.800
[Guest]: come back. So from that to being served with dozens of defamation notice and parliamentary

00:47:53.800 --> 00:47:58.240
[Guest]: privilege notice and this and that, one goes through it and also nobody has come and beaten

00:47:58.240 --> 00:48:05.040
[Guest]: me up. But very in a sweet way of threatening, very nicely you get threatened. But to me,

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:12.600
[Guest]: the most bizarre fact, not bizarre, most interesting aspect is when you talk loudly in the public

00:48:12.600 --> 00:48:20.800
[Guest]: square like me, many of them actually either try to ignore you or try to co-opt you. Meaning

00:48:20.800 --> 00:48:26.120
[Guest]: the rewards available to you not to speak the next time are very positive. Huge money,

00:48:26.120 --> 00:48:31.400
[Guest]: huge favors, etc. That's what I would say. But then there is also a larger reality. Amit,

00:48:31.400 --> 00:48:37.560
[Guest]: you know, in India, in a year, one and a half lakh people die on our roads. How many journalists

00:48:37.560 --> 00:48:44.920
[Guest]: die on the line of duty? So I think being a journalist is far safer than being on the

00:48:44.920 --> 00:48:51.640
[Guest]: Indian road. So we have to find solace really from such statistics, which may be absurd

00:48:51.640 --> 00:48:55.320
[Guest]: comparisons. Yeah, but on a serious note, Amit, if you are writing, if you are somebody

00:48:55.320 --> 00:48:59.800
[Guest]: who is committed to writing about the here and now of the society and what's happening

00:48:59.800 --> 00:49:04.520
[Guest]: around, then between your fingertips and the keyboard, you cannot have prejudices. You

00:49:04.520 --> 00:49:09.320
[Guest]: cannot speculate what my words might mean and what it can bring to me. You will have

00:49:09.320 --> 00:49:12.760
[Guest]: to write with the courage, you will have to write with the awareness that you are going

00:49:12.760 --> 00:49:17.400
[Guest]: to be lonely. Not very many people are going to defend you. And the process itself can

00:49:17.400 --> 00:49:22.760
[Guest]: be the punishment, which could begin any moment. And I write with that awareness, but I don't

00:49:22.760 --> 00:49:27.560
[Amit Varma]: write with censorship as you must have noticed. You mentioned that people threatened you in

00:49:27.560 --> 00:49:34.280
[Amit Varma]: a nice way. So what would a nice way of threatening somebody be? Can you give me an example?

00:49:34.280 --> 00:49:40.040
[Guest]: See in a city like Delhi, everyone knows everyone around. So when you are trying to do something

00:49:40.040 --> 00:49:46.600
[Guest]: on Mr. X, Mr. Y, who might be a lawyer or some fixer, we'll meet you for a coffee and

00:49:46.600 --> 00:49:51.880
[Guest]: say that, look, I heard you are doing something on so and so. Why do you want to do it? He

00:49:51.880 --> 00:49:59.320
[Guest]: is a rascal, badmash. Do you want me to talk to him? Why don't you meet him? So it's that

00:49:59.320 --> 00:50:04.760
[Guest]: way. It's threat combined with the other thing. The other is that some people actually do

00:50:04.760 --> 00:50:11.400
[Guest]: fixing at the other end. When they know that I am working on something, which is something

00:50:11.400 --> 00:50:16.280
[Guest]: very strange I've realized, they would do setting at the other end and come to you and

00:50:16.280 --> 00:50:20.600
[Guest]: say that, look, I know that you are doing something on so and so. We've got a budget.

00:50:20.600 --> 00:50:28.040
[Guest]: Why don't we just split it? Then there are people who make money out of you and showing

00:50:28.040 --> 00:50:31.640
[Guest]: their proximity to you and they will tell somebody, look, I'll ensure that he doesn't

00:50:31.640 --> 00:50:37.640
[Guest]: write against you. So one day somebody got drunk and from his mouth it came out. He told

00:50:37.640 --> 00:50:41.640
[Guest]: somebody, he boasted saying that, you know, Josie will never write against me. And his

00:50:41.640 --> 00:50:45.560
[Guest]: drinking companion came and told me, I said, why? Because he said, oh, he said you are

00:50:45.560 --> 00:50:51.640
[Guest]: being managed. So it operates at multiple layers, multiple levels, because of which

00:50:51.640 --> 00:50:54.760
[Guest]: one thing I don't do is I don't go drinking with people. I don't even go to press club

00:50:54.760 --> 00:50:59.000
[Guest]: to drink. If I don't want to drink, I drink at home, you know, I avoid those companies,

00:50:59.640 --> 00:51:04.600
[Guest]: because you will never know in a political city like Delhi who is on to what game. So

00:51:04.600 --> 00:51:09.880
[Guest]: when I say sweet threats, it can be any of this. That's so fascinating. So now I know

00:51:09.880 --> 00:51:15.640
[Amit Varma]: that there's a managing Josie Joseph economy out there for scammers. So prominent people

00:51:15.640 --> 00:51:20.040
[Amit Varma]: in India will be getting emails not from Nigerian fraudsters, but from people saying, hey, we'll

00:51:20.040 --> 00:51:25.080
[Amit Varma]: manage Josie is on your case, but we'll manage him. You may not even know who they are. Tell

00:51:25.080 --> 00:51:31.640
[Amit Varma]: me also then about what are the kind of knowledge management systems that you have gathered

00:51:31.640 --> 00:51:38.280
[Amit Varma]: over the years in terms of just managing all the knowledge that you're taking in. And especially

00:51:38.280 --> 00:51:42.600
[Amit Varma]: as we get older, and we're pretty much the same age, I realized that my memory kind of

00:51:42.600 --> 00:51:47.320
[Amit Varma]: is very unreliable. And, you know, something I might have read two weeks ago, I would completely

00:51:47.320 --> 00:51:52.120
[Amit Varma]: have forgotten even having read it. And, you know, for Feast of Vultures, you mentioned

00:51:52.120 --> 00:51:58.200
[Amit Varma]: earlier in an interview elsewhere that you had some 1500 documents or 15,000 documents, which,

00:51:58.200 --> 00:52:03.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, you got for that. So what are the kind of knowledge management systems you used to use?

00:52:03.160 --> 00:52:09.240
[Amit Varma]: And what do you do now in terms of putting your research together, putting your thoughts together?

00:52:09.240 --> 00:52:14.680
[Amit Varma]: How has that workflow evolved in a sense? So I've always been fond of documents.

00:52:14.680 --> 00:52:22.280
[Guest]: So I used to store a lot of documents, but ever since digitization happened, you will see

00:52:23.400 --> 00:52:27.160
[Guest]: hard disk lying around here and there, which I keep updating my computers. I got

00:52:27.960 --> 00:52:36.040
[Guest]: Google, iCloud backups, etc. So the standard, the same. I email myself a lot of things.

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:43.720
[Guest]: I do keep notebooks. And for various things, because, as you said, you know, like, for example,

00:52:45.320 --> 00:52:51.880
[Guest]: this notebook is about what I should do. This notebook is about some stories I'm working on.

00:52:52.440 --> 00:52:56.680
[Guest]: There is a book in my bag, which is when I take notes for meetings. So not, it's not perfect.

00:52:57.640 --> 00:53:02.040
[Guest]: And it keeps changing. So sometimes I start my day making notes about what to be done today and

00:53:02.040 --> 00:53:07.640
[Guest]: start psyching off. Sometimes I don't do it. That's one part of managing my thought process.

00:53:08.520 --> 00:53:14.680
[Guest]: The second, and which is, I think, what has really worked for me in terms of output, is my time

00:53:14.680 --> 00:53:19.560
[Guest]: management, where it also flows into what you said about knowledge management, which is that in the

00:53:19.560 --> 00:53:27.000
[Guest]: morning, I get up by 6.15, I'm up. And I'm very disciplined in that sense. Till about nine o'clock,

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:31.800
[Guest]: I don't like anyone disturbing, I don't pick up my phone. And I'm not really bothered by

00:53:31.800 --> 00:53:38.600
[Guest]: it. That's when I actually sit in front of my laptop. I'm reading or writing, either reading

00:53:38.600 --> 00:53:43.080
[Guest]: something for the book I'm writing or I'm typing my book. Nothing else. I do nothing else. I might

00:53:43.080 --> 00:53:48.520
[Guest]: look at the Guardian, Indian Express and New York Times to let you know what's happening around.

00:53:48.520 --> 00:53:52.760
[Guest]: I don't even look at Twitter or anything because that helps me to. So every morning when I'm,

00:53:52.760 --> 00:53:57.800
[Guest]: when I'm, when I start my day, I'm very sorted in my mind about what I'm looking for, what I'm

00:53:57.800 --> 00:54:04.520
[Guest]: reading. And if I don't find something, I mail my colleagues, etc. The other thing is, I organize

00:54:04.520 --> 00:54:11.080
[Guest]: my backend because a lot of the stories that I'm pursuing are in gestation for years.

00:54:13.720 --> 00:54:18.760
[Guest]: Because as soon as I get it organized, I put a folder name and it goes in there. But I have a

00:54:18.760 --> 00:54:27.400
[Guest]: fairly good sense of, so if you, if I want to know about, let's say something, let's call it

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:32.280
[Guest]: 2G scam. I can pull it out quickly. I just need to research. I know the keywords. So it's stored

00:54:32.280 --> 00:54:38.120
[Guest]: here and there. I got some backups. Now it's all on cloud and all that. That's how I manage. I

00:54:38.120 --> 00:54:45.560
[Guest]: don't, there is no other rocket science beyond it. As far as books are concerned, one bad thing

00:54:45.560 --> 00:54:52.520
[Guest]: is that I do, I find it, I struggle to recall names of even writers, but some books which

00:54:52.520 --> 00:55:00.200
[Guest]: are stuck with me or which really impressed me, those I can recall, not to the page, but I would

00:55:00.200 --> 00:55:05.160
[Guest]: know where is that reference in which chapter. That's a practice. You know how we all, there are

00:55:05.160 --> 00:55:12.680
[Guest]: certain books that remains with you. The third thing is that I also tend to speed read because

00:55:12.680 --> 00:55:17.800
[Guest]: if one doesn't have the time and the luxury to read everything, like these days I'm reading

00:55:17.800 --> 00:55:22.600
[Guest]: transfer of power papers, massive volumes, right? But I speed read. I know I'm looking for a so and

00:55:22.600 --> 00:55:28.200
[Guest]: so date and then I spend time there. So it's each one of us develop our own strategies. I'm sure you

00:55:28.200 --> 00:55:32.600
[Guest]: have, I can see the way you have kept book behind you and the way I have arranged book behind you

00:55:32.600 --> 00:55:39.400
[Guest]: are very different. And it might also tell about the reading habits of others. Beyond that, I do

00:55:39.400 --> 00:55:45.080
[Guest]: take some security precautions. So I don't just save my passwords anywhere and everywhere anymore.

00:55:45.080 --> 00:55:51.320
[Guest]: I just ensure some encryption, et cetera, et cetera. I've just moved into a new house. So what

00:55:51.320 --> 00:55:55.480
[Amit Varma]: you're seeing besides me is a bunch of unopened cartons with some books piled on top of them,

00:55:55.480 --> 00:56:00.120
[Amit Varma]: but that's not how I keep my books. I also have bookshelves like you do, but I also have

00:56:00.120 --> 00:56:05.400
[Amit Varma]: a massive amount of mess normally, but not the kind that you're looking at right now. So you

00:56:05.400 --> 00:56:11.160
[Amit Varma]: spoke about sort of books that have tended to stay with you. My next question before we take a break

00:56:11.160 --> 00:56:18.040
[Amit Varma]: and go on to then talk about your latest book is what are the kind of sort of nonfiction books or

00:56:18.040 --> 00:56:24.360
[Amit Varma]: writers that you've admired or learned from given the kind of stuff that you are writing? Like your

00:56:24.360 --> 00:56:29.880
[Amit Varma]: books have been these investigative books of nonfiction, but also they feature very fine

00:56:29.880 --> 00:56:35.960
[Amit Varma]: storytelling use of novelistic techniques. So what are the kind of books that you admired when

00:56:35.960 --> 00:56:41.320
[Amit Varma]: you read them and you took as models and are there writers who influenced you where, you know,

00:56:41.320 --> 00:56:44.680
[Amit Varma]: you looked at a particular writer and you said, yeah, yeah, that's the kind of work I want to do.

00:56:45.640 --> 00:56:53.000
[Guest]: Since the last 20, 30 years, as you know, nonfiction writing has really boomed and scaled

00:56:53.000 --> 00:57:01.560
[Guest]: up qualitatively. But even then a book like this, it's called the Bear Trap, Afghanistan's Untold

00:57:01.560 --> 00:57:10.920
[Guest]: Story. This was written by a former ISI colonel and Mark Atkin in the 80s. I mean, this is courage.

00:57:12.200 --> 00:57:18.440
[Guest]: They're detailing how ISI ran the Afghan operations. So to me, this is also an inspirational

00:57:18.440 --> 00:57:25.240
[Guest]: book to what people like James Wright, Twin Towers, etc. write. So there are all of them,

00:57:25.240 --> 00:57:30.600
[Guest]: but I don't, I don't, I don't, I'm not the kind who has an inspirational figure or someone I look

00:57:30.600 --> 00:57:36.520
[Guest]: up to. But yeah, when I was writing my first book, A Feast of Vultures, my prologue is set in a

00:57:36.520 --> 00:57:42.760
[Guest]: village in Bihar and they're struggling to get road and hospital, etc. Some people have noticed

00:57:42.760 --> 00:57:51.080
[Guest]: that I've tried to use some of the magical realism techniques that Marques popularized in that. So I

00:57:51.080 --> 00:57:55.080
[Guest]: love the way, you know, when Marques, Marques will never tell you, I'm going to tell you magic.

00:57:55.080 --> 00:57:59.320
[Guest]: You'll just tell the magic, right? So little, little things like that. But, you know, I grew

00:57:59.320 --> 00:58:05.080
[Guest]: up on Aldous Huxley and George Orwell and all that. So you'll find a lot of my sentences are

00:58:05.080 --> 00:58:09.880
[Guest]: very pithy. I don't know if you'll find it, some wicked sense of humor you'll find here and there.

00:58:09.880 --> 00:58:15.320
[Guest]: So all that is inspired from those writers. Because if you, if you recall those, the Orwellian

00:58:15.320 --> 00:58:21.000
[Guest]: English or the Huxley's writing and all that is very matter of fact to the world. So because

00:58:21.640 --> 00:58:28.040
[Guest]: that shaped my thinking from very early days as a student, that I as a writer, I have a

00:58:28.040 --> 00:58:35.960
[Guest]: responsibility towards you, which is you as a reader, which is to ensure that you are not forced

00:58:35.960 --> 00:58:42.280
[Guest]: to take a dictionary in your hand while you read me. The reading has to be an activity between you

00:58:42.280 --> 00:58:49.080
[Guest]: and me and my pages, not between you, a dictionary or a Google and me, and then the game is over.

00:58:49.960 --> 00:58:56.760
[Guest]: So find the appropriate words, but not the difficult words is a big, big challenge for me,

00:58:56.760 --> 00:59:02.920
[Guest]: because I'm very insecure and unsure of my language skills, even today. So I read, I sometimes

00:59:02.920 --> 00:59:08.920
[Guest]: write, rewrite sentences, but yes, you will never find unusually long draft sentences,

00:59:08.920 --> 00:59:14.760
[Guest]: you will not find unwieldy adjectives and adverbs in my writings. So those have been shaped by,

00:59:15.400 --> 00:59:19.000
[Guest]: you know, I told you when I was in the signing school, I had this great English teacher called

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:26.680
[Guest]: Prem C. Nair, who came from Oxford, British educator. People like him taught us, there was another

00:59:26.680 --> 00:59:31.960
[Guest]: teacher called N. Balasundar Nair. These people, because I come from Malayalam mediums, I learned

00:59:31.960 --> 00:59:40.760
[Guest]: English from them. And one of the things that I learned was to use bare minimum words to tell

00:59:40.760 --> 00:59:45.480
[Guest]: something. And I think that's the greatest way to connect with the reader. So, and it's a very

00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:50.200
[Guest]: deliberate thing I do, because there was a time if you read what I used to write early in my 20s,

00:59:50.200 --> 00:59:54.600
[Guest]: and I used to write with this flurry language, like a lot of mallus, and you will never figure

00:59:54.600 --> 00:59:59.560
[Guest]: out what they're writing, you know, take names, but even if I repeat some sentence, you'll figure

00:59:59.560 --> 01:00:04.440
[Guest]: out who I'm talking about. There are many of them like that. Yeah, so I have been very conscious,

01:00:04.440 --> 01:00:08.760
[Amit Varma]: if I can cut out an adjective, I would. This is brilliant. And you mentioned Orwell,

01:00:08.760 --> 01:00:12.920
[Amit Varma]: and obviously Orwell in terms of prose is my absolute hero. But it's interesting that you

01:00:12.920 --> 01:00:16.600
[Amit Varma]: mentioned Orwell, because while reading your book, and by the way, I can't believe that you have

01:00:16.600 --> 01:00:20.680
[Amit Varma]: doubts about your own language, like you just said, because it's such a bloody well written

01:00:20.680 --> 01:00:25.480
[Amit Varma]: book. But while reading your book, I was reminded of this quote that I keep sharing with my writing

01:00:25.480 --> 01:00:30.040
[Amit Varma]: class, which is, you know, Orwell's quote, good prose is like a windowpane, where his whole point

01:00:30.040 --> 01:00:34.200
[Amit Varma]: was that prose like a windowpane is a means to an end, you know, a windowpane is supposed to show

01:00:34.200 --> 01:00:38.920
[Amit Varma]: you what's on the other side, and the prose should be equally invisible, you don't notice it at all,

01:00:38.920 --> 01:00:45.080
[Amit Varma]: you just go with it, where it is going. The other point that also struck me just now is, you know,

01:00:45.080 --> 01:00:50.200
[Amit Varma]: when you speak of coming from a Mallu medium school, and then learning English and all and

01:00:50.200 --> 01:00:54.760
[Amit Varma]: I wonder if in some ways that might be an advantage, because what that forces you to do

01:00:54.760 --> 01:01:00.440
[Amit Varma]: is to pay deeper attention in a more granular way to the intricacies of language to the words that

01:01:00.440 --> 01:01:04.920
[Amit Varma]: you choose to the way that you use grammar, like, you know, I remember one of my writing students

01:01:04.920 --> 01:01:09.480
[Amit Varma]: for the online course I teach once asked me about how you know, her first language was in English,

01:01:09.480 --> 01:01:14.040
[Amit Varma]: and you know, how does one do it? Should one write in English? And I pointed her to this

01:01:14.040 --> 01:01:18.760
[Amit Varma]: great interview of Jhumpa Lahiri in Tyler Cowen's podcast conversations with Tyler,

01:01:18.760 --> 01:01:22.360
[Amit Varma]: and Jhumpa of course, learned Italian and has just written a book in Italian.

01:01:22.360 --> 01:01:26.200
[Amit Varma]: And through what Jhumpa said in that interview, I discovered this incredible

01:01:26.200 --> 01:01:31.240
[Amit Varma]: writer I recommend to all my listeners, called Agatha Christophe, I think Hungarian,

01:01:31.240 --> 01:01:37.240
[Amit Varma]: but moved to France when she was 21, learned French from scratch, and wrote this incredible

01:01:37.240 --> 01:01:42.120
[Amit Varma]: series of books called the Notebook Trilogy. The language there is incredible. It's very spare,

01:01:42.120 --> 01:01:46.520
[Amit Varma]: very sparse, very powerful, you know, and I'm reading her in translation, of course,

01:01:46.520 --> 01:01:54.280
[Amit Varma]: but you still get a sense of what it is. So do you feel that that also made a difference perhaps,

01:01:54.280 --> 01:01:58.840
[Amit Varma]: in your early attempts to be more florid than one would otherwise be because you might also

01:01:58.840 --> 01:02:03.720
[Amit Varma]: be trying to convince yourself that hey, I can do this language. And you know, does that change

01:02:03.720 --> 01:02:09.560
[Guest]: later? No, no, you're so right, you know, because I think, when I started writing English,

01:02:10.120 --> 01:02:15.880
[Guest]: I was writing to impress others, and impress myself, not impress myself to give myself

01:02:15.880 --> 01:02:24.440
[Guest]: confidence. But I was writing absolute trash. But as I progressed, and my own sense of language

01:02:24.440 --> 01:02:31.960
[Guest]: moved from being the curtain to the windowpane that you're talking about, right? I wanted to be

01:02:31.960 --> 01:02:38.920
[Guest]: that. And that's where I dropped this entire, so my own writing has changed. And in fact,

01:02:38.920 --> 01:02:46.680
[Guest]: my agent Kanishka that they were telling me that probably, the Silent Coup is a far faster paced

01:02:46.680 --> 01:02:51.320
[Guest]: pithy writing than even Feast of Vultures. Even Ajitha, my editor was telling me that.

01:02:51.320 --> 01:02:56.760
[Guest]: It could well be true, because in the first book, I'm also making this entire effort to

01:02:57.320 --> 01:03:01.080
[Guest]: explain everything to the audience. Because I'm also trying to explain to myself,

01:03:01.080 --> 01:03:05.640
[Guest]: you know what I'm saying? When a writer is writing something, he's writing it for the reader,

01:03:05.640 --> 01:03:11.960
[Guest]: and also for himself. But with the new book, I am more confident, I know my audience, because

01:03:11.960 --> 01:03:17.000
[Guest]: I give them more respect, and I give myself more respect. So it's a process. So I think

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:21.640
[Guest]: language keeps changing. My writing in the next book might be something else. But probably,

01:03:21.640 --> 01:03:27.640
[Guest]: as you said, I was, I grew up in Malayalam. And then I shifted to English. And now I think I even

01:03:27.640 --> 01:03:33.080
[Guest]: think in English. Now I not struggle, I find it very difficult to communicate complex ideas in

01:03:33.080 --> 01:03:39.240
[Guest]: Malayalam to people. Whereas I'm very comfortable talking Malayalam with my parents, my siblings.

01:03:39.240 --> 01:03:43.320
[Guest]: But even when I think in English and write in English, I think at somewhere in the back of

01:03:43.320 --> 01:03:50.760
[Guest]: your mind, your sense of language is so rooted in your native sensibilities. I'll tell you,

01:03:50.760 --> 01:03:57.000
[Guest]: for example, something that MS Madhavan recently pointed out, which struck me very big time,

01:03:57.560 --> 01:04:02.120
[Guest]: was that rain is so much part of the Malayali life. But rain doesn't have too many adjectives

01:04:02.120 --> 01:04:07.640
[Guest]: in Malayalam. There's only one or two words for Malayalam. There are very few words about rain,

01:04:07.640 --> 01:04:14.280
[Guest]: because it's so part of us. So if you look at my book, I think if you break down the book,

01:04:14.280 --> 01:04:18.840
[Guest]: my book, it may be just a few thousand words, meaning I'm repeating a few thousand words,

01:04:18.840 --> 01:04:24.920
[Guest]: nothing more. I'm not, I will not introduce an adjective that I know there. I will not.

01:04:24.920 --> 01:04:29.160
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, it's a very, very interesting conversation. I'm not, I'm not such a literary

01:04:29.160 --> 01:04:38.520
[Guest]: accomplished guy, but I think language for me is the means to tell a story. And I'm telling

01:04:38.520 --> 01:04:44.440
[Guest]: you a story or many stories because I have an argument to make. So it goes to that way.

01:04:45.480 --> 01:04:52.040
[Guest]: And I have an argument to make because it's an argument that I think everyone around me should,

01:04:52.040 --> 01:04:58.200
[Guest]: or my readers should know the way I know. So he's able to look at the democracy, the society,

01:04:58.200 --> 01:05:04.120
[Guest]: with the same lens and comfort that I have. So when a leader makes a promise for a certain

01:05:04.120 --> 01:05:11.400
[Guest]: statement, I can see through what Prem said, that I'm a very typical beat reporter. So when in beat

01:05:11.400 --> 01:05:17.800
[Guest]: reporting, we say that, have you cracked the beat or not? Crack meaning, then you are so comfortable,

01:05:17.800 --> 01:05:22.040
[Guest]: you can predict what's going to happen in the beat. So I can tell you in military, if I see

01:05:22.040 --> 01:05:25.000
[Guest]: something, I can tell you, okay, there's a war going to happen or not. That much confidence I

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:34.200
[Guest]: have, seeing elements around. So I think it's about cracking that apart to helping the reader

01:05:34.920 --> 01:05:37.960
[Guest]: crack the beat called India or beat called democracy.

01:05:39.480 --> 01:05:43.880
[Amit Varma]: So a final question before we go in for the break, and then we come back to discuss the book.

01:05:43.880 --> 01:05:49.240
[Amit Varma]: And this is again, from an interesting anecdote that in fact, Prem shared in a workshop that he

01:05:49.240 --> 01:05:54.280
[Amit Varma]: did for our writing class, which is by the way on YouTube, and I'll share the link in the show notes

01:05:54.280 --> 01:05:58.360
[Amit Varma]: where Prem pointed to this interview of a writer, I forget if he mentioned the name, but if he did,

01:05:58.360 --> 01:06:02.200
[Amit Varma]: I don't remember it. But this interview of a writer who was asked about his writing process,

01:06:02.200 --> 01:06:07.240
[Amit Varma]: and he said, first I go into a room, and I sit down, you know, with my computer or typewriter or

01:06:07.240 --> 01:06:13.160
[Amit Varma]: whatever. And then I shut the door. But I'm not alone. Because, you know, I can sense behind me

01:06:13.160 --> 01:06:17.800
[Amit Varma]: all the people who have expectations of me or who are looking over my shoulder in different ways,

01:06:17.800 --> 01:06:21.480
[Amit Varma]: or who I care about. And also I just sit there quietly till all of them leave.

01:06:21.480 --> 01:06:25.400
[Amit Varma]: So whoever was asking the question, then asked him, so so that's when you begin writing.

01:06:25.400 --> 01:06:29.240
[Amit Varma]: And he said, No, that's not when I begin writing either, because there is still one person in the

01:06:29.240 --> 01:06:35.080
[Amit Varma]: room, and that's me. And I wait till I leave. And then I let the story tell itself. So and I was

01:06:35.080 --> 01:06:40.920
[Amit Varma]: very struck by this. And is this something that you have thought about in your work or tried to

01:06:40.920 --> 01:06:45.400
[Amit Varma]: do? Because earlier, you spoke about how a reporter should never be the hero of a story.

01:06:45.400 --> 01:06:50.200
[Amit Varma]: Also, in terms of language, in our youth, we all write that kind of florid style, right,

01:06:50.200 --> 01:06:55.240
[Amit Varma]: when we're trying to be impressive, and which is obviously putting ourselves front and center

01:06:55.240 --> 01:06:59.480
[Amit Varma]: and saying, Look at me, how will I write, but then eventually you learn to kind of take that out and

01:06:59.480 --> 01:07:05.560
[Amit Varma]: just do justice to the story and to let it speak for itself. So tell me about your thoughts on this.

01:07:07.080 --> 01:07:12.360
[Guest]: So I said, I write in the morning, but, you know, like, after nine, I go for my walk.

01:07:12.360 --> 01:07:20.360
[Guest]: When I'm walking, I'm usually thinking about what should come next. And that process goes on

01:07:20.360 --> 01:07:26.520
[Guest]: through the day while I'm driving. And very often when I'm sitting in meetings with people,

01:07:26.520 --> 01:07:32.440
[Guest]: they do notice that I get bored very quickly and my attention goes away. One of the reasons is that

01:07:32.440 --> 01:07:36.440
[Guest]: I'm still thinking processing, how should I now structure the next two paragraphs.

01:07:36.440 --> 01:07:41.960
[Guest]: So that is something which constantly happens with me. And people have to slap me out even

01:07:41.960 --> 01:07:48.040
[Guest]: at home also. Sometimes my wife or daughter do get surprised that I'm sitting in front of TV

01:07:48.040 --> 01:07:52.680
[Guest]: and just watching. It's not that I'm lost in the TV, I'm thinking about the sentence,

01:07:52.680 --> 01:07:58.440
[Guest]: how should I introduce this character? How should I come in? I as a, you know, meaning the little

01:07:58.440 --> 01:08:05.240
[Guest]: David, how should he come into the story about explaining how often should I? So that process is

01:08:05.240 --> 01:08:12.280
[Guest]: to me, it's 24 hours. It's almost anxiety inducing to me. And I'm anxious. I suffer from anxiety.

01:08:12.280 --> 01:08:17.080
[Guest]: So I get very anxious about, you know, how much should I come in? So last, when I wrote my first

01:08:17.080 --> 01:08:21.960
[Guest]: book, my editors pushed me to come in more into the book because I was so heavy. I was skipping

01:08:21.960 --> 01:08:27.960
[Guest]: away like a traditional reporter. So when I get into the room in the morning with a cup of tea

01:08:27.960 --> 01:08:36.440
[Guest]: and sit in front of my laptop, then my previous 24 hours of processing that has happened,

01:08:36.440 --> 01:08:43.640
[Guest]: just flows. And there is an end to it. Because sometimes I have only thought about a paragraph.

01:08:44.280 --> 01:08:49.560
[Guest]: So this morning I was writing something about formation of Indian democracy. And I've been

01:08:49.560 --> 01:08:56.040
[Guest]: writing about that one incident over the last four weeks. And I've been getting so irritated

01:08:56.040 --> 01:09:01.640
[Guest]: with myself, but I am unable to pull myself away from reading transfer of power papers regarding

01:09:01.640 --> 01:09:06.520
[Guest]: those days. So it happens, it happens, but because it's lingering on and you know that there's a

01:09:06.520 --> 01:09:11.800
[Guest]: great seed out there. How do you now write it? Right? So when I sit in front of the computer

01:09:11.800 --> 01:09:17.800
[Guest]: in the morning, I am not bothered about anybody. I am just writing what I've been processing for

01:09:17.800 --> 01:09:22.840
[Guest]: the last previous 24 hours. But there is one more thing which makes my writing, which made

01:09:22.840 --> 01:09:28.680
[Guest]: it possible for me to write two books in the last five years. One is that I am, I think,

01:09:28.680 --> 01:09:32.120
[Guest]: I believe that I'm a multitasker. I can do multiple things. And a lot of people find it

01:09:32.120 --> 01:09:37.880
[Guest]: overwhelming, including my family and many friends. I mean, my mind keeps racing about

01:09:37.880 --> 01:09:41.720
[Guest]: ideas and things and people. So while I'm writing the book, I was also doing a startup.

01:09:42.520 --> 01:09:46.920
[Guest]: While I was writing this book and doing the startup, I was also helping people structure

01:09:46.920 --> 01:09:51.400
[Guest]: some film stories or documentary structures. While I was doing all these things, I was also

01:09:51.400 --> 01:09:56.040
[Guest]: fundraising. While I was doing all this, I'm also mentoring reporters on university. So I'm

01:09:56.040 --> 01:10:00.360
[Guest]: genuinely a multitasker. And maybe I become a machine in that sense. So yeah.

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:05.400
[Amit Varma]: That's very impressive. Because not only am I not a multitasker myself, like I sometimes find

01:10:05.400 --> 01:10:11.240
[Amit Varma]: it hard even to be a single tasker, and just to kind of focus on one thing. And one of the

01:10:11.240 --> 01:10:16.840
[Amit Varma]: kind of problems that I've also had is self absorption, where like you pointed out, you're

01:10:16.840 --> 01:10:20.120
[Amit Varma]: sitting in front of the TV and your mind is somewhere else. So you're sitting with someone,

01:10:20.120 --> 01:10:24.120
[Amit Varma]: but you're not in the moment, your mind is somewhere else doing something, which is something

01:10:24.120 --> 01:10:28.760
[Amit Varma]: obviously one feels guilty about if you're with loved ones, because, you know, then that becomes

01:10:28.760 --> 01:10:32.360
[Amit Varma]: a problem. Are you treating them as a means to an end? Are you not there in the moment there

01:10:32.360 --> 01:10:38.680
[Amit Varma]: for them, your mind is somewhere else. That's a complicated sort of trade off. Is that something

01:10:38.680 --> 01:10:40.360
[Amit Varma]: you've thought about? What does one do about this?

01:10:40.360 --> 01:10:46.120
[Guest]: Of course, you know, it's family is very close knit. My wife, daughter, my parents, siblings,

01:10:46.120 --> 01:10:51.960
[Guest]: all of them. But there are weeks and months when I have to make an effort to make the phone call.

01:10:51.960 --> 01:10:57.720
[Guest]: Meaning the old parents are back in village and we talk almost every other day. But there are

01:10:57.720 --> 01:11:03.160
[Guest]: weeks when I have to force myself to call them. Not that I don't love them any less, not that

01:11:03.160 --> 01:11:08.440
[Guest]: there is any friction. But what you said, you know, you're so caught up in your mind is racing

01:11:08.440 --> 01:11:13.800
[Guest]: on something that even a phone call to your loved ones is a distraction. So there are days when I

01:11:13.800 --> 01:11:19.800
[Guest]: come into my house, go to the bathroom, take bath, come back, and they're just wondering what is he

01:11:19.800 --> 01:11:29.400
[Guest]: up to. So it's a problem. But then I think all of us do have our own peculiarities that get

01:11:29.400 --> 01:11:36.280
[Guest]: accentuated as we grow older and then we get more irritated and irritating. So I am sure I'm one of

01:11:36.280 --> 01:11:41.240
[Guest]: them. But yeah, you can't help it, you know, because I used to think that this is a boarding

01:11:41.240 --> 01:11:45.160
[Guest]: school problem because you are emotionally plugged away from your family at the age of 11, 12.

01:11:45.800 --> 01:11:51.160
[Guest]: And that may be the gap. But yeah, what you're saying, I understand. So I do have to make an

01:11:51.160 --> 01:11:57.720
[Guest]: effort very often. You know, I tell myself, call your wife, call Priya. Don't keep driving for an

01:11:57.720 --> 01:12:04.040
[Guest]: hour without calling her. Yeah, it's an effort. It's an effort sometimes. Yeah, and definitely

01:12:04.040 --> 01:12:10.040
[Amit Varma]: not a boarding school problem because I didn't go to one. So anyway, we'll take a quick commercial

