[Amit Varma]: the unseen. I'm chatting with Josie Joseph about his wonderful book, The Silent Coup, a history of

01:13:35.960 --> 01:13:42.200
[Amit Varma]: India's deep state. You know, you structured the book really interestingly in terms of storytelling

01:13:42.200 --> 01:13:46.520
[Amit Varma]: where you humanize it with this character you meet early in the story in your first section in

01:13:46.520 --> 01:13:52.760
[Amit Varma]: Bombay. But I'll take more of an approach of coming at the issue from root causes. You know,

01:13:52.760 --> 01:13:58.840
[Amit Varma]: before we even start talking about our security establishment, I found three particular strands

01:13:58.840 --> 01:14:05.960
[Amit Varma]: in your book, very fascinating. And one of them is the 1857 mutiny and the 1861 Indian Police Act

01:14:05.960 --> 01:14:11.560
[Amit Varma]: that it leads to and why we still kind of feel the after effects of that. So tell me a little

01:14:11.560 --> 01:14:17.400
[Amit Varma]: bit about that. Because not many people think that our current problems go that far back. But

01:14:17.400 --> 01:14:24.840
[Amit Varma]: of course they do. So tell me a bit more about why the mutiny was so formative in having the

01:14:24.840 --> 01:14:34.520
[Guest]: kind of police force that we do now. Post-mutiny, as you know, the empire decides to take complete

01:14:34.520 --> 01:14:45.080
[Guest]: control. And one of the big steps they do is to bring in this police act and give the framework

01:14:45.080 --> 01:14:56.520
[Guest]: for a police force to run the country on behalf of the empire and to control the locals, the

01:14:56.520 --> 01:15:03.560
[Guest]: revolting locals and put them in their place. And that police act has remained the framework

01:15:04.120 --> 01:15:08.440
[Guest]: for most police acts after that, even those that have been passed after independence.

01:15:08.440 --> 01:15:16.600
[Guest]: And that remains an overarching umbrella that governs Indian police forces even today.

01:15:17.480 --> 01:15:24.440
[Guest]: For the last two, two and a half decades, and mind you, starting from the post-independence

01:15:24.440 --> 01:15:29.320
[Guest]: period, there have been administrative reforms commissions, there have been police commissions

01:15:29.320 --> 01:15:35.080
[Guest]: and others who have recommended reforms to the police act. They have all been scuttled.

01:15:35.080 --> 01:15:41.160
[Guest]: And two decades ago, Prakash Singh and others, former IPS officer landed in Supreme Court

01:15:41.160 --> 01:15:46.520
[Guest]: demanding police reforms and Supreme Court has passed landmark judgments, but they are all on

01:15:46.520 --> 01:15:51.800
[Guest]: paper. None of it seems to have worked. In nutshell, the police reforms is basically

01:15:51.800 --> 01:15:57.800
[Guest]: to depoliticise the police, which involves simple steps like at TANA level, there will be,

01:15:57.800 --> 01:16:03.480
[Guest]: or district level also, there will be a committee of nominated citizens, prominent personalities

01:16:03.480 --> 01:16:10.280
[Guest]: ensured to be, it is apolitical or with political representatives from all sides to look at the

01:16:10.280 --> 01:16:15.720
[Guest]: performance of the TANA, which is what a democracy should let do, look at their investigations or

01:16:15.720 --> 01:16:21.240
[Guest]: their operations. At the state level to give the police chief a fixed tenure so that he

01:16:21.240 --> 01:16:26.440
[Guest]: knows that whatever he does, he will, he cannot be shaken for two years by the political masters,

01:16:26.440 --> 01:16:30.600
[Guest]: which means he is not trying to please the masters. There are all these recommendations

01:16:30.600 --> 01:16:37.080
[Guest]: that are out there. Not one Indian state has fully implemented it because our politicians

01:16:37.800 --> 01:16:43.480
[Guest]: do not like the police to be apolitical. Because the moment they lose control of the police,

01:16:44.200 --> 01:16:51.400
[Guest]: their thuggery, their criminal political bent of mind cannot exist. Many of them could land up in

01:16:51.400 --> 01:16:58.920
[Guest]: jail. So, they have been, it is a political class with the active support of some part of bureaucracy

01:16:58.920 --> 01:17:06.680
[Guest]: and a lot of silence by judiciary that has helped the remnants of the First War of Independence

01:17:06.680 --> 01:17:13.800
[Guest]: and the Police Act of 1861 to remain today, which in very simple one sentence, the police

01:17:14.680 --> 01:17:22.840
[Guest]: is not of the people, police is the agent of the state and the state is empire or the politician

01:17:22.840 --> 01:17:29.240
[Guest]: and the people are potential enemies. Into that mix, add the deadly poison called corruption.

01:17:30.840 --> 01:17:34.920
[Guest]: So, the politician on top is corrupt or his party is corrupt because he needs a lot of money.

01:17:35.560 --> 01:17:42.520
[Guest]: Now, he uses this police force and other arms of the state to collect money at various levels.

01:17:44.120 --> 01:17:50.600
[Guest]: So, he helps legitimize daily corruption. So, the police constable on ground who is asking

01:17:50.600 --> 01:17:57.080
[Guest]: for a bribe knows that he will be protected by some politician at some level because he is also

01:17:57.080 --> 01:18:03.320
[Guest]: helping that politician make money somewhere else, collect some hafta somewhere. Between these two,

01:18:03.320 --> 01:18:09.000
[Guest]: we have a deadly nuclear bomb attack on the masses. Yeah, and you've detailed in your book

01:18:09.000 --> 01:18:14.040
[Amit Varma]: about how this group of people went to the Supreme Court in 1996, ex-IPS officers said,

01:18:14.040 --> 01:18:18.920
[Amit Varma]: let's get this changed. 2006, the Supreme Court rules that, hey, this is what the states need to

01:18:18.920 --> 01:18:24.200
[Amit Varma]: do and no one's run it to date. And why would they? I mean, why would any class of politicians

01:18:24.200 --> 01:18:28.920
[Amit Varma]: give up so much power? What is also kind of interesting and we almost take this for granted,

01:18:28.920 --> 01:18:35.880
[Amit Varma]: but I think it needs to be pointed out how much structurally the police here is really serving

01:18:35.880 --> 01:18:41.720
[Amit Varma]: the political class and not so much the people and it's supposed to serve the people. And this

01:18:41.720 --> 01:18:45.160
[Amit Varma]: notion of the police was something we carried over from colonial times. Like I remember during the

01:18:45.160 --> 01:18:50.920
[Amit Varma]: Constituent Assembly debates, there was one legislator who complained about how the constitution

01:18:50.920 --> 01:18:55.400
[Amit Varma]: is being written from the point of view of a policeman, which is, you know, and we kept most

01:18:55.400 --> 01:19:01.320
[Amit Varma]: of the Indian Penal Code, the IPC, which was, you know, intended to kind of subjugate the ruled,

01:19:01.320 --> 01:19:06.680
[Amit Varma]: as it were. And I think those words would still hold this way today. And an interesting thing that

01:19:06.680 --> 01:19:11.080
[Amit Varma]: not many people realize, you know, we complain about, for example, the sedition law, which,

01:19:11.080 --> 01:19:14.360
[Amit Varma]: you know, why do we need that after the British left? Well, the Supreme Court struck it down in

01:19:14.360 --> 01:19:19.160
[Amit Varma]: 1950 and Nehru brought it back with the First Amendment in a process that's detailed in

01:19:19.160 --> 01:19:23.960
[Amit Varma]: Rupardaman Singh's excellent 16 Stormy Days, which I had an episode with Rupardaman also,

01:19:23.960 --> 01:19:29.400
[Guest]: which I'll link from the show notes. So those days, the sedition, the limits of freedom of

01:19:29.400 --> 01:19:36.120
[Guest]: expression was triggered by the fear of the communist. Today, it is being triggered by the

01:19:36.120 --> 01:19:44.440
[Guest]: fear of the Muslim terrorists, or the Islamic terror conspiracies, right, and urban Naxals.

01:19:44.440 --> 01:19:49.560
[Guest]: So the enemies keep changing, enemy of the state, the so called enemies keep changing.

01:19:49.560 --> 01:19:52.600
[Guest]: But the tools against them remain the same.

01:19:53.400 --> 01:19:57.880
[Amit Varma]: The tools remain the same. The second factor out of the three, which I want to talk about,

01:19:57.880 --> 01:20:02.840
[Amit Varma]: which struck me as contributing to the security establishment being the way it is here,

01:20:02.840 --> 01:20:09.080
[Amit Varma]: is that interesting phase, post-independence, where you have this security apparatus,

01:20:09.080 --> 01:20:13.560
[Amit Varma]: which is taken over from the colonial rules, but where it's different from other countries freed

01:20:13.560 --> 01:20:19.480
[Amit Varma]: from colonialism, is that our political rulers in their wisdom realized that the military was

01:20:19.480 --> 01:20:24.040
[Amit Varma]: a danger, that there were coups happening all over the place in other newly independent countries.

01:20:24.040 --> 01:20:30.360
[Amit Varma]: We've seen on Pakistan how big a hand the military plays. So therefore, that kind of decision was

01:20:30.360 --> 01:20:36.520
[Amit Varma]: made that keep the military under control. And therefore, the parts of the security establishment,

01:20:36.520 --> 01:20:41.320
[Amit Varma]: and I'll ask you to go into detail soon. But before that, the just this kind of general phase,

01:20:41.320 --> 01:20:45.240
[Amit Varma]: the parts of the security establishment, which are dominant are, you know, the police and all

01:20:45.240 --> 01:20:51.400
[Amit Varma]: the intelligence agencies we have, and all of those and not the military per se. And there,

01:20:51.400 --> 01:20:57.640
[Amit Varma]: of course, it's a vicious circle. But tell me a little bit about how important this decision was,

01:20:57.640 --> 01:21:03.080
[Amit Varma]: and could there have been a little more foresight in seeing the way the things played out with the

01:21:03.080 --> 01:21:08.040
[Amit Varma]: rest of the security establishment as you detail in your book? Or is it not fair to expect that

01:21:08.040 --> 01:21:11.960
[Amit Varma]: of the people back in the day? I mean, how would they know that it would turn out like this?

01:21:13.000 --> 01:21:21.560
[Guest]: I think, see, the generation of Nehru, Ambedkar, Patel, Assad, that generation truly believed in

01:21:21.560 --> 01:21:28.440
[Guest]: parliamentary democracy. But they were creating the world's largest democracy. There were a

01:21:28.440 --> 01:21:34.440
[Guest]: million problems to deal with. And as old democracies, it is a process, it was a process.

01:21:35.480 --> 01:21:40.200
[Guest]: So we can't blame them for not doing it. They did some of the cornerstone moves like,

01:21:41.080 --> 01:21:46.200
[Guest]: I don't know if you go to UPSC office, you will see a photograph, Nehru is visiting UPSC to call

01:21:46.200 --> 01:21:51.560
[Guest]: on the UPSC chairman. That's the respect that Nehru, the Prime Minister gave UPSC, which is

01:21:51.560 --> 01:21:57.400
[Guest]: recruiting civil servants. Like Chief Election Commissioner is autonomy, discussions of which

01:21:57.400 --> 01:22:04.600
[Guest]: begins very early. I'm saying that the democratic state did bring in like, for example, the way it

01:22:04.600 --> 01:22:10.120
[Guest]: structured the Ministry of Defence, Army, Air Force, Navy, and Coast Guard, they became the

01:22:10.120 --> 01:22:16.280
[Guest]: adjunct offices. They were not inside the ministry. Ministry was fully civilian. And even today, I

01:22:16.280 --> 01:22:20.520
[Guest]: don't know if you know this, the Defence Secretary has to approve the budget of the military

01:22:20.520 --> 01:22:26.280
[Guest]: intelligence. So the controls are very strong, sometimes absurd also. Sometimes they go overboard

01:22:26.280 --> 01:22:30.360
[Guest]: with the babus, trying to decide everything that should be done in Siachen or you know,

01:22:30.360 --> 01:22:36.680
[Guest]: but controls are very strong. While the other part of the non-military security establishment,

01:22:36.680 --> 01:22:43.640
[Guest]: which largely came over from the British era, especially the Intelligence Bureau and later

01:22:43.640 --> 01:22:49.560
[Guest]: R&DW, also, I think, to a great extent, Indira Gandhi's autocratic base or whatever you want

01:22:49.560 --> 01:22:55.800
[Guest]: to call it, they did not put them under proper parliamentary accountability. One of the arguments

01:22:55.800 --> 01:23:00.360
[Guest]: given by many of the intelligence operatives even today is that, oh, no, no, our politicians are

01:23:00.360 --> 01:23:03.880
[Guest]: correct, we can't trust them. Maybe they're correct, but ultimately, they're people's

01:23:03.880 --> 01:23:10.520
[Guest]: representatives. But there are countries where even if the intelligence agencies are not under

01:23:10.520 --> 01:23:16.760
[Guest]: parliamentary audit, there are some kind of factional audit, checks and balances. For example,

01:23:16.760 --> 01:23:24.200
[Guest]: the entire industry of sources. So all agencies are dependent upon information and information

01:23:24.200 --> 01:23:30.600
[Guest]: comes from sources or technical intelligence. And this source industry is massive, much,

01:23:30.600 --> 01:23:38.360
[Guest]: much bigger than any industry that we know. But if a CIA or MI6, if they get information from a

01:23:38.360 --> 01:23:45.240
[Guest]: source X, and that source X is misleading, they have systems in place to audit who is X and what

01:23:45.240 --> 01:23:50.360
[Guest]: information they gave, was it misleading, then cut him off. But in India, you don't have any

01:23:51.240 --> 01:23:57.000
[Guest]: verifiable auditing mechanisms. So the fake information industry, which in turn,

01:23:57.000 --> 01:24:03.240
[Guest]: can help these agencies or arms of them to create fake narratives, etc., got strengthened over the

01:24:03.240 --> 01:24:09.640
[Guest]: years. And as the parliamentary accountability deteriorated, and parliamentary debates

01:24:09.640 --> 01:24:14.840
[Guest]: deteriorated, and parliament as an institution deteriorated, which right under Mr. Narendra

01:24:14.840 --> 01:24:19.480
[Guest]: Modi is in the worst phase. And I think the government is almost inimical towards parliament

01:24:19.480 --> 01:24:25.320
[Guest]: today. Those accountabilities have been weakening. And on the parallelly, the sinister arms,

01:24:25.320 --> 01:24:30.440
[Guest]: the unknown arms of these agencies were strengthening. Because their strength is

01:24:30.440 --> 01:24:35.480
[Guest]: not just from their lack of accountability. Their strength is also from the fact that

01:24:35.480 --> 01:24:40.760
[Guest]: they are the tools for the political masters to create their narratives, to intimidate their

01:24:40.760 --> 01:24:46.760
[Guest]: rivals, to silence the media, to silence critics. So they draw power from two sides. One,

01:24:47.480 --> 01:24:54.760
[Guest]: that they naturally are not accountable at any reasonable rate. Second, they are the tools of

01:24:54.760 --> 01:24:59.080
[Guest]: the political executive for creating the narratives and terrorizing the masses.

01:24:59.640 --> 01:25:07.080
[Guest]: So we can't say that Nehru or Patel or Assad, they were not foresighted. It is that the state

01:25:07.080 --> 01:25:13.080
[Guest]: formation is a long process. Democracies take decades to mature. And democracies collapse in

01:25:13.080 --> 01:25:19.800
[Guest]: decades. We have seen both. And we are standing at a point where, you and me today sitting here,

01:25:19.800 --> 01:25:26.920
[Guest]: I don't know how much of optimism we share about democracy's future in India. I am hopeful,

01:25:26.920 --> 01:25:32.840
[Guest]: but I don't see any reason to be optimistic that we would be a mature liberal democracy anytime

01:25:32.840 --> 01:25:41.240
[Guest]: soon. And for that, the reason is that the process of democratization of India, it doesn't happen

01:25:41.240 --> 01:25:47.400
[Guest]: like climbing a peak. In India, it is always, there have been governments during which it has

01:25:47.400 --> 01:25:52.280
[Guest]: really gone up. For example, the first Manmohan Singh government, the way right to information,

01:25:52.280 --> 01:25:57.000
[Guest]: right to education, etc. came in, it was quite impressive and revolutionary. But by the second

01:25:57.000 --> 01:26:01.160
[Guest]: Manmohan Singh government, you have corruption, all the mismanagement. So it has always been in

01:26:01.160 --> 01:26:09.240
[Guest]: ebbs and flows. But the fact is that we gave up that process somewhere, strategic process of

01:26:09.240 --> 01:26:16.200
[Guest]: bringing agencies accountable to minimize sinister sides to a democracy, to polish the edges of the

01:26:16.200 --> 01:26:21.720
[Guest]: rough edges of democratic institutions. And that's where our problems are stuck. It is not impossible

01:26:21.720 --> 01:26:30.520
[Guest]: to reform and rewind. It's not impossible to move forward. But today, we are in a very vicious cycle

01:26:30.520 --> 01:26:36.520
[Guest]: where a generation of politicians, both in power and outside have mostly been beneficiaries,

01:26:36.520 --> 01:26:42.600
[Guest]: and have actively used these arms of the security forces to create their images and narrative and

01:26:42.600 --> 01:26:48.600
[Amit Varma]: even gaps of power. To give you my view on, you know, you just said, I wonder how we feel about

01:26:48.600 --> 01:26:53.080
[Amit Varma]: liberal democracy. I'm pessimistic in the short term, pessimistic in the medium term. I'm

01:26:53.080 --> 01:26:58.520
[Amit Varma]: optimistic in the long term. But in the long term, we are all dead, as Keen said. So who knows. And

01:26:58.520 --> 01:27:01.880
[Amit Varma]: I'm also reminded by what you're saying. And I kind of agree with you that this kind of stuff

01:27:01.880 --> 01:27:05.720
[Amit Varma]: would have been impossible to foresee at the founding of the nation. And I had an episode

01:27:05.720 --> 01:27:09.800
[Amit Varma]: with the historian Gyan Prakash, who's written this very fine book on the emergency. And his

01:27:09.800 --> 01:27:15.000
[Amit Varma]: central argument there is that, you know, everything that Indira Gandhi did was really

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:19.880
[Amit Varma]: constitutional. And why was it constitutional in the first place? Why was it legit to do it?

01:27:19.880 --> 01:27:25.000
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, which has the same answer as to why did we design the state for a policeman?

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:30.360
[Amit Varma]: And what Gyan's thesis was that look, when the framers of our constitution was sitting in a room

01:27:30.360 --> 01:27:34.760
[Amit Varma]: in Delhi, framing the constitution, the country was falling apart, there was violence all over,

01:27:34.760 --> 01:27:40.280
[Amit Varma]: no one knew if the center would hold. So from their point of view, it is rational to, you know,

01:27:40.280 --> 01:27:45.160
[Amit Varma]: follow the same impulse of the colonialists, make sure it all stays together and doesn't kind of

01:27:45.160 --> 01:27:50.200
[Amit Varma]: fragment and all of that. My third question, which is not something that you've spoken about

01:27:50.200 --> 01:27:57.240
[Amit Varma]: in the book explicitly per se, but that strikes me as a big contributing factor to as one of the

01:27:57.240 --> 01:28:03.960
[Amit Varma]: manifestations of the decay in the security establishment, not a core part of it per se,

01:28:03.960 --> 01:28:10.120
[Amit Varma]: but a manifestation, a new enemy and also an old enemy is this whole Hindu Muslim thing.

01:28:10.120 --> 01:28:14.840
[Amit Varma]: More and more as I have gone through life, I realized that I kind of grew up in this kind of

01:28:14.840 --> 01:28:20.760
[Amit Varma]: clustered elite existence where one assumed that people were generally secular, and that religion

01:28:20.760 --> 01:28:27.400
[Amit Varma]: generally didn't matter. And then over a period of time, you sort of realize that it does. You

01:28:27.400 --> 01:28:33.160
[Amit Varma]: know, one thesis I have long held is that our constitution doesn't reflect who we are as a

01:28:33.160 --> 01:28:37.480
[Amit Varma]: people. And this is almost again, a cliche on the show, because I keep chatting about this with

01:28:37.480 --> 01:28:42.280
[Amit Varma]: especially constitutional experts. But the point there is that look, our constitution is not as

01:28:42.280 --> 01:28:46.680
[Amit Varma]: liberal as you and I would perhaps like it to be, but it is still more liberal than society,

01:28:46.680 --> 01:28:52.840
[Amit Varma]: which leads us to the question of was it merely a topsoil as Ambedkar so eloquently said,

01:28:52.840 --> 01:28:58.840
[Amit Varma]: and therefore, did we make a mistake in assuming that, you know, we could make the country liberal

01:28:58.840 --> 01:29:04.520
[Amit Varma]: in a top down kind of way, which itself seems a little illiberal. And did we fail at those who

01:29:04.520 --> 01:29:09.160
[Amit Varma]: are liberal among us, though many people interpret the word liberal differently, but on this, I think

01:29:09.160 --> 01:29:14.200
[Amit Varma]: they would all be agreed, did we fail among us in some way to make India more liberal, because it

01:29:14.200 --> 01:29:19.080
[Amit Varma]: now seems that, you know, politics has finally caught up with society that we were like, like

01:29:19.080 --> 01:29:23.560
[Amit Varma]: this all along. I did an episode with Akshay Mukul also on his great book in the Gita Press. And

01:29:23.560 --> 01:29:28.280
[Amit Varma]: one of the things that I learned while reading that book and looking at his work is that this

01:29:28.280 --> 01:29:34.280
[Amit Varma]: has been a country where these divisions are much deeper than we realize and much more widespread.

01:29:34.280 --> 01:29:38.840
[Amit Varma]: And this is represented in, for example, in some of the stats that you've given in your book,

01:29:38.840 --> 01:29:43.400
[Amit Varma]: like early on, you speak about the under representation of Muslims where, you know,

01:29:43.400 --> 01:29:48.680
[Amit Varma]: you speak about, and I'll quote you, less than 1% of Muslims made up the ranks of the Maharashtra

01:29:48.680 --> 01:29:54.680
[Amit Varma]: State Police, far below India's embarrassingly low 4% Muslim representation in the IPS.

01:29:54.680 --> 01:29:58.360
[Amit Varma]: The story was not very different in other states in Uttar Pradesh, 2.3%,

01:29:59.160 --> 01:30:05.880
[Amit Varma]: little over 3% head constables, just over 4% constables. And also just over 3% of the paramilitary

01:30:05.880 --> 01:30:11.640
[Amit Varma]: force was Muslim, only 3% of the IAS was Muslim, and so on. And at one level, one could say that

01:30:11.640 --> 01:30:16.360
[Amit Varma]: it's because Muslims tend to be from a lower socioeconomic class, so less opportunities and

01:30:16.360 --> 01:30:21.720
[Amit Varma]: all of that, but that can't possibly explain this massive disparity. The other thing that is very

01:30:21.720 --> 01:30:28.280
[Amit Varma]: clear in your book, time and again, is that constantly the security establishment is building

01:30:28.280 --> 01:30:34.840
[Amit Varma]: narratives of Islamic terror when none exist, creating fake news, implicating innocent people,

01:30:34.840 --> 01:30:41.000
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth. So is this a tendency that you have noticed that goes beyond all of

01:30:41.000 --> 01:30:45.240
[Amit Varma]: this? Okay, we understand that the security establishment is a tool of the political class,

01:30:45.240 --> 01:30:51.480
[Amit Varma]: and they have their own aims and all of that. But is there also this overarching anti-Muslimness,

01:30:51.480 --> 01:30:57.640
[Amit Varma]: which has been expressing itself in our governance in these ways, long before our

01:30:57.640 --> 01:31:06.360
[Guest]: politics got there? Yeah, there are a few things to consider together. One is that for the last

01:31:06.360 --> 01:31:13.000
[Guest]: three decades, what has been most of our security establishment doing? Fighting in Kashmir,

01:31:13.800 --> 01:31:19.080
[Guest]: or operating there. And what is Kashmir? While it may be militancy for Kashmir's freedom,

01:31:19.080 --> 01:31:25.960
[Guest]: whatever, it's mostly an Islamic militancy. That has really got into the nerves and DNA

01:31:25.960 --> 01:31:31.800
[Guest]: of our organizations. That has created such anti-Islamic bias, that it's going to take a

01:31:31.800 --> 01:31:37.000
[Guest]: long time to wipe away. Second, because agencies are not accountable, nobody's bothered to inspect

01:31:37.000 --> 01:31:45.800
[Guest]: these biases. Third is that if your bias and the resultant action do not attract any punishment,

01:31:45.800 --> 01:31:52.520
[Guest]: or any other pushback, you'll keep at it, because that's the safest thing to do. That's what most of

01:31:52.520 --> 01:31:58.360
[Guest]: the agency people have been doing. And because of all this, our agencies have always been

01:31:58.360 --> 01:32:04.920
[Guest]: very hostile towards Muslims. I should use the word hostile, because R&DW at the senior level

01:32:04.920 --> 01:32:12.520
[Guest]: doesn't appoint a single Muslim, after all these years. And IB has Muslims, but there have been so

01:32:12.520 --> 01:32:19.800
[Guest]: many whispers about the kind of anti-Muslim bias there. And the kind of fake information IB and

01:32:19.800 --> 01:32:25.080
[Guest]: other agencies actively spread in the last decade, when I say last decade, the first decade of the

01:32:25.080 --> 01:32:33.240
[Guest]: century, when two terror groups were bombing our cities, one was Indian Mujahideen, the other was

01:32:33.240 --> 01:32:40.760
[Guest]: a Hindu terror group. When both were bombing us, especially IB and police, they were spreading

01:32:40.760 --> 01:32:48.200
[Guest]: fake narratives and creating fake terrorists. So, I've had this couple of personal, very bizarre

01:32:48.200 --> 01:32:52.600
[Guest]: experience. So, Malegaon, first bomb blast happened. My own sources in the agencies told me,

01:32:52.600 --> 01:32:57.640
[Guest]: look, there have been Hindutva, terrorists, violence forces in that area, don't ignore it.

01:32:57.640 --> 01:33:02.760
[Guest]: So, I wrote an analysis. Next day, I am summoned, I'm called in by one of the senior most officers

01:33:02.760 --> 01:33:09.160
[Guest]: in IB, who lectures me about how two different Muslim groups are fighting in Malegaon. And one

01:33:09.160 --> 01:33:19.880
[Guest]: is Wahhabis. I think Sunnis versus Deobandis. So, I'm saying they are actively creating a

01:33:19.880 --> 01:33:25.400
[Guest]: narrative, which made me much later suspicious. If are they, were they trying to cover up

01:33:26.520 --> 01:33:32.200
[Guest]: the fact that there is a Hindutva group existing, because later on I've heard very serious senior

01:33:32.200 --> 01:33:37.400
[Guest]: people saying that there may have been some kind of a state involvement in creating the

01:33:37.400 --> 01:33:42.840
[Guest]: terrorist group. And if you look at Colonel Perot's testimonies, etc., there are hints out

01:33:42.840 --> 01:33:51.240
[Guest]: there. So, what I'm saying is that the anti-Muslim bias that really peaked because of Kashmir,

01:33:51.800 --> 01:33:59.080
[Guest]: within the ranks, have been further strengthened by actions within the organizations of not

01:33:59.080 --> 01:34:03.160
[Guest]: actively recruiting enough Muslims, not bringing Muslims to leadership positions,

01:34:03.160 --> 01:34:09.880
[Guest]: not that there were not Muslims available, etc. And third, the lack of accountability. So,

01:34:09.880 --> 01:34:14.440
[Guest]: those intelligence operatives, those policemen who created the fake narratives, who created

01:34:14.440 --> 01:34:19.480
[Guest]: fake terrorists, all of them have gotten away without any punishment. Some of your most

01:34:19.480 --> 01:34:24.840
[Guest]: celebrated IPS officers have been crass anti-Muslim communal people in their ranks.

01:34:25.880 --> 01:34:29.080
[Guest]: And that is what I captured in my book. I have tried to capture in my book.

01:34:29.080 --> 01:34:35.320
[Guest]: Many of our police officers and policemen who have been honoured by the president and the

01:34:35.320 --> 01:34:41.400
[Guest]: states year after year are mere, brutal, daylight murderers. So, there is no accountability,

01:34:41.400 --> 01:34:47.240
[Guest]: they are not held accountable. You don't see very many policemen, there are some exceptions

01:34:47.240 --> 01:34:51.960
[Guest]: in Manipur, for example, 50 policemen are on trial for state-sponsored killings, but I don't

01:34:51.960 --> 01:34:56.280
[Guest]: know what's happening to them. Other than that, look at Punjab, thousands disappeared. I mean,

01:34:56.280 --> 01:35:01.320
[Guest]: you come in, KPS, Gill or others, whatever justifications you can give, but in a democracy,

01:35:02.280 --> 01:35:08.360
[Guest]: even in the thickest fog of war, the police or the agencies are supposed to be upholding

01:35:08.360 --> 01:35:13.560
[Guest]: the constitution of the country, which guarantees individual liberty to everyone,

01:35:13.560 --> 01:35:18.600
[Guest]: including every Sardarji, every Punjabi in Punjab, every Manipuri, every Kashmiri.

01:35:18.600 --> 01:35:25.640
[Guest]: So, somewhere we got completely messed up and because, see, without accountability,

01:35:25.640 --> 01:35:33.960
[Guest]: no systems improve. So, you are speaking of emergency, how did Indira Gandhi and Kothari

01:35:33.960 --> 01:35:39.480
[Guest]: manage to run this country for one and a half, two years under emergency? It is because they

01:35:39.480 --> 01:35:44.840
[Guest]: had this non-security, non-military arm of the security establishment, especially the police,

01:35:44.840 --> 01:35:51.960
[Guest]: income tax, etc., to terrorize people. And after that, what happened? Jagmohan, who was in Delhi,

01:35:52.760 --> 01:35:57.880
[Guest]: leading many of the demolitions or actions of Delhi, what happened to him? He went on to become

01:35:57.880 --> 01:36:03.000
[Guest]: a cabinet minister and twice the governor of Jammu and Kashmir. So, is the story of almost

01:36:03.000 --> 01:36:09.640
[Guest]: every other bureaucrat who played the gunda role for the Indira Gandhi's emergency period. What

01:36:09.640 --> 01:36:16.520
[Guest]: happened to policemen who did ridiculous things in Gujarat under Narendra Modi? They are all now

01:36:16.520 --> 01:36:23.880
[Guest]: in powerful positions or have been given police medals and honors. So, we have a pattern which

01:36:24.840 --> 01:36:32.760
[Guest]: encourages anti-Muslim biases and hostility towards minorities. And that is only going up

01:36:32.760 --> 01:36:38.360
[Guest]: by the day because ever since our new government has come into power, they have been, I mean,

01:36:38.360 --> 01:36:43.480
[Guest]: it is an embarrassing thing for you to hear a prime minister say that I can identify the

01:36:43.480 --> 01:36:49.160
[Guest]: protesters by their clothes. I mean, forget the communal tone of it. Look at the, what is the

01:36:49.160 --> 01:36:57.080
[Guest]: word, illiteracy of that language. Look at the stupidity of that language. So, we are in a crisis,

01:36:57.080 --> 01:37:05.000
[Guest]: a crisis where anti-Muslim bias is both good politics and good for the rascals in the police

01:37:05.000 --> 01:37:10.520
[Guest]: ranks or influence ranks. It's almost like a criminal collusion. Yeah, that's what it's come

01:37:10.520 --> 01:37:16.760
[Amit Varma]: down to. And let's talk now about, you know, I want to go through each region one at a time,

01:37:16.760 --> 01:37:20.280
[Amit Varma]: the way you've laid it out in your book is beautiful. And we'll probably start with

01:37:20.280 --> 01:37:26.040
[Amit Varma]: Kashmir. I want to talk about Punjab, about Bombay, all of these. But first, I'd like you to

01:37:26.040 --> 01:37:32.120
[Amit Varma]: define for my listeners what you mean by the security establishment, because one of the

01:37:32.120 --> 01:37:36.920
[Amit Varma]: staggering sort of numbers in your book was when you point out that there are about 4 million

01:37:36.920 --> 01:37:42.600
[Amit Varma]: members in the non-military security establishment distributed across the country, from, you know,

01:37:42.600 --> 01:37:47.880
[Amit Varma]: state police to tax collectors, and so on. Let's define this. We don't mean the military by the

01:37:47.880 --> 01:37:53.080
[Amit Varma]: non-military security establishment. What exactly does it mean? And how widespread is it?

01:37:54.120 --> 01:38:01.400
[Guest]: So, non-military means you have the paramilitary forces, which increasingly play a lot of role in

01:38:01.400 --> 01:38:07.880
[Guest]: domestic politics, militancy, etc. You have the state police forces, who are governed by the

01:38:08.600 --> 01:38:16.520
[Guest]: legacy of the 1861 Police Act. You have a countrywide network of income tax

01:38:17.240 --> 01:38:22.920
[Guest]: enforcement directorate. You have the Directorate of Revenue Intelligence. You have the Central

01:38:22.920 --> 01:38:29.400
[Guest]: Bureau of Investigation. All of them have state nationwide presence. All of them are empowered

01:38:29.400 --> 01:38:35.160
[Guest]: with bundles of laws, which are very, very efficient and can be easily misused if there

01:38:35.160 --> 01:38:41.800
[Guest]: is no accountability. And all of these forces, so unless the state police force is under

01:38:42.440 --> 01:38:47.960
[Guest]: an opposition party, otherwise it's available to the centre or the party in power.

01:38:49.480 --> 01:38:55.560
[Guest]: Even in states where the opposition is ruling, even that opposition, the formula of misuse is

01:38:55.560 --> 01:39:01.320
[Guest]: the same. So, you can't say that in Mamata Banerjee's West Bengal Police is very good. No,

01:39:01.320 --> 01:39:06.600
[Guest]: because there also political power draws significantly from the misuse or the

01:39:06.600 --> 01:39:13.080
[Guest]: leverage with the police. So, this 4 million approximate number that I had calculated,

01:39:14.120 --> 01:39:20.520
[Guest]: 4 lakh people are spread across the country. They are empowered by various laws and they are

01:39:20.520 --> 01:39:27.080
[Guest]: almost faceless. And whatever they do, very little of accountability. And they're assured

01:39:27.640 --> 01:39:33.080
[Guest]: that they just need to obey the political masters of the day. In fact, their careers will boom. I

01:39:33.080 --> 01:39:40.280
[Guest]: mean, it will flourish. They'll go to great heights in careers. That is non-military.

01:39:40.280 --> 01:39:46.920
[Guest]: And why am I not stressing too much on the IAS is because yes, IAS also is part of the

01:39:46.920 --> 01:39:53.480
[Guest]: political manipulation, but my focus was more on the security aspects of the state.

01:39:54.520 --> 01:40:00.280
[Guest]: But add to it now the civil service, IAS. A large number of the IAS officers are available to the

01:40:00.280 --> 01:40:06.120
[Guest]: political establishment. The good ones have gone quiet or left the service. So, we have a monster

01:40:06.120 --> 01:40:13.800
[Guest]: out there. Most of it is not even visible to us. You can't put a shape to it. And you wouldn't

01:40:13.800 --> 01:40:19.320
[Guest]: know that in your neighborhood sits an Income Tax Office or Enforcement Directorate. So,

01:40:19.320 --> 01:40:24.840
[Guest]: it's almost invisible and they're present across the country and abroad. And they've got enormous

01:40:24.840 --> 01:40:32.520
[Guest]: clout, power and laws. And that's the non-security establishment, what I call the non-military arm

01:40:32.520 --> 01:40:37.880
[Amit Varma]: of the security establishment, if I may call it. Yeah, and all of them are used by politicians as

01:40:37.880 --> 01:40:43.080
[Amit Varma]: by whoever is in power at that moment as a tools because that's just the structure of the whole

01:40:43.080 --> 01:40:48.840
[Amit Varma]: thing. And you mentioned civil service, which brought to my mind, a thought I probably shouldn't

01:40:48.840 --> 01:40:53.880
[Amit Varma]: share, but I'll share it anyway, that should an impolite IAS officer be considered part of the

01:40:53.880 --> 01:41:00.280
[Amit Varma]: civil service. I had to get my one dad joke out of the way at this part of the episode. Let's talk

01:41:00.280 --> 01:41:05.080
[Amit Varma]: about Kashmir now. And Kashmir seems to me an apt place to start because it's perhaps the starkest

01:41:05.080 --> 01:41:11.400
[Amit Varma]: illustration of how the security establishment can grow and how it can create a kind of a vicious

01:41:11.400 --> 01:41:17.000
[Amit Varma]: circle. Now, it's interesting you point out how you could see the security establishment in action

01:41:17.000 --> 01:41:21.960
[Amit Varma]: as early as 1951, where you write about Sheikh Abdullah in the elections in that year, where you

01:41:21.960 --> 01:41:26.440
[Amit Varma]: say, quote, Sheikh Abdullah was a seasoned politician quoted by two countries and stood

01:41:26.440 --> 01:41:31.480
[Amit Varma]: astride the fault lines of nation making in South Asia. In October 51, when elections in the Kashmir

01:41:31.480 --> 01:41:36.120
[Amit Varma]: Constituent Assembly were held, he ensured that the nomination papers of several leaders of Praja

01:41:36.120 --> 01:41:41.720
[Amit Varma]: Parishad, a party of Jammu Hindus that was opposed to him, were rejected on mere technicalities.

01:41:41.720 --> 01:41:48.840
[Amit Varma]: NC won all 75 seats. Abdullah went on to jail over 10,000 people on political charges. And in many

01:41:48.840 --> 01:41:54.600
[Amit Varma]: instances, his detractors were expelled to Pakistan. In short, he manipulated the state machinery to

01:41:54.600 --> 01:41:59.400
[Amit Varma]: meet his own political ambitions. Thinking back, it's not surprising that JNK, which has witnessed

01:41:59.400 --> 01:42:04.040
[Amit Varma]: some of the worst tragedies of state machinations, should have been one of the first Indian states

01:42:04.040 --> 01:42:08.760
[Amit Varma]: where the political and permanent executive manipulated the security apparatus. Now, this is,

01:42:08.760 --> 01:42:15.240
[Amit Varma]: of course, pretty standard. But where we see the underpinnings of the crisis that is sort of still

01:42:15.240 --> 01:42:21.560
[Amit Varma]: going on is when you talk about the 60s and what's happening there, and how what you so eloquently

01:42:21.560 --> 01:42:28.680
[Amit Varma]: call the business of militancy begins to sort of take shape. And tell me a little bit more about

01:42:28.680 --> 01:42:35.240
[Amit Varma]: this period in the 1960s and the sort of vicious circle that it leads to, where you have this sort

01:42:35.240 --> 01:42:41.720
[Amit Varma]: of security apparatus, whose incentives are tailored towards continuing to have an enemy

01:42:41.720 --> 01:42:46.920
[Amit Varma]: to fight against and therefore whose brutalities against this imagined and supposed, sometimes

01:42:46.920 --> 01:42:52.680
[Amit Varma]: imagined and supposed enemies, actually create more disaffected people. And then it just becomes

01:42:52.680 --> 01:42:57.960
[Amit Varma]: a spiral. And we've seen that spiral play out, you know, the 90s onwards. But, you know, until I read

01:42:57.960 --> 01:43:03.400
[Amit Varma]: your book, I hadn't realized the extent to which it took solid shape in the 60s itself. So tell me

01:43:03.400 --> 01:43:10.120
[Guest]: a bit about that. Yeah, so, you know, Kashmir always had this elements there who either wanted

01:43:10.120 --> 01:43:16.280
[Guest]: to be part of Pakistan or wanted to be independent, right. And if you recall, during the

01:43:16.280 --> 01:43:21.240
[Guest]: independence, in the Poonch side, there have been huge rebellions, etc. So in Kashmir Valley,

01:43:21.240 --> 01:43:28.360
[Guest]: the militancy actually starts in the 1960s. It started then with very educated youngsters taking

01:43:28.360 --> 01:43:36.760
[Guest]: up arms in a very limited way. Many of them were actually wanting to support the 1965 Pakistan

01:43:36.760 --> 01:43:42.120
[Guest]: invaders. And then they went on to carry on with the militancy and there were bank robberies,

01:43:42.120 --> 01:43:47.720
[Guest]: etc. And many of them are very educated. The fact is that these were these, you know,

01:43:47.720 --> 01:43:56.200
[Guest]: young educated college graduates, etc. from well-to-do families, engineers, doctors, etc.

01:43:56.200 --> 01:44:03.720
[Guest]: And these pioneers of militancy were definitely anti-India. They were very clear about the fact

01:44:03.720 --> 01:44:08.920
[Guest]: that Kashmir should be independent or with Pakistan. When the militancy started,

01:44:08.920 --> 01:44:16.760
[Guest]: these militants started doing bank robberies or attacks, police responded. And the more brutal

01:44:16.760 --> 01:44:21.320
[Guest]: the police, the more rewards the police got from the state, meaning the state actively started

01:44:21.320 --> 01:44:27.640
[Guest]: encouraging brutal policing. And thus began to come up one of the most important landmarks of

01:44:27.640 --> 01:44:33.240
[Guest]: Kashmir which are interrogation centres. They started creating interrogation centres into

01:44:33.240 --> 01:44:38.680
[Guest]: which these youngsters were hauled up and they were tortured and forced to confess whatever.

01:44:39.400 --> 01:44:43.560
[Guest]: You can argue about the goodness or badness of waterboarding and torture, but I think in a

01:44:43.560 --> 01:44:53.480
[Guest]: democracy it has no place. Now that phenomenon of militancy and the counter policing, unaccounted

01:44:53.480 --> 01:45:05.080
[Guest]: policing, it began to pick pace, but did not really take off because by the 1970s, as you know,

01:45:05.080 --> 01:45:12.280
[Guest]: the Sheikh Indira Accord came into being and Kashmir actually witnessed a large period of

01:45:12.280 --> 01:45:18.840
[Guest]: peaceful democratic existence. And if India had, Indian leadership had made the efforts

01:45:19.880 --> 01:45:22.600
[Guest]: in the 80s, Kashmir would have been a peaceful paradise.

01:45:24.520 --> 01:45:32.840
[Guest]: But the political machinations that both centre, Congress and the local politicians did,

01:45:32.840 --> 01:45:42.440
[Guest]: especially Farooq Abdullah and Rajiv Gandhi did in 1987, triggered the storm and it triggered

01:45:42.440 --> 01:45:49.880
[Guest]: the new militancy which till day continues to consume Kashmir, consume India's democratic

01:45:49.880 --> 01:45:57.000
[Guest]: credentials, consume thousands of lives of local ordinary people there and thousands of Indian

01:45:57.000 --> 01:46:05.640
[Guest]: security forces. And even then, 87, so first the political manipulation happens and then as the

01:46:05.640 --> 01:46:14.280
[Guest]: militancy picks up, instead of finding political solutions to the problem, India securitized the

01:46:14.280 --> 01:46:21.640
[Guest]: entire Kashmir issue and sent more forces in, more interrogations came up, more agencies came in,

01:46:21.640 --> 01:46:27.720
[Guest]: more cruelties came in. And while it is all happening, you have the monster of ISI and

01:46:27.720 --> 01:46:32.920
[Guest]: Pakistan on the other side. On the other side, and that's the foolishness of the Indian

01:46:33.720 --> 01:46:39.480
[Guest]: myopic political leadership of the day, that they couldn't realize the fact that

01:46:41.000 --> 01:46:47.080
[Guest]: Pakistan had by then become a state where one was it was a state owned by the military,

01:46:47.080 --> 01:46:51.960
[Guest]: second, the military's legitimacy largely came from and Pakistan's legitimacy largely came from

01:46:51.960 --> 01:47:00.120
[Guest]: the struggle in fight for Kashmir. And in Afghanistan, you had the CIA, ISI sponsored

01:47:00.120 --> 01:47:06.520
[Guest]: Mujahideen and by the end of the 80s, when the Soviet Union collapses, withdraws from there,

01:47:06.520 --> 01:47:15.640
[Guest]: all of them, all the resources is diverted into Kashmir. And we have till date, we might say

01:47:15.640 --> 01:47:22.760
[Guest]: anything. Indian state till date doesn't have neither the control over Kashmir narrative,

01:47:23.400 --> 01:47:30.760
[Guest]: nor found a formula to deal with it. We have done the same things that the other side has been

01:47:30.760 --> 01:47:39.160
[Guest]: doing. We can't take any much, much higher moral grounds than anyone else. And that's a frightening

01:47:39.160 --> 01:47:47.240
[Guest]: part for a democracy to be playing as dirty as the militants or an ISI sponsored state is

01:47:47.240 --> 01:47:57.560
[Guest]: embarrassing. So, Kashmir, in many ways, captures the decay that I'm talking about in the heart of

01:47:57.560 --> 01:48:08.120
[Guest]: Indian democracy, which is that we let our agencies go to rot in Kashmir. And there are thousands of

01:48:08.120 --> 01:48:12.840
[Guest]: floors that are being pumped into that state every year in the name of security. And we don't seem

01:48:12.840 --> 01:48:17.320
[Guest]: to find any solution. We try various tactics, nothing seems to be working. And the latest

01:48:17.320 --> 01:48:23.720
[Guest]: efforts by the Modi government to withdraw Article 370 and bifurcate the state doesn't seem to have

01:48:23.720 --> 01:48:31.320
[Guest]: done anything much. It again looks to me that it will burst out any day. But Kashmir, what it did

01:48:31.320 --> 01:48:38.440
[Guest]: was the Indian response in Kashmir to the militancy of the 60s and later in the 80s and 90s is to

01:48:38.440 --> 01:48:46.360
[Guest]: contaminate the Indian democratic project while letting massive human rights violations and

01:48:46.360 --> 01:48:57.160
[Guest]: sacrifices by Indian security agencies both. So, it's a very tragic tale of how, what could have

01:48:57.160 --> 01:49:04.520
[Guest]: been the crown on India's head turning into an embarrassment and a shame. You mentioned

01:49:04.520 --> 01:49:08.120
[Amit Varma]: interrogation centers and one of the striking details I was struck by in your book was that

01:49:08.120 --> 01:49:13.960
[Amit Varma]: one of them was called Papa 2, which is such a benign name. I remember back in my days as a

01:49:13.960 --> 01:49:18.200
[Amit Varma]: professional poker player, when I would win a big pot, I would often say come to Papa as I would

01:49:18.200 --> 01:49:22.600
[Amit Varma]: bring the chips towards me. And, you know, so if I ever make a comeback, I can say come to Papa 2,

01:49:22.600 --> 01:49:28.200
[Amit Varma]: which now has multiple shades of meaning. And it's also interesting that you point out how many

01:49:28.200 --> 01:49:34.120
[Amit Varma]: of the people in that early swell in the 1960s were highly educated, which reminds me of exactly

01:49:34.120 --> 01:49:39.480
[Amit Varma]: the same thing, what people talk about early Naxalism, that, you know, the best minds of the

01:49:39.480 --> 01:49:44.200
[Amit Varma]: generation were kind of drawn to it, which I find so tragic, I mean, says a lot about, you know,

01:49:44.200 --> 01:49:48.680
[Amit Varma]: a little knowledge being a dangerous thing about misplaced idealism, you know, taking up arms

01:49:48.680 --> 01:49:53.640
[Amit Varma]: against the state and all that never kind of works as an interesting sort of para I want to read out

01:49:53.640 --> 01:50:01.080
[Amit Varma]: from your book, which refers to the 60s, but which actually seems resonant, far beyond that as well.

01:50:01.080 --> 01:50:08.280
[Amit Varma]: So I'll just read it out, where you talk about some of these torture chambers or interrogation

01:50:08.280 --> 01:50:12.360
[Amit Varma]: centers, as it were, and you write quote, behind the soundproof walls of these buildings,

01:50:12.360 --> 01:50:17.480
[Amit Varma]: a new narrative was created for Kashmir. Within these confines, the security forces tortured both

01:50:17.480 --> 01:50:23.000
[Amit Varma]: militants and ordinary protesters. The torture in turn fed the anger and fury of the local narratives

01:50:23.000 --> 01:50:27.800
[Amit Varma]: against India. Regardless of the explanation supplied by security agencies, the secret

01:50:27.800 --> 01:50:32.760
[Amit Varma]: compounds of the interrogation centers tarnish the credentials of Indian democracy while feeding the

01:50:32.760 --> 01:50:37.720
[Amit Varma]: ranks of militancy. And as violence rose, security deployment went up further, and so did the number

01:50:37.720 --> 01:50:43.160
[Amit Varma]: of interrogation centers. Meanwhile, Pakistan had over the years established an efficient network of

01:50:43.160 --> 01:50:48.680
[Amit Varma]: informants, couriers, gossip mongers and overground workers with extensive funding channels. As it

01:50:48.680 --> 01:50:53.640
[Amit Varma]: pumped in more money and militants into Kashmir, India increased its own deployment of security

01:50:53.640 --> 01:50:59.800
[Amit Varma]: forces and created even more interrogation centers. The business of militancy was flourishing,

01:50:59.800 --> 01:51:05.640
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. So you know, before I come to the 90s, and you know, ask you to elaborate on how

01:51:05.640 --> 01:51:10.920
[Amit Varma]: all of this spun out of control, a tangential thought, which is a few years ago, I read this

01:51:10.920 --> 01:51:15.720
[Amit Varma]: great book by David Galula called counter insurgency warfare. And, you know, a lot of the

01:51:15.720 --> 01:51:22.280
[Amit Varma]: lessons in that are lessons that, for example, speak to the mistakes that the US made in Vietnam,

01:51:22.280 --> 01:51:27.160
[Amit Varma]: or that we made in Kashmir throughout, or that people have always made fighting counter

01:51:27.160 --> 01:51:33.640
[Amit Varma]: insurgents, where Galula's fundamental point made by many others, and learned by the US to some

01:51:33.640 --> 01:51:40.920
[Amit Varma]: extent after the invasion of Iraq went out of whack, was that you don't fight a counter insurgency

01:51:40.920 --> 01:51:46.440
[Amit Varma]: just by defeating that proximate bunch of people who turn up as militants and, you know, just

01:51:46.440 --> 01:51:53.560
[Amit Varma]: getting rid of them and killing them. It involves really getting the local people on your side. And,

01:51:53.560 --> 01:51:59.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, T.E. Lawrence once spoke about how, you know, beating a counter insurgency is like eating

01:51:59.000 --> 01:52:05.160
[Amit Varma]: soup with a knife. It's incredibly difficult. And the typical formula for that, which, you know,

01:52:05.160 --> 01:52:11.000
[Amit Varma]: again comes from Galula, is that it has to be 20% military 80% political. And it seems to me that at

01:52:11.000 --> 01:52:17.000
[Amit Varma]: some level, this lesson, like first of all, the Indian establishment took completely the wrong

01:52:17.000 --> 01:52:22.120
[Amit Varma]: approach to it. Almost none of it was political, it was really 100% military from what it would

01:52:22.680 --> 01:52:27.880
[Amit Varma]: seem to me. And it continues that way, the thinking still percolates that way. And that

01:52:27.880 --> 01:52:32.920
[Amit Varma]: sense of you need to gain the trust of the local people and all of that simply doesn't happen. So

01:52:32.920 --> 01:52:38.440
[Amit Varma]: tell me about, you know, one, your views on this. And, you know, so many people within the security

01:52:38.440 --> 01:52:43.560
[Amit Varma]: establishment, was there a sense that this should be done differently? Or even looking back in

01:52:43.560 --> 01:52:48.040
[Amit Varma]: hindsight today, that this could have been done differently. Like I read this great book by David

01:52:48.040 --> 01:52:53.400
[Amit Varma]: Devdas called A Generation of Rage in Kashmir, where he postulates that, you know, the Kashmir

01:52:53.400 --> 01:52:59.560
[Amit Varma]: problem was kind of improving by the middle of the aughties. You know, Vajpayee spoke to Musharraf

01:52:59.560 --> 01:53:04.200
[Amit Varma]: and or was it Nawaz Sharif, I forget, but you had talks happening, you had things coming down,

01:53:04.200 --> 01:53:08.600
[Amit Varma]: there was a new generation of people in Kashmir who wanted jobs, who wanted economic progress,

01:53:08.600 --> 01:53:15.320
[Amit Varma]: all of that. But the security establishment that was there, just continued with their oppressive

01:53:15.320 --> 01:53:20.600
[Amit Varma]: ways, torturing innocent people, building narratives, and that just disenchanted an

01:53:20.600 --> 01:53:25.800
[Amit Varma]: entirely new generation. And then we entered another spiral at that point in time. So just

01:53:25.800 --> 01:53:31.880
[Amit Varma]: at an attitudinal level, just at that level of understanding that fine, at one hand, there is a

01:53:31.880 --> 01:53:37.000
[Amit Varma]: terrorism problem, Pakistan is sending people, all that is happening, you know, we need to

01:53:37.720 --> 01:53:44.120
[Amit Varma]: beat that back with a firm hand. But at the same time, you also need to do the 80% politics to go

01:53:44.120 --> 01:53:49.080
[Amit Varma]: with the 20% military and that was never done. First of all, would you agree with it? And if so,

01:53:49.080 --> 01:53:53.480
[Amit Varma]: is there a sense of recognition of that within the establishment, even in hindsight,

01:53:53.480 --> 01:53:59.240
[Guest]: even now after the ship has sailed? So I don't think so. I think if you look at

01:53:59.240 --> 01:54:05.560
[Guest]: the present government, it's a very securitized, communalized view of Kashmir, which is very

01:54:05.560 --> 01:54:12.920
[Guest]: unfortunate, which might get them immediate votes in the rest of India. But it's a disaster for

01:54:12.920 --> 01:54:21.800
[Guest]: India, if you ask me, for democracy, Indian democracy. In the past, you're right, there have been efforts, there have been moments when we thought there is a breakthrough coming,

01:54:21.800 --> 01:54:28.760
[Guest]: especially in 2000, during the Hezbollah Mujahideen ceasefire. And if that ceasefire, while it was

01:54:28.760 --> 01:54:35.400
[Guest]: called off from Pakistan by Sayyid Salahuddin, because I had interviewed Abdul Majid, the

01:54:35.400 --> 01:54:40.680
[Guest]: military commander on ground, and there were enough people on ground who were supporting that

01:54:40.680 --> 01:54:46.040
[Guest]: efforts at peace, and it could have been a dramatic breakthrough. But my own reading those

01:54:46.040 --> 01:54:53.640
[Guest]: days, because I was actively reporting, is that many within the Indian system did not want any

01:54:53.640 --> 01:55:01.880
[Guest]: risky affair, which could bring peace into Kashmir. Because by then, our military leadership,

01:55:01.880 --> 01:55:09.640
[Guest]: our intelligence leadership, leadership of the paramilitary forces, etc., etc., a generation of

01:55:09.640 --> 01:55:15.480
[Guest]: them had all earned their medals and applauds in Kashmir. They had tested power, unbridled power.

01:55:16.280 --> 01:55:22.280
[Guest]: And in that, military is also to be blamed in Kashmir's problem. They almost actively scuttled

01:55:22.280 --> 01:55:26.760
[Guest]: or misled the political establishment. Otherwise, we could have had peace. There have been moments

01:55:27.400 --> 01:55:32.680
[Guest]: in all through, during watch face time, there was moments when we thought we are very close to

01:55:32.680 --> 01:55:40.120
[Guest]: peace. But I think that is where the agencies played dirty and people created their own

01:55:40.120 --> 01:55:47.400
[Guest]: narratives. If there was proper accountability and proper audit of the agencies and Kashmir

01:55:47.400 --> 01:55:53.880
[Guest]: situation, I think we could have found breakthroughs at various points of time.

01:55:53.880 --> 01:56:03.400
[Guest]: See, what happens that many societies have grievances. But a mature democracy would find

01:56:03.400 --> 01:56:12.680
[Guest]: its ways like the Irish problem or others, would find political means of mellowing it down and

01:56:12.680 --> 01:56:19.000
[Guest]: weaning away the anger over a period of time. And that is a very patient political process.

01:56:19.000 --> 01:56:25.080
[Guest]: If I am not wrong, the Truth and Reconciliation Commission of Ireland ran for over a decade,

01:56:25.080 --> 01:56:32.280
[Guest]: decade and a half before it punished a policeman or anybody. So, it is a very patient, it is a

01:56:32.280 --> 01:56:38.920
[Guest]: very demanding task and nation building itself is a very demanding task. I think our political

01:56:38.920 --> 01:56:46.520
[Guest]: leadership failed on both ends and Kashmir became the prime example. But mind you, not just Kashmir,

01:56:46.520 --> 01:56:55.080
[Guest]: if you look at Nagaland, Northeast, all of it, we have a very, very poor track record in dealing

01:56:55.080 --> 01:57:01.160
[Guest]: with militancy. Globally, post Second World War, the average militancy has been, I think,

01:57:01.160 --> 01:57:06.760
[Guest]: 8 to 10 years old. Within that, either it is defeated or political solutions are found.

01:57:06.760 --> 01:57:11.160
[Guest]: But in our country, the Naga insurgency problem continues to date after,

01:57:11.160 --> 01:57:18.120
[Guest]: started in independence, continues to date. So, in all these places, if you dispassionately look

01:57:18.120 --> 01:57:25.720
[Guest]: from a perspective of state building, politically, you will realize that it is the lack of

01:57:25.720 --> 01:57:33.480
[Guest]: accountability of our agencies, including our military, while it is operating on ground,

01:57:33.480 --> 01:57:39.560
[Guest]: that has led to this crisis and to the million mutinies that you are witnessing today.

01:57:39.560 --> 01:57:45.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I had a very memorable episode with Srinath Raghavan right after, you know,

01:57:45.400 --> 01:57:50.280
[Amit Varma]: 370 was repealed, which is to date the most downloaded episode of my podcast. And it is

01:57:50.280 --> 01:57:55.160
[Amit Varma]: really good because Srinath is such an amazing historian. Now, one of the things that you've

01:57:55.160 --> 01:57:59.960
[Amit Varma]: pointed out is how these security agencies, many of which the common man may not even be

01:57:59.960 --> 01:58:05.080
[Amit Varma]: aware of, have proliferated, where at one point you write, quote, the army is only one piece of

01:58:05.080 --> 01:58:11.000
[Amit Varma]: the Indian security web in the valley. Until the 1960s, the IB was India's prime and only

01:58:11.000 --> 01:58:17.000
[Amit Varma]: federal intelligence agency dealing with J&K. By the late 60s, R&AW was established to deal with

01:58:17.000 --> 01:58:21.160
[Amit Varma]: external intelligence. Within a few years, started its operation in Kashmir. As India

01:58:21.160 --> 01:58:25.960
[Amit Varma]: struggled with internal strife and external threats, new intelligence agencies and security

01:58:25.960 --> 01:58:31.000
[Amit Varma]: arms were added. Almost two dozen intelligence agencies of various kinds exist in India today.

01:58:31.000 --> 01:58:35.320
[Amit Varma]: Some are part of larger forces like the paramilitary or state police, and others are

01:58:35.320 --> 01:58:40.840
[Amit Varma]: standalone agencies. And many of them have a significant presence in Kashmir. Now, what also

01:58:40.840 --> 01:58:46.360
[Amit Varma]: strikes me about that is incentive theme that has played out across pretty much all my episodes

01:58:46.360 --> 01:58:50.600
[Amit Varma]: about how people respond to incentives. And there are two kinds of incentives at play. And one is

01:58:50.600 --> 01:58:55.880
[Amit Varma]: just a larger incentives. Like one of the things that we have seen from the Pakistani military

01:58:55.880 --> 01:59:01.320
[Amit Varma]: being so powerful out there is that they need to keep Kashmir on the boil always alive, because

01:59:01.320 --> 01:59:05.960
[Amit Varma]: that is where they get a lot of their power and their budgets and their justifications and all of

01:59:05.960 --> 01:59:12.280
[Amit Varma]: the narratives that they use to thrive. Similarly, even for the Indian military establishment,

01:59:12.280 --> 01:59:18.600
[Amit Varma]: it is in their interest to have an enemy, because that is then their justification. If, you know,

01:59:18.600 --> 01:59:23.240
[Amit Varma]: suddenly we were guaranteed eternal peace by some miracle, military establishments would not

01:59:23.240 --> 01:59:28.760
[Amit Varma]: like that. So in a sense, there is that at a larger level, there is that imperative to keep

01:59:28.760 --> 01:59:35.480
[Amit Varma]: the pot boiling. At a smaller level. Also, there are all kinds of incentives in play like one is

01:59:35.480 --> 01:59:40.920
[Amit Varma]: power always corrupts when your security establishment gets so much power in Kashmir,

01:59:40.920 --> 01:59:44.760
[Amit Varma]: where they're giving away building contracts, and there's so many opportunities of corruption,

01:59:44.760 --> 01:59:48.840
[Amit Varma]: they're obviously never going to let it go. And they're never going to do anything that could

01:59:48.840 --> 01:59:55.560
[Amit Varma]: diminish their presence and their power in in the area. And also direct incentives like, for example,

01:59:55.560 --> 02:00:00.360
[Amit Varma]: security forces at the time as you have written about as David Devdas wrote about in his books,

02:00:00.360 --> 02:00:05.480
[Amit Varma]: were rewarded for quote unquote kills, the more people you kill, the greater the reward. And that

02:00:05.480 --> 02:00:10.840
[Amit Varma]: led to a position where all the time repeatedly and you've of course highlighted some egregious

02:00:10.840 --> 02:00:16.280
[Amit Varma]: episodes of this, but all the time, people were being framed and killed in fake encounters

02:00:16.280 --> 02:00:21.640
[Amit Varma]: as terrorists so that people could get reward for kills in a different context in the context of

02:00:21.640 --> 02:00:27.800
[Amit Varma]: Bombay, which we'll come to after a while, you point out how where how informers were in fact

02:00:27.800 --> 02:00:33.880
[Amit Varma]: expected to radicalize young Muslims. So those young Muslims could then be picked up by the

02:00:33.880 --> 02:00:40.600
[Amit Varma]: security establishment, which is just crazy. And this is almost ubiquitous in the sense that

02:00:40.600 --> 02:00:45.320
[Amit Varma]: about Punjab, which I'd like to talk about next about Punjab, you also mentioned that a similar

02:00:45.320 --> 02:00:51.880
[Amit Varma]: incentive existed, which led to all kinds of innocent people being constantly picked up and

02:00:51.880 --> 02:00:57.080
[Amit Varma]: killed off. And this reminds me of the cobra effect, where you know, in colonial times,

02:00:57.080 --> 02:01:02.200
[Amit Varma]: the British authorities, they had a problem of too many cobras in Delhi. So they offered

02:01:02.200 --> 02:01:05.800
[Amit Varma]: incentives for getting rid of cobras, they said for every dead cobra that you bring in,

02:01:05.800 --> 02:01:10.680
[Amit Varma]: we'll pay you some money. And what happened is what you would expect people started breeding cobras

02:01:10.680 --> 02:01:15.960
[Amit Varma]: to get some of that money, then the establishment realized that this is not working out. So they

02:01:15.960 --> 02:01:21.320
[Amit Varma]: remove the reward. And then the people who were breeding cobras, let the cobras lose. And you

02:01:21.320 --> 02:01:27.480
[Amit Varma]: actually had more cobras in before. I don't know if you you'd agree that that seems to be an apt

02:01:27.480 --> 02:01:32.760
[Amit Varma]: metaphor. Yeah. So how earlier you said you were pessimistic about liberal democracy,

02:01:32.760 --> 02:01:37.480
[Amit Varma]: not just looking at the incentives of the situation here like talking, continuing on

02:01:37.480 --> 02:01:42.440
[Amit Varma]: Kashmir for a moment before we get to Punjab. You know, how could things ever get better? I mean,

02:01:42.440 --> 02:01:46.360
[Amit Varma]: were there causes of optimism? What could have reversed this? Were there efforts to

02:01:47.080 --> 02:01:51.640
[Amit Varma]: reverse this? Like you point out that, you know, you were in Kashmir for a while you met

02:01:52.760 --> 02:01:57.560
[Amit Varma]: Mr. Dar while he was, you know, negotiating for peace with India. And of course, he got brutally

02:01:57.560 --> 02:02:03.320
[Amit Varma]: murdered soon after that. And those efforts came to nothing. So does this become an inevitable

02:02:03.320 --> 02:02:08.600
[Amit Varma]: downward spiral? That once you enter this situation, where a powerful security apparatus

02:02:08.600 --> 02:02:13.880
[Amit Varma]: is given power, that, you know, in a country where there are no safeguards, where, you know,

02:02:13.880 --> 02:02:19.160
[Amit Varma]: where this kind of structure is there by design? What are your thoughts on this? Is this one of

02:02:19.160 --> 02:02:23.800
[Amit Varma]: the reasons you're pessimistic? And if so, when you speak about your wanting to write,

02:02:23.800 --> 02:02:26.920
[Amit Varma]: because writing makes a difference? Can it make a difference to this?

02:02:26.920 --> 02:02:35.400
[Guest]: The first part, which is that, can it be undone? The incentive structures, etc, etc. I think it's

02:02:35.400 --> 02:02:42.840
[Guest]: doable. Today, you know, as you know, the kills part. So militants are graded ABCD and depending

02:02:42.840 --> 02:02:48.440
[Guest]: upon the grade of militant that you kill, there are rewards available to policemen, etc. Those

02:02:48.440 --> 02:02:55.000
[Guest]: obviously that reward system has been completely corrupted also. The security agencies have built

02:02:55.000 --> 02:03:01.000
[Guest]: such complex infrastructures and power centers within Kashmir. In fact, in about 10 years ago,

02:03:01.720 --> 02:03:07.800
[Guest]: there was very credible inputs about how a section of the army was orchestrating grenade

02:03:07.800 --> 02:03:18.040
[Guest]: throwing because the violence was going down in Kashmir. So, yeah, so it can be, it can be

02:03:18.040 --> 02:03:26.040
[Guest]: dismantled. You need strong, moralistic political leadership committed to the idea of a democratic

02:03:26.040 --> 02:03:34.840
[Guest]: India, not to some fantasy of a majoritarian state, not to the fantasy of some oligarchy

02:03:34.840 --> 02:03:40.600
[Guest]: ruled country. If you are committed to liberal democratic ideas, it's a patient process,

02:03:40.600 --> 02:03:45.720
[Guest]: but it's a doable process because there are n number of examples around the world

02:03:45.720 --> 02:03:52.360
[Guest]: where you have seen corrupted democracies. For example, in the US, the Gilded Age gave way to

02:03:52.360 --> 02:03:58.840
[Guest]: a liberal democratic phase. In the UK, you have had insurgencies, the Irish rebels bombing London

02:03:58.840 --> 02:04:04.680
[Guest]: and other places. You have seen n number of such cases. So it's not that democracies can't mature,

02:04:05.400 --> 02:04:10.120
[Guest]: but that maturing of democracy is not achieved through elections. It is achieved through

02:04:10.120 --> 02:04:18.120
[Guest]: the emergence of leaders who are committed to democratic ideals. And that is where my,

02:04:19.400 --> 02:04:24.360
[Guest]: that's a cause of, one of the cause of my pessimism because even leaders who have emerged

02:04:24.360 --> 02:04:29.880
[Guest]: in recent times do not give me the hope of democracy because they all turned out to be

02:04:30.680 --> 02:04:38.120
[Guest]: little people in pursuit of power, pretending to be Gandhi, but deep inside, very small minded men

02:04:38.120 --> 02:04:44.280
[Guest]: are stuck on petty power. So that's a cause of pessimism, but to answer your question,

02:04:44.280 --> 02:04:49.640
[Guest]: it can be dismantled. It's doable. Countries have done it. Come to the second question,

02:04:49.640 --> 02:04:53.160
[Guest]: whether writing makes an impact. Writing is the only thing that will make impact.

02:04:54.440 --> 02:04:58.680
[Guest]: Writing is what will trigger revolutions. Writing is what will get people on the streets. Writing

02:04:58.680 --> 02:05:05.960
[Guest]: is what will cause protests. Writing is what will make people think. Writing is what will

02:05:05.960 --> 02:05:12.040
[Guest]: make people talk loudly in the public square. You know what I'm saying?

02:05:12.920 --> 02:05:16.360
[Amit Varma]: I absolutely know what you're saying. And it is so inspiring, writing and

02:05:16.920 --> 02:05:21.240
[Amit Varma]: podcasting, who knows? But you know, just to push back on the earlier question, like one,

02:05:21.240 --> 02:05:25.640
[Amit Varma]: I would argue that, or rather, I have a question like the examples you pointed to

02:05:25.640 --> 02:05:29.400
[Amit Varma]: are kind of different. They don't have to do with the structure of the state. Like sure,

02:05:29.400 --> 02:05:33.560
[Amit Varma]: you know, the Irish problem is a political problem. I agree that political problems

02:05:33.560 --> 02:05:39.800
[Amit Varma]: are solvable over a period of time, if there is will. And also there is, one can imagine incentives

02:05:39.800 --> 02:05:45.000
[Amit Varma]: for the politicians to solve those problems, you know, all of that. But here, the problem that we

02:05:45.000 --> 02:05:51.160
[Amit Varma]: have is a classic problem of a state becoming more and more powerful and bigger and bigger,

02:05:51.160 --> 02:05:56.120
[Amit Varma]: which states tend to do, power constantly corrupting, and you enter this kind of a vicious

02:05:56.120 --> 02:06:01.240
[Amit Varma]: cycle. Is there anywhere in the world where something like that has changed, where an

02:06:01.240 --> 02:06:07.720
[Amit Varma]: autocratic state has actually been reined in using democratic methods, like not a war or a

02:06:07.720 --> 02:06:12.040
[Amit Varma]: coup or whatever? Can you think of an example where that has actually happened?

02:06:12.600 --> 02:06:18.280
[Guest]: I'm not a historian. So I don't know whether I would be able to give an appropriate example.

02:06:19.640 --> 02:06:27.640
[Guest]: But I would say that what the US saw in the last century, if you take the pre Second World War

02:06:27.640 --> 02:06:32.760
[Guest]: period, and what happened later, there are a lot of parallels to what's happening in India.

02:06:34.200 --> 02:06:43.240
[Guest]: So there were robber barons, there was, the church had more political influence, probably.

02:06:44.600 --> 02:06:45.720
[Guest]: So there have been changes.

02:06:45.720 --> 02:06:48.920
[Amit Varma]: But that didn't have anything to do with the structure of the state.

02:06:50.360 --> 02:06:55.720
[Guest]: Yeah, that is true. Structure of the state. So you know, our problem is that problem that

02:06:55.720 --> 02:07:04.520
[Guest]: you're pointing out is not a problem that can't be solved. The state becoming more and more

02:07:04.520 --> 02:07:11.720
[Guest]: powerful, the powerful state can be dismantled in favour of a more republic, more liberal state,

02:07:11.720 --> 02:07:18.520
[Guest]: a republic state, is a doable process, if you have strong leaderships at both at the political

02:07:18.520 --> 02:07:25.160
[Guest]: level and judiciary level and even media. Right now, we are living through an era of big

02:07:25.160 --> 02:07:33.000
[Guest]: of pygmies. And so it looks very intimidating to dismantle the powerful state sector. Right.

02:07:33.880 --> 02:07:38.280
[Guest]: But when giants come, it won't be impossible is my take.

02:07:38.280 --> 02:07:42.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, my, my pushback on that is that we are living in an age of pygmies, because the

02:07:42.360 --> 02:07:47.400
[Amit Varma]: incentives are designed to produce pygmies, like you're speaking of an entitled, moralistic

02:07:47.400 --> 02:07:51.640
[Amit Varma]: leadership, those kind of people won't even enter politics to begin with, because it's pointless.

02:07:51.640 --> 02:07:55.800
[Amit Varma]: And if they do enter politics, you know, they'll get corroded by the process till none of the

02:07:55.800 --> 02:08:00.360
[Amit Varma]: moralism actually remains by the time they get to wherever they want to get to. It's all,

02:08:00.360 --> 02:08:06.280
[Amit Varma]: it's all signalling and posturing. By that point, I think the giants are more in other areas,

02:08:06.280 --> 02:08:11.800
[Amit Varma]: like writing the area that you are in politics, I think will, you know, so it just feels like a

02:08:11.800 --> 02:08:17.480
[Amit Varma]: vicious circle to me for that reason. But you know, equally, what makes me positive sometimes

02:08:17.480 --> 02:08:22.280
[Amit Varma]: is that technology can empower individuals. So who knows what will happen in the future. But as of

02:08:22.280 --> 02:08:26.840
[Amit Varma]: now, if the system is to be changed, it can only be changed by those who are benefiting the most

02:08:26.840 --> 02:08:32.360
[Amit Varma]: from it. So why would they change it? So we get caught in this kind of complicated...

02:08:32.360 --> 02:08:38.840
[Guest]: Ah, but, but Amit, history is not a logical moment, no? History is a lot of accidents and

02:08:38.840 --> 02:08:46.440
[Guest]: incidents. So did you, 20 years ago, did you think that there could be an Indian who will donate

02:08:46.440 --> 02:08:51.880
[Guest]: most of his life saving, which is substantially more than what we can imagine? Somebody like a

02:08:51.880 --> 02:08:58.120
[Amit Varma]: Premji would come along? I would actually assume that someone like a Premji would inevitably come

02:08:58.120 --> 02:09:03.000
[Amit Varma]: along in private life, because there have been examples like that in public life, including some

02:09:03.000 --> 02:09:08.680
[Amit Varma]: of the robber barons that you mentioned earlier, say someone like Rockefeller. But I would not

02:09:08.680 --> 02:09:15.320
[Amit Varma]: imagine that kind of a public spirit in government, in politics, which is where I'm happy to be proved

02:09:15.320 --> 02:09:23.480
[Guest]: wrong if it ever happens, which is... No, I'll come to you, Amit. In 2009, I used to be taunted

02:09:23.480 --> 02:09:28.600
[Guest]: by my bosses saying that, what corruption stories are you bringing? Who is interested? Right? I would

02:09:28.600 --> 02:09:34.040
[Guest]: bring some scams, some allegations, you know, some audit report. They would all say that nobody's

02:09:34.040 --> 02:09:41.000
[Guest]: interested in these stories. And they were true, because no, it triggered nothing. 2G scam had

02:09:41.000 --> 02:09:49.880
[Guest]: happened in 2008. But by 2010, this country went into a different frenzy, that you had millions of

02:09:49.880 --> 02:09:56.040
[Guest]: middle class people out on the streets, the same or many of them today who are communal, who are

02:09:56.040 --> 02:09:59.800
[Guest]: supporting a majoritarian state, they were out on the streets demanding, I mean, they didn't know

02:09:59.800 --> 02:10:06.120
[Guest]: what Lokmahal meant, but they were already a corruption free society. Right? And, and mind you,

02:10:06.120 --> 02:10:11.720
[Guest]: if you look at Aam Aadmi Party, I mean, I'm not a supporter of the party, but the time from within

02:10:11.720 --> 02:10:17.080
[Guest]: which a very powerful political movement emerged is unbelievable. Right? You own very little

02:10:17.080 --> 02:10:25.480
[Guest]: resources. You cannot rule out the happenstance that future holds and potentials. Let's not

02:10:25.480 --> 02:10:32.600
[Guest]: underestimate, see, India, despite all of Modi's efforts, India still has a very vibrant civil

02:10:32.600 --> 02:10:40.360
[Guest]: society. And on a bad day, not even bad day, on a normal day for decades, Indian democracy has

02:10:40.360 --> 02:10:46.120
[Guest]: been held on the shoulders, has been carried forward by few individuals, spirited lawyers,

02:10:46.120 --> 02:10:51.560
[Guest]: some journalists, some activists. That's a reality, because our institutions have not been

02:10:51.560 --> 02:10:57.400
[Guest]: maturing enough. Well, so you can never predict what could be in the store. So that is optimism

02:10:57.400 --> 02:11:03.800
[Guest]: with which I write. And I talk because we are writing against people who might have a lot of

02:11:03.800 --> 02:11:10.520
[Guest]: power today. But I know that if they were to misuse the power beyond a point, the very people

02:11:10.520 --> 02:11:16.120
[Amit Varma]: who are supporting them will rise up in revolt. Yeah, and that's a great point about civil society.

02:11:16.120 --> 02:11:19.800
[Amit Varma]: And indeed, one of the, possibly the highlight of the last two years, which have been a very

02:11:19.800 --> 02:11:23.800
[Amit Varma]: dismal time, but the highlight of the last two years in terms of what's been happening in the

02:11:23.800 --> 02:11:28.680
[Amit Varma]: public space is how civil society protested against NRC, you know, where you had young

02:11:28.680 --> 02:11:32.840
[Amit Varma]: people across the country coming out and waving the preamble, like who would have thunk though,

02:11:32.840 --> 02:11:36.680
[Amit Varma]: I wish it was the Ambedkar version of the preamble and not the Indira Gandhi version,

02:11:36.680 --> 02:11:40.680
[Amit Varma]: with the toxic word socialism thrown in with all its state coercion and all of that.

02:11:40.680 --> 02:11:46.920
[Amit Varma]: But regardless, that's still heartening. So hopefully, things change. Let's talk about

02:11:46.920 --> 02:11:53.400
[Amit Varma]: Punjab now. Because in a sense, what unfolded later in Kashmir in terms of what the security

02:11:53.400 --> 02:11:58.280
[Amit Varma]: establishment did and the lessons it learned was something that you also see mirrored in the

02:11:58.280 --> 02:12:04.520
[Amit Varma]: Punjab problem, where it is actually Indira Gandhi after losing the elections post the emergency

02:12:04.520 --> 02:12:09.160
[Amit Varma]: realizes that the party is doing really badly in Congress, they are coming third there, they need

02:12:09.160 --> 02:12:14.280
[Amit Varma]: someone to, you know, counteract the Kali Dal. And Sanjay Gandhi, you mentioned in your book

02:12:14.280 --> 02:12:19.240
[Amit Varma]: meets with a couple of potential candidates, the first one doesn't look fierce enough.

02:12:19.240 --> 02:12:24.920
[Amit Varma]: So he eventually chooses Bhindranwale. So Bhindranwale was really therefore a creation

02:12:24.920 --> 02:12:29.960
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, arose out of a political imperative, and was then given shape by the

02:12:29.960 --> 02:12:36.920
[Amit Varma]: security establishment and protected by it till it got to a point where the incentives diverged.

02:12:36.920 --> 02:12:42.200
[Amit Varma]: And you also point out, for example, how Bhindranwale did his first killing of a newspaper

02:12:42.200 --> 02:12:47.640
[Amit Varma]: publisher, he was actually protected for a while by Gyanizal Singh, who would go on to become

02:12:47.640 --> 02:12:52.760
[Amit Varma]: India's president. And once said that he would clean toilets for Indira Gandhi if he was asked to

02:12:52.760 --> 02:12:59.960
[Amit Varma]: and Bhajan Lal, the Chief Minister of Haryana. So tell me a bit about that sort of period and

02:12:59.960 --> 02:13:04.600
[Amit Varma]: the lessons we learned like the 80s old fascinating lessons. It's really interesting that,

02:13:04.600 --> 02:13:09.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, both Indira and Rajiv, in a sense were killed by monsters that they created.

02:13:09.240 --> 02:13:13.240
[Amit Varma]: In Rajiv's case, of course, the monster was partly created by his mother as well.

02:13:13.240 --> 02:13:18.280
[Amit Varma]: But the Bhindranwale monster was created by Indira, the LTTE around the same time,

02:13:18.280 --> 02:13:24.120
[Amit Varma]: late 70s was propped up by the security establishment, and so on. So tell me a bit

02:13:24.120 --> 02:13:29.480
[Amit Varma]: about that period, and especially from the prism that is there in your book of watching

02:13:29.480 --> 02:13:36.200
[Amit Varma]: the security establishment at play and what those events reveal about it, and how those lessons

02:13:36.200 --> 02:13:40.520
[Amit Varma]: then go on to, you know, the 87 elections in Kashmir and what happens next.

02:13:41.560 --> 02:13:49.240
[Guest]: See, one of the worst things about Indira Gandhi, if I may say, was that she did not look across

02:13:49.240 --> 02:13:54.600
[Guest]: to Pakistan and draw the right lessons. There already was enough lessons about the monsters

02:13:54.600 --> 02:14:00.680
[Guest]: rising, how when the states are creating militants, terrorists, etc. for state purpose, it will

02:14:00.680 --> 02:14:08.440
[Guest]: devour the state itself. And she made these mistakes. And if you really look at it impartially,

02:14:09.320 --> 02:14:15.400
[Guest]: in many ways, she is responsible for her own killings and her son's killings. So beyond a

02:14:15.400 --> 02:14:22.600
[Guest]: point in an Asian state, armed insurgencies, if they become part of the state tool, then it is

02:14:22.600 --> 02:14:29.080
[Guest]: going to have disastrous consequences. And we played with it in the 70s and 80s. And Kanjab

02:14:29.080 --> 02:14:34.600
[Guest]: problem, if you look at it, while there have been, you know, all kinds of disgruntlement in Punjab

02:14:34.600 --> 02:14:42.920
[Guest]: since the 47 Akali issue, etc. If Bindranwale was not propped up and provided the resources that

02:14:42.920 --> 02:14:47.480
[Guest]: the Congress provided and the support provided, we would not have had an Operation Blue Star.

02:14:47.480 --> 02:14:51.640
[Guest]: We probably would not have had the assassination of Indira Gandhi. And we would not have had the

02:14:51.640 --> 02:14:58.920
[Guest]: anti-Muslim pogrom. And India would have been a much more liberal, safer place. All of this

02:14:58.920 --> 02:15:07.240
[Guest]: happened because of a very nasty, short-sighted pursuit of power in Punjab. And not for nationally,

02:15:07.240 --> 02:15:13.800
[Guest]: just for a state. And see what it came up with. And when it began to get out of hand,

02:15:14.680 --> 02:15:20.600
[Guest]: what does the state do? State securitize the problem. You deploy policemen with,

02:15:20.600 --> 02:15:27.000
[Guest]: and military for a short while, but policemen with all kinds of power saying that go, kill,

02:15:27.000 --> 02:15:34.760
[Guest]: kidnap, rape, do what you want, but I want peace. That's not peace. That's thagari, that is cruelty,

02:15:34.760 --> 02:15:42.040
[Guest]: that is murder, that's killing. So, you blessed a generation of policemen out there to become

02:15:42.040 --> 02:15:47.800
[Guest]: state-sponsored killers. And vicious cycle that continues to play even today. Even today,

02:15:47.800 --> 02:15:53.000
[Guest]: thousands of families in Punjab and abroad, meaning Sikhs, they don't know where their

02:15:53.000 --> 02:15:57.960
[Guest]: dear ones are. People have just disappeared because police has kidnapped and killed and

02:15:57.960 --> 02:16:04.520
[Guest]: tortured and militants killed on the other side. But the discussion cannot be drawing a parity

02:16:04.520 --> 02:16:09.320
[Guest]: between the militants and police. So, what militants are killing, so we will also kill. No,

02:16:09.320 --> 02:16:15.320
[Guest]: militants are militants. They are criminals. They are not the state. The state has a paratus which

02:16:15.320 --> 02:16:21.640
[Guest]: is bound by written constitution and its laws. And we violated it. And Indira Gandhi, in her

02:16:21.640 --> 02:16:26.600
[Guest]: whatever strategic vision it was, she empowered, created the LTT out there and other Tamil

02:16:26.600 --> 02:16:33.720
[Guest]: militants in Sri Lanka. That also had such blowback on India. And look at the cumulative

02:16:33.720 --> 02:16:42.360
[Guest]: effect of such short-sighted decisions of that era that not only do we have Rajiv Gandhi being

02:16:42.360 --> 02:16:49.000
[Guest]: assassinated by LTT, we also have a military disaster in Sri Lanka. And at the end of it,

02:16:49.000 --> 02:16:55.640
[Guest]: you have thousands of Tamils butchered in a modern world. And you see the rise of another

02:16:57.160 --> 02:17:05.160
[Guest]: strong family in Sri Lanka which is completely scuttling democracy. So, India, unless we do

02:17:05.160 --> 02:17:13.960
[Guest]: very honest introspection of how our political politicians have been and continues to use

02:17:13.960 --> 02:17:23.400
[Guest]: use state power and violence as a means to further their power, we will not be able to move into a

02:17:23.400 --> 02:17:29.000
[Guest]: mature democracy. And I say this being very conscious of what's happening today and what

02:17:29.000 --> 02:17:35.720
[Amit Varma]: the arc of Narendra Modi also tells us. One of the sort of stories I was very struck by

02:17:35.720 --> 02:17:40.680
[Amit Varma]: and someone who also must have been inspiring to you for not investigative journalism per se,

02:17:40.680 --> 02:17:46.200
[Amit Varma]: but a kind of investigative zeal is Jaswant Singh Khalra, who I hadn't heard of again

02:17:46.200 --> 02:17:50.120
[Amit Varma]: till your book and what a remarkable story. Tell me a little bit about him.

02:17:51.320 --> 02:17:57.560
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, in fact, of all the people that I have written about, he's probably the most

02:17:57.560 --> 02:18:03.320
[Guest]: fascinating and one of the most saddest stories because he came from this famed family. His

02:18:03.320 --> 02:18:09.960
[Guest]: grandfather was a freedom fighter, etc. And he is the one who actually, in a systematic manner

02:18:09.960 --> 02:18:18.280
[Guest]: uncovers the police brutality in Punjab. And what he does is he goes around collecting details of

02:18:19.080 --> 02:18:26.200
[Guest]: firewood that is given for funeral pyres. And it is a licensed government thing. So

02:18:26.200 --> 02:18:31.640
[Guest]: there is a logging happening at some end for firewood that is wood that is given for funeral

02:18:31.640 --> 02:18:38.840
[Guest]: pyres. And using that he proves that the number of people cremated in districts like Amritsar

02:18:38.840 --> 02:18:44.600
[Guest]: and present-day Taran-Taran are several times more than what was officially being recorded.

02:18:45.320 --> 02:18:52.600
[Guest]: And he, from there, he starts recording the brutality of the state police and the encounter

02:18:52.600 --> 02:18:58.840
[Guest]: killings and the disappearances. And he becomes so powerful that KPS Gill, then the police,

02:18:58.840 --> 02:19:02.440
[Guest]: he comes down to Amritsar to challenge him for public debate, this, that, what,

02:19:02.440 --> 02:19:06.680
[Guest]: what. But Khalra is not intimidated because he is cut from a different kind of cloth.

02:19:06.680 --> 02:19:12.920
[Guest]: And he continues to record 2-3 thousand disappearances of cases. And finally the

02:19:12.920 --> 02:19:20.760
[Guest]: police got so irritated with him that they just kidnapped him. And he has also disappeared.

02:19:21.800 --> 02:19:31.160
[Guest]: So, his legacy continued. And during the time he has been kidnapped,

02:19:31.160 --> 02:19:36.360
[Guest]: the Supreme Court takes notice of it and there are efforts, but the state government and the

02:19:36.360 --> 02:19:43.480
[Guest]: police lies to the Supreme Court. And Khalra is killed meanwhile. But his findings have found

02:19:43.480 --> 02:19:49.880
[Guest]: judicial approval. But that has not brought justice to Punjab because at various stages in the

02:19:49.880 --> 02:19:56.120
[Guest]: National Human Rights Commission, even Supreme Court, justice has been watered away. And because

02:19:56.120 --> 02:20:03.960
[Guest]: ultimately in India, we do not believe in individual liberties, individual rights. So,

02:20:03.960 --> 02:20:07.800
[Guest]: it has been watered away. Even today, there are thousands of families in Punjab who are

02:20:07.800 --> 02:20:13.160
[Guest]: looking for their dear ones, something to know about it. But it was Khalra who actually

02:20:13.160 --> 02:20:18.040
[Guest]: triggered that fight back. And that is what I was saying that history is very, very,

02:20:18.840 --> 02:20:23.800
[Guest]: you cannot say, if you had met Khalra as a young man, probably you would not predict that this man

02:20:23.800 --> 02:20:31.640
[Guest]: could shake up the entire Punjab story. And even today, there are youngsters, young lawyers I know,

02:20:31.640 --> 02:20:38.920
[Guest]: who are carrying on with Khalra's fight. Very smart lawyers. So, it is a long drawn battle.

02:20:39.560 --> 02:20:43.160
[Guest]: It is like the Bhopal gas tragedy. The fighters live on, they are there,

02:20:43.160 --> 02:20:48.280
[Guest]: they continue to fight. We may not know their fight. So, I am not an expert on Khalra or Punjab.

02:20:48.280 --> 02:20:52.120
[Guest]: I just came across his story and I said, oh, this fits into what I have been saying.

02:20:52.120 --> 02:20:57.560
[Guest]: So, I read about him and wrote about him. I wish I had known about him much long ago. I mean,

02:20:57.560 --> 02:21:01.000
[Guest]: I wish I had met him because he would have been such an inspirational figure. I mean,

02:21:01.000 --> 02:21:07.080
[Guest]: what a smart investigative strategy to go looking for the wood that is used for fires.

02:21:07.640 --> 02:21:13.400
[Guest]: I mean, which policeman would think that his crime would be captured in a log kept

02:21:13.960 --> 02:21:20.760
[Guest]: on the wood that is supplied? I mean, to me, it is like the highest standards,

02:21:20.760 --> 02:21:23.560
[Guest]: the gold standard of investigative journalism or investigations.

02:21:24.520 --> 02:21:29.960
[Guest]: So, he is, yeah, I mean, but all of it is a tragedy. He was also killed. But the man,

02:21:30.520 --> 02:21:34.280
[Guest]: yeah, man accused of killing him, the police officer, he finally committed suicide.

02:21:35.160 --> 02:21:38.600
[Amit Varma]: So, all sides pays. Yeah, but I mean, that's a scant

02:21:38.600 --> 02:21:43.240
[Amit Varma]: consolation. No, but it's a kind of good story that could so easily be made into a film or a

02:21:43.240 --> 02:21:47.960
[Amit Varma]: web series that, you know, you have these incentives where they are being rewarded

02:21:47.960 --> 02:21:52.600
[Amit Varma]: for killing terrorists. So, you assume that they must be killing lots of innocent people,

02:21:52.600 --> 02:21:55.480
[Amit Varma]: but how the hell do you prove it? Then you figure out that, wait a second,

02:21:55.480 --> 02:22:00.440
[Amit Varma]: the police has to cremate these people for which they have to buy wood. And then he goes off and

02:22:00.440 --> 02:22:05.240
[Amit Varma]: then he, you know, does an audit of all the firewood sold in the state and he calculates

02:22:05.240 --> 02:22:10.440
[Amit Varma]: so many thousands of people have been killed. And then eventually he is abducted by the police,

02:22:10.440 --> 02:22:17.160
[Amit Varma]: tortured, killed, chopped up, and the body parts thrown in the Sutlej. Absolutely crazy story. And

02:22:17.160 --> 02:22:21.560
[Amit Varma]: you also point out that this is not really an outlier. It's probably an outlier in terms of

02:22:21.560 --> 02:22:26.200
[Amit Varma]: the ingenuity, but how activists were treated. Very much par for the course. You speak about

02:22:26.200 --> 02:22:33.480
[Amit Varma]: people like Ram Singh Billing, Ajit Singh Bans, Param Satyajit Singh, Malvinder Singh Malli,

02:22:33.480 --> 02:22:39.960
[Amit Varma]: Jagvinder Singh. And these are like lawyers. These are people you would imagine would have some kind

02:22:39.960 --> 02:22:45.080
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, influence or ways of protecting themselves or whatever. But, you know, they all

02:22:45.080 --> 02:22:51.720
[Guest]: disappear and this is all just par for the course. And what happens? Yeah, the Punjabis and Punjab

02:22:51.720 --> 02:22:57.000
[Guest]: and Kashmir and Nagaland, etc. are all the same story. I mean, you know, the state let the security

02:22:57.000 --> 02:23:02.440
[Guest]: apparatus go berserk. And policemen thought they are the state and they behaved like one.

02:23:02.440 --> 02:23:07.000
[Guest]: They just became killer squads. And it continues. It continues even today.

02:23:08.200 --> 02:23:11.160
[Guest]: It has not gotten away. I mean, it needs to end somewhere.

02:23:11.160 --> 02:23:15.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, maybe not in terms of killing, but what we see with Bhima Koregaon case,

02:23:15.400 --> 02:23:19.720
[Amit Varma]: which you've also written about so eloquently in your last chapter, and you know, and some

02:23:19.720 --> 02:23:25.000
[Amit Varma]: could argue what happened to Stan Swamy is an extrajudicial killing. So, you know, now tell

02:23:25.000 --> 02:23:30.840
[Amit Varma]: me a little bit about Rajiv Gandhi's approach, because Rajiv takes power and he's this callow

02:23:30.840 --> 02:23:37.320
[Amit Varma]: young man, perhaps drunk on power to some extent. And there are just so many in different contexts,

02:23:37.320 --> 02:23:42.360
[Amit Varma]: so many political missteps that he takes, which prove disastrous. But one of them, of course,

02:23:42.360 --> 02:23:48.280
[Amit Varma]: is the whole IPKF thing, which is a classic example of how, you know, if you create a monster,

02:23:48.280 --> 02:23:52.680
[Amit Varma]: you don't know if you can control it. And I wonder if that even has current resonance,

02:23:52.680 --> 02:23:58.120
[Amit Varma]: like you mentioned how, you know, both Indira and Rajiv were killed by monsters created in a sense

02:23:58.120 --> 02:24:03.480
[Amit Varma]: by Indira. And I wonder how that applies to current day leaders and the monsters that they create?

02:24:03.480 --> 02:24:08.520
[Amit Varma]: Can you control them? Where does it all end? And when I see political leaders pandering to all

02:24:08.520 --> 02:24:13.640
[Amit Varma]: these extreme emotions, it just feels that, you know, they haven't really learned the lessons

02:24:13.640 --> 02:24:19.160
[Amit Varma]: of history either. So tell me a little bit about all of that, because one of the striking features

02:24:19.160 --> 02:24:25.160
[Amit Varma]: of that whole IPKF misadventure, where basically for listeners who might not be aware, Rajiv did

02:24:25.160 --> 02:24:30.680
[Amit Varma]: a deal with the Sri Lankan government that, hey, we'll send the Indian Peacekeeping Force, IPKF,

02:24:30.680 --> 02:24:36.040
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, we'll send our military and we'll take care of your Tamil extremism problem for you.

02:24:36.040 --> 02:24:39.720
[Amit Varma]: And of course, the Tamil extremism problem was created by India in the first place.

02:24:39.720 --> 02:24:45.720
[Amit Varma]: And all the security forces told their political overlords that, listen, we created them,

02:24:45.720 --> 02:24:49.960
[Amit Varma]: we tell them to put down arms, they will put down arms. And then they go there and they find that

02:24:49.960 --> 02:24:54.280
[Amit Varma]: it's a completely different story. This is another monster they can't control. Tell me a bit about

02:24:54.280 --> 02:25:03.480
[Guest]: that period. To me, the story of Prabhakaran and Rajiv is very interesting, right? One is a

02:25:03.480 --> 02:25:10.440
[Guest]: political princeling. And the other is a romantic who left studies midways and become a militant.

02:25:10.440 --> 02:25:15.240
[Guest]: And for a short while, they were friends. Prabhakaran was actually flown to Delhi.

02:25:15.240 --> 02:25:21.560
[Guest]: And if I'm not wrong, it's Rahul Gandhi who carries his father's Rajiv Gandhi's bulletproof

02:25:21.560 --> 02:25:27.640
[Guest]: jacket, which Rajiv Gandhi gives to Prabhakaran. And Prabhakaran comes back to Jaffna. By the time

02:25:27.640 --> 02:25:34.280
[Guest]: IPKF has landed, IPKF flown in from Hyderabad. So, the GOC of the division told me they went with

02:25:34.280 --> 02:25:39.720
[Guest]: tourist maps of Jaffna. He said, I sent my soldiers out to Hyderabad market to buy

02:25:39.720 --> 02:25:45.720
[Guest]: tourist maps of Sri Lanka. That is how well prepared they were. Anyway, they land up there

02:25:45.720 --> 02:25:53.000
[Guest]: and they thought that Prabhakaran can be bullied around. And they told him to lay down arms

02:25:53.640 --> 02:26:00.280
[Guest]: and as agreed. And one leads to the other and within months, the Rajiv-Prabhakaran friendship

02:26:00.280 --> 02:26:08.440
[Guest]: collapses. And Rajiv sends one of the world's most powerful militaries on an operation, which

02:26:08.440 --> 02:26:12.600
[Guest]: is probably the most dramatic military operation of recent memories. I can't think of another

02:26:12.600 --> 02:26:18.840
[Guest]: operation anywhere in the world. The operation to capture Prabhakaran and his LTT leadership from

02:26:18.840 --> 02:26:25.400
[Guest]: Jaffna University. You have the commando raid and as the helicopter lands, the LTT is waiting

02:26:25.400 --> 02:26:30.520
[Guest]: for them because I think LTT was listening into the radio communication. And the troops that are

02:26:30.520 --> 02:26:37.320
[Guest]: moving on ground towards Jaffna, they encounter all kinds of obstacles. And some of them are

02:26:37.320 --> 02:26:45.160
[Guest]: taken for a ride by Tamils. Many of them are met with children and women providing cover to LTT

02:26:45.160 --> 02:26:50.920
[Guest]: militants at the hospital, in a civil hospital there in Jaffna. Whatever may happen, Indian

02:26:50.920 --> 02:26:56.360
[Guest]: military says, militants fired from inside the hospital, but for the next two days, they will

02:26:56.360 --> 02:27:03.880
[Guest]: preserve their butcher people. Finally, it's Black Hawk down 10 times bigger. When Prabhakaran

02:27:03.880 --> 02:27:10.040
[Guest]: disappears from there, leaves behind at the football ground, if I'm not wrong, just one

02:27:10.040 --> 02:27:14.280
[Guest]: injured Indian soldier. He said, let him be alive so that he can go back and tell his masters what

02:27:14.280 --> 02:27:20.520
[Guest]: I'm capable of. And Prabhakaran digs down and stays underground for the next several years,

02:27:20.520 --> 02:27:27.400
[Guest]: plotting his way back and he gets Rajiv. So that's it. So even the greatest military

02:27:27.400 --> 02:27:32.520
[Guest]: is not capable of solving a political problem. It has to be a political solution.

02:27:32.520 --> 02:27:39.720
[Guest]: That's a big takeaway for me in the story. And Prabhakaran craves by power. And once you test

02:27:39.720 --> 02:27:45.560
[Guest]: violence, you can never give it up. You can't become... People might say that every saint has

02:27:45.560 --> 02:27:52.200
[Guest]: a past and every criminal has a future and all that, but he couldn't give up. By the mid of 2000s,

02:27:52.760 --> 02:27:58.360
[Guest]: he could have had an autonomous Northeast region. Everything was in his favor. And people like

02:27:58.360 --> 02:28:03.720
[Guest]: Anton Balasingham actually told him, let's buy this space. Let's have an autonomous region. No,

02:28:03.720 --> 02:28:12.280
[Guest]: he has to fight for freedom. He has to create his country and he also ends up dead in a backwater,

02:28:12.280 --> 02:28:22.680
[Guest]: in a lake. So Rajiv Gandhi, in his brashness as a young Prime Minister, he goes into Sri Lanka,

02:28:22.680 --> 02:28:29.320
[Guest]: sends military into Sri Lanka for nothing and pays for it with his life. And parallelly

02:28:30.360 --> 02:28:38.360
[Guest]: in Kashmir with Farooq Abdullah, he lets Farooq have a field day in Kashmir and they manipulate

02:28:38.360 --> 02:28:43.720
[Guest]: elections and Kashmir erupts in violence and the violence continues till date. So,

02:28:44.440 --> 02:28:50.280
[Guest]: legacy of Rajiv Gandhi, while there are a lot of good things we can talk about him and he truly

02:28:50.280 --> 02:28:56.520
[Guest]: had a very visionary idea for India, but practically on ground, he messed up the Indian

02:28:56.520 --> 02:29:03.320
[Amit Varma]: democracy project big time. Very true. And the 87 elections, as you've pointed out, was rigged so

02:29:03.320 --> 02:29:09.480
[Amit Varma]: blatantly that an entire generation of militants were created from there. You mentioned people

02:29:09.480 --> 02:29:15.960
[Amit Varma]: like Saeed Salahuddin, Saeed Ali Shah Jilani, Yasin Malik, Javed Mir, Shabbir Shah's brother,

02:29:15.960 --> 02:29:21.160
[Amit Varma]: Mohammed Saeed Shah. They were all taking part in the elections, trying to be part of the democratic

02:29:21.160 --> 02:29:25.160
[Amit Varma]: process. But once the whole thing was rigged, they said, forget it. We're not going to get

02:29:25.160 --> 02:29:29.640
[Amit Varma]: anything done this way. And of course, one can imagine why they thought that way. It was rational.

02:29:29.640 --> 02:29:36.680
[Amit Varma]: And so they go into militancy and everything kind of gradually begins to go to hell. So that's one

02:29:36.680 --> 02:29:42.200
[Amit Varma]: interesting strand there. Let's move back. There are really two more places I want to talk about

02:29:42.200 --> 02:29:46.840
[Amit Varma]: where you've got interesting narratives in your book. And I'll save Gujarat for last, because I

02:29:46.840 --> 02:29:51.640
[Amit Varma]: think that that narrative of the Gujarat model, as it were, of the security establishment is

02:29:51.640 --> 02:29:56.360
[Amit Varma]: something that has great resonance for what is happening right now at a national level. So we'll

02:29:56.360 --> 02:30:02.680
[Amit Varma]: save that for last. But tell me a little bit about Mumbai. You know, the first big section of your

02:30:02.680 --> 02:30:07.960
[Amit Varma]: book, which could have been a book in itself, absolutely gripping section, is about Mumbai,

02:30:07.960 --> 02:30:13.640
[Amit Varma]: is about, you know, this friend that you made there called Wahid, you know, and there is so much

02:30:14.200 --> 02:30:18.600
[Amit Varma]: happening there. So how did you, like what you have done in that interesting section

02:30:18.600 --> 02:30:24.760
[Amit Varma]: is in a very novelistic way, you've interspersed a personal narrative of this person called Wahid

02:30:24.760 --> 02:30:29.560
[Amit Varma]: and made him such a flesh and blood, real life figure that the reader empathizes with,

02:30:29.560 --> 02:30:35.480
[Amit Varma]: and tied in the rest of the narrative of whatever is happening with the legit terrorism that is

02:30:35.480 --> 02:30:40.840
[Amit Varma]: there with the security establishment doing all the nonsense that it is doing with not only the

02:30:40.840 --> 02:30:45.800
[Amit Varma]: way they fight the legit terrorism, but also the way they keep kind of framing people and

02:30:45.800 --> 02:30:52.600
[Amit Varma]: victimizing poor Muslims like Wahid himself. It's really interesting. So how did all of this begin

02:30:52.600 --> 02:30:57.960
[Amit Varma]: to take shape in your mind? And when did you sort of come to the conclusion that

02:30:57.960 --> 02:31:02.840
[Amit Varma]: this is a major story that what is happening in Mumbai, the framing of these people, the way

02:31:02.840 --> 02:31:08.680
[Amit Varma]: the security establishment kind of has been working here, you know, tell me about your

02:31:08.680 --> 02:31:14.760
[Amit Varma]: impetus of looking deeper into that. And was this perhaps the first instance of when you

02:31:14.760 --> 02:31:20.120
[Amit Varma]: really got to see the depths of depravity that the security establishment can fall prey to?

02:31:21.320 --> 02:31:29.560
[Guest]: So when I began my book, Wahid was not a big subject of my book. I was looking at writing

02:31:29.560 --> 02:31:35.320
[Guest]: about the business of terror is that and I started research. So in fact, my original

02:31:35.320 --> 02:31:41.560
[Guest]: chapterization is the book was in the reverse. It begins with Kashmir and Wahid was the second part.

02:31:42.680 --> 02:31:51.320
[Guest]: It was editor Ajitha who said that let's reverse it. See, being a beat reporter, I knew that in

02:31:51.320 --> 02:31:56.760
[Guest]: 2006 when the train bomb blast happened, the claims made by the ATS of Maharashtra

02:31:56.760 --> 02:32:06.280
[Guest]: was completely fake and false. And as a reporter, I also knew that later the real terrorists,

02:32:06.280 --> 02:32:11.320
[Guest]: Indian Mujahideen terrorists were caught and they had owned up to the bombings.

02:32:12.520 --> 02:32:17.880
[Guest]: So I knew that I'm going to talk about it. But what I did not realize was that Wahid and his

02:32:17.880 --> 02:32:25.400
[Guest]: other co-accused have filed copious amounts of documents in the trial court detailing the

02:32:25.400 --> 02:32:31.480
[Guest]: torture that they went through, detailing the depravity of the Indian security establishment.

02:32:32.120 --> 02:32:38.680
[Guest]: Because I think at some level they were innocent probably or they were very committed jihadis.

02:32:39.240 --> 02:32:45.720
[Guest]: Whatever it is, they showed great trust, faith and courage in the judiciary of India. And that's

02:32:45.720 --> 02:32:49.960
[Guest]: what attracted me when I started interacting with Wahid. I realized that look, these guys,

02:32:49.960 --> 02:32:55.800
[Guest]: everything that he's saying is there out somewhere recorded. So when you're writing against powerful

02:32:55.800 --> 02:33:01.800
[Guest]: institutions and people, while they could harass you, one thing that I wanted to be sure which as

02:33:01.800 --> 02:33:07.640
[Guest]: a journalist is my duty is to ensure that you don't make wild allegations which are not backed

02:33:07.640 --> 02:33:17.480
[Guest]: by documents. And in his case, it's pure gold. While his lives were ruined, they have recorded

02:33:17.480 --> 02:33:24.040
[Guest]: that and I hope whatever was recorded in that court proceedings, I hope future police officers

02:33:24.040 --> 02:33:28.120
[Guest]: and intelligence officers of this country would read and draw the right lessons from that,

02:33:28.120 --> 02:33:35.000
[Guest]: those documentations. The Indian police service should put its head down in shame for the

02:33:35.000 --> 02:33:39.880
[Guest]: embarrassing way in which many of their so-called senior IPS officers behaved in their case.

02:33:39.880 --> 02:33:45.400
[Guest]: So, since 2006, I knew that this was a fake claim and the real terrorists have not been caught.

02:33:46.840 --> 02:33:52.360
[Guest]: But when I started meeting with Wahid, I realized that his story actually goes back

02:33:53.160 --> 02:33:59.880
[Guest]: and his entire life took a turn after 9-11. So, it was the waves of 9-11 attacks that hits the

02:33:59.880 --> 02:34:08.440
[Guest]: Bombay slum where Wahid lived and the US attack happens, India decides to act and overnight

02:34:08.440 --> 02:34:13.880
[Guest]: Simi, the student Islamic movement of India has declared a terrorist organization and police

02:34:13.880 --> 02:34:19.320
[Guest]: around the country is going around looking for Simi terrorists. And at Parkside police station,

02:34:19.320 --> 02:34:25.480
[Guest]: which is near Wahid's house, the police, as usual, with very few Muslims on its ranks,

02:34:25.480 --> 02:34:30.120
[Guest]: reaches out to informants and as you know informants in most societies are petty criminals

02:34:30.120 --> 02:34:34.680
[Guest]: or some with some criminal background, etc. So, the local mosque, one of the mullahs,

02:34:34.680 --> 02:34:40.680
[Guest]: preacher there, he tells, who had a kundak, who had some score to settle with Wahid,

02:34:40.680 --> 02:34:45.800
[Guest]: tells the police that Wahid is a Simi member. Police fix him up and that day his life changes.

02:34:45.800 --> 02:34:53.080
[Guest]: For the next 10, 12, 15 years, from a school teacher with some conservative views of Islamic

02:34:53.080 --> 02:34:59.720
[Guest]: views, religious views that Wahid has, which is his right, he is turned into a Simi terrorist and

02:34:59.720 --> 02:35:06.760
[Guest]: by 2013, the court throws out those claims. And later 2014, I think, Wahid is executed also. But

02:35:07.880 --> 02:35:12.760
[Guest]: life is ruined and nobody is responsible. No policeman has paid for it. And there are

02:35:12.760 --> 02:35:17.960
[Guest]: hundreds of such policemen around the country who have fake encounters, who have killed people,

02:35:17.960 --> 02:35:22.520
[Guest]: ruined people's lives because of either ill-information or some rivalry or revenge.

02:35:22.520 --> 02:35:30.600
[Guest]: Until we bring in accountability, we will have more and more Wahids being framed. Wahid is

02:35:30.600 --> 02:35:35.000
[Guest]: outstanding hero because he at least had the courage to record his story in the courts and he

02:35:35.000 --> 02:35:44.120
[Guest]: should trust. What we do not know is the stories of people who do not have the faith and courage

02:35:44.120 --> 02:35:52.920
[Guest]: to do this, to document their experiences. So, if you look at him, Wahid is tortured and there

02:35:52.920 --> 02:36:00.200
[Guest]: are torture chambers in ATS office in Mumbai, where in the room the AC is put at full blast

02:36:00.200 --> 02:36:07.320
[Guest]: and he is stripped naked and there are industrial belts kept there written, Sach bolne wala patta

02:36:07.320 --> 02:36:14.120
[Guest]: and there are posters saying that even the deaf and dumb will speak here. I mean, is that police

02:36:14.120 --> 02:36:18.680
[Amit Varma]: or is that some underworld don s chamber? I actually want to read out those couple of

02:36:18.680 --> 02:36:23.000
[Amit Varma]: paragraphs because I just want all the listeners to listen to it and pick up your book and I think

02:36:23.000 --> 02:36:28.200
[Amit Varma]: they are important paragraphs. So, I will read this out and first you set it up. And this is

02:36:28.200 --> 02:36:33.640
[Amit Varma]: after he is being arrested at one point in time and he is taken to this ATS office and you write,

02:36:33.640 --> 02:36:38.200
[Amit Varma]: quote, Wahid already knew that this repetition was anything but true. From the school, he was

02:36:38.200 --> 02:36:43.720
[Amit Varma]: taken to the ATS's Kala Chowki office and straight to a very odd room. He vividly recalls it,

02:36:43.720 --> 02:36:48.040
[Amit Varma]: describing the room as looking like the set of a cheap Bollywood film. It had no windows and its

02:36:48.040 --> 02:36:52.600
[Amit Varma]: walls were painted white. Much later, he realised that the wall had two layers to make it sound

02:36:52.600 --> 02:36:57.560
[Amit Varma]: proof. In the middle was a table and a chair. A bright light was on. On the table were syringes,

02:36:57.560 --> 02:37:03.400
[Amit Varma]: batons, coins, iodex gel, electric wires and a water pipe. A large truck tyre hung at one end.

02:37:03.400 --> 02:37:07.160
[Amit Varma]: There was a big bell, the kind used in factories which are several inches broad,

02:37:07.160 --> 02:37:12.600
[Amit Varma]: with slogans on it. Sach bol patta, meri awas suno, idhar goonga bhi bolta hai. And then there

02:37:12.600 --> 02:37:16.920
[Amit Varma]: were handcuffs and old newspapers. Even before he could make sense of the lay of the room,

02:37:16.920 --> 02:37:21.800
[Amit Varma]: Wahid was asked to strip naked. The AC was on full blast and the cement floor was freezing.

02:37:21.800 --> 02:37:26.600
[Amit Varma]: As a naked Wahid stood shivering, Raghuvanshi walked in wearing civvies. It must have been

02:37:26.600 --> 02:37:31.400
[Amit Varma]: around 12.30pm, Wahid estimates. Pointing his finger at Wahid, Raghuvanshi asked,

02:37:31.400 --> 02:37:36.680
[Amit Varma]: who is this? Wahid sir, a subordinate replied. Raghuvanshi took a step forward and kicked Wahid

02:37:36.680 --> 02:37:42.280
[Amit Varma]: in his groin. Stop quote. And then you go on to say, like basically Raghuvanshi who is this

02:37:42.280 --> 02:37:47.800
[Amit Varma]: police officer leading this, leading the ATS at the time, wants him to confess to hosting Pakistani

02:37:47.800 --> 02:37:52.840
[Amit Varma]: militants in his house for a couple of days and he says, hey, you know, that didn't happen. And

02:37:52.840 --> 02:37:57.000
[Amit Varma]: then you continue your description, quote, after half an hour of the dramatic interrogation,

02:37:57.000 --> 02:38:02.920
[Amit Varma]: the ATS chief left, issuing instructions. I want a photo of him jumping, so warm him up.

02:38:02.920 --> 02:38:07.960
[Amit Varma]: He slapped Wahid and said, I am not used to no. The gentleman cop, and you put this in quotes

02:38:07.960 --> 02:38:11.880
[Amit Varma]: because that's how he'd been described earlier. The gentleman cop walked out. After their boss's

02:38:11.880 --> 02:38:16.520
[Amit Varma]: departure, the other policemen told Wahid to accept everything. He refused. And then their

02:38:16.520 --> 02:38:21.000
[Amit Varma]: torture shifted to a new gear. The policemen pulled out a bottle of Surya Prakash oil,

02:38:21.000 --> 02:38:25.560
[Amit Varma]: an Ayurvedic mix of oils extracted from eucalyptus, clove, mint and camphor,

02:38:25.560 --> 02:38:30.520
[Amit Varma]: prescribed for pain relief. But in the interrogation rooms of the ATS, the oil was not

02:38:30.520 --> 02:38:35.720
[Amit Varma]: being put to use as per the directions of DM Patel, Pharma Private Limited, but as a tool in

02:38:35.720 --> 02:38:41.640
[Amit Varma]: the war on terror. The team thrust a tube into Wahid's rectum and injected the oil into his body.

02:38:41.640 --> 02:38:47.240
[Amit Varma]: Within a few minutes, his body was on fire. He started jumping. What the ATS chief wanted,

02:38:47.240 --> 02:38:52.600
[Amit Varma]: his subordinates and Surya Prakash oil had delivered in a few minutes, stop quote.

02:38:52.600 --> 02:38:58.680
[Amit Varma]: And what we see happening here, and by the way, Wahid was, you know, acquitted later by the court.

02:38:58.680 --> 02:39:02.840
[Amit Varma]: And I wanted to read this bit out because I just feel it's dramatic and everyone needs to,

02:39:02.840 --> 02:39:07.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, read the entire book, not just details of this. And Wahid was later acquitted. And what

02:39:07.240 --> 02:39:12.600
[Amit Varma]: was happening at this moment in time was that, you know, Surya Vanshi and the Mumbai Police

02:39:12.600 --> 02:39:18.680
[Amit Varma]: Commissioner A.N. Roy and the entire security establishment there was intent on fixing the

02:39:18.680 --> 02:39:23.800
[Amit Varma]: blame of the bomb blast, which, you know, ripped through those trains on someone and not leave it

02:39:23.800 --> 02:39:27.880
[Amit Varma]: as a case unsolved. And because they couldn't find the real perpetrators, they caught this guy.

02:39:27.880 --> 02:39:31.640
[Amit Varma]: And later on, when people from the Indian Mujahideen were apprehended in separate case,

02:39:31.640 --> 02:39:35.800
[Amit Varma]: they actually confessed to the bomb blast, gave details and so on and so forth. But the case

02:39:35.800 --> 02:39:40.760
[Amit Varma]: against these people continued nevertheless. And in fact, while, you know, reading your book,

02:39:40.760 --> 02:39:46.920
[Amit Varma]: I did some searches and came across this clip of Raghuvanshi being interrogated by Arnab

02:39:46.920 --> 02:39:51.720
[Amit Varma]: Goswami of All People in 2016, where, you know, Arnab is quizzing him on, you know,

02:39:51.720 --> 02:39:56.440
[Amit Varma]: why the other agencies, IB or CBI, I forgot, came out with different conclusions and he had

02:39:56.440 --> 02:40:01.800
[Amit Varma]: these conclusions. But let that part. My question is on, you know, what people call the streetlight

02:40:01.800 --> 02:40:06.760
[Amit Varma]: effect. Have you heard of the streetlight effect? No. So the streetlight effect takes its name from

02:40:07.480 --> 02:40:14.200
[Amit Varma]: this old anecdote that there is a drunk guy searching under a streetlight for something.

02:40:14.200 --> 02:40:18.760
[Amit Varma]: So a policeman comes to him and says, what are you searching for? And he says, oh, I dropped so

02:40:18.760 --> 02:40:23.320
[Amit Varma]: and so thing and so I'm searching for it. So the policeman helps him. And after a while,

02:40:23.320 --> 02:40:27.480
[Amit Varma]: the policeman asked him that, did you drop it here? And the drunk guy says, no, no, I dropped

02:40:27.480 --> 02:40:31.480
[Amit Varma]: it in the park there. So he says, and why are you searching here? So he said, because the park is

02:40:31.480 --> 02:40:37.480
[Amit Varma]: dark, there's light here. So I'm searching here. And that seems to me to be an apt metaphor for

02:40:37.480 --> 02:40:43.000
[Amit Varma]: the way security agencies in India do so much of their investigation that they don't really

02:40:43.000 --> 02:40:47.080
[Amit Varma]: care about the truth. They'll just do what is convenient. So if something happens,

02:40:47.080 --> 02:40:52.520
[Amit Varma]: you have so much power, it is far more convenient for you to pick up a few poor Muslims, get

02:40:52.520 --> 02:40:58.040
[Amit Varma]: confessions out of some of them, torture them till some of them turn approvers and build these false

02:40:58.040 --> 02:41:03.080
[Amit Varma]: cases. And oh my God, it's an inconvenience if the real culprits run up later, because you just

02:41:03.080 --> 02:41:07.160
[Amit Varma]: want the case solved and you want it over with. And so you're searching under the streetlight.

02:41:07.160 --> 02:41:14.040
[Amit Varma]: So does this seem like an accurate metaphor? And also in your book, this just happens time and time

02:41:14.040 --> 02:41:19.880
[Amit Varma]: again, it's almost institutionalized. So tell me a little bit about this and what leads to this kind

02:41:19.880 --> 02:41:25.560
[Amit Varma]: of mindset, like at some level it is that anti-Muslim nature, which we spoke about earlier,

02:41:25.560 --> 02:41:30.440
[Amit Varma]: but is that just state or are the incentives really out of whack that finding the real

02:41:30.440 --> 02:41:36.360
[Amit Varma]: criminals is not important, lowering the number of unsolved cases matters? What's happening here?

02:41:36.360 --> 02:41:45.240
[Guest]: And tell my listeners, how widespread is this? All of it, Amit, but beyond all that,

02:41:45.240 --> 02:41:50.680
[Guest]: there is an utter and complete lack of respect for the victims of this bomb blast.

02:41:52.440 --> 02:41:57.080
[Guest]: There are hundreds of people, Hindus, Muslims, Christians, all kinds of faith,

02:41:58.040 --> 02:42:01.640
[Guest]: and I would presume largely Hindus, who have lost their dear ones.

02:42:01.640 --> 02:42:07.800
[Guest]: They want to know who killed their dear ones, who destroyed their families. Our police officers,

02:42:07.800 --> 02:42:12.120
[Guest]: these police officers have no respect for them. Forget about the anti-Muslim bias.

02:42:13.000 --> 02:42:16.680
[Guest]: Our police officers don't have any respect for those grieving souls.

02:42:18.360 --> 02:42:21.800
[Guest]: And that is where we should begin the conversation and we should not be talking about anti-Muslim

02:42:21.800 --> 02:42:27.240
[Guest]: bias. Forget the Muslims. Tell me who killed my dear one in that bomb blast.

02:42:27.240 --> 02:42:32.760
[Guest]: For all the politics that we talk about, for all the anti-Muslim bias in the organization,

02:42:33.320 --> 02:42:40.280
[Guest]: I am saying that don't you have any sympathy or any concern about the quest for closure that

02:42:40.280 --> 02:42:46.840
[Guest]: the grieving families have? And this is not just in Mumbai. You find this across the country.

02:42:46.840 --> 02:42:54.440
[Guest]: You find this in Gujarat over and over again, in encounter killings. You find this in Naxal areas.

02:42:54.440 --> 02:43:02.440
[Guest]: You find this in Manipur. You find this in down south, in Tamil Nadu recently. All over.

02:43:03.560 --> 02:43:09.560
[Guest]: It's rampant. Our police forces are also in many ways uniformed gundas.

02:43:11.240 --> 02:43:17.240
[Guest]: And a few hundred, a few thousand people are killed in their, you know, in their custody annually.

02:43:18.840 --> 02:43:22.840
[Guest]: So, it's not an isolated thing. It's not even, it's not democratic. I mean,

02:43:22.840 --> 02:43:26.680
[Guest]: it's not democratic. I mean, how can you, how can we call ourselves a democracy

02:43:26.680 --> 02:43:32.280
[Guest]: if in the metropolis of ours, in the most important city of ours, you have interrogation chambers

02:43:32.920 --> 02:43:39.080
[Guest]: where they can do anything. And your judiciary has not, and you know, when Indian Mujahideen

02:43:39.080 --> 02:43:48.200
[Guest]: people owned up to the bombing, Waheed and the group went to appeal. So, Indian Mujahideen

02:43:48.200 --> 02:43:54.200
[Guest]: people in the court, the key witness, he was slightly shaky and did not own up completely

02:43:54.200 --> 02:43:59.000
[Guest]: because obviously legal pressure, etc, etc, whatever. When they appealed for the police

02:43:59.000 --> 02:44:04.920
[Guest]: officer who interrogated the Indian Mujahideen to be brought, to be called in as a witness,

02:44:04.920 --> 02:44:11.800
[Guest]: the appeal went to the Supreme Court and Supreme Court Chief Justice God bless him and other

02:44:11.800 --> 02:44:20.280
[Guest]: officers who said that it will set a wrong precedent. He wasn't bothered about the,

02:44:20.280 --> 02:44:24.440
[Guest]: probably the 12 innocents being accused as dreaded terrorists. He was bothered about

02:44:24.440 --> 02:44:31.960
[Guest]: wrong precedents. So, from the highest judiciary to the lowest courtroom, from the highest office

02:44:31.960 --> 02:44:37.720
[Guest]: of police and intelligence to the lower, we have become so insensitive. We are not even bothered

02:44:37.720 --> 02:44:45.080
[Guest]: about providing closure to the grieving families of ours. Forget about the Muslim biases, forget

02:44:45.080 --> 02:44:54.120
[Guest]: about the way we dehumanise Muslims, Dalits, dehumanise other people, Kashmiris, Manipuris,

02:44:54.120 --> 02:45:03.640
[Guest]: Northeast, whatever. So, if you see in the book, I, writing with angst about many such

02:45:03.640 --> 02:45:09.320
[Guest]: instances of which I could access records, it's only a minuscule part of what's happening.

02:45:09.960 --> 02:45:14.840
[Guest]: On a daily basis, the existence of an average Indian is a cruel existence. He is being

02:45:14.840 --> 02:45:19.080
[Guest]: tortured. He is afraid of going to a police station. In which country will a person be

02:45:19.080 --> 02:45:24.120
[Guest]: afraid of going into a police station? In which democracy can an ordinary human being be

02:45:24.120 --> 02:45:30.040
[Guest]: afraid of going into a police station? In which democracy will the lawyers tell their clients,

02:45:30.040 --> 02:45:35.960
[Guest]: don't go to police, avoid going to police at any cost? This is advice that people like me,

02:45:35.960 --> 02:45:41.240
[Guest]: I have received this advice. No, no, no, let's not do. If there are occasions when some shit,

02:45:41.240 --> 02:45:45.800
[Guest]: some notice, somebody sends, the lawyer is saying, no, no, let's avoid police because

02:45:45.800 --> 02:45:49.880
[Guest]: they can say anything. They can frame anything. Look at what's happening in Uttar Pradesh.

02:45:50.520 --> 02:45:57.000
[Guest]: I mean, they're killing left, right and centre man, which rule book of this country allows police

02:45:57.000 --> 02:46:05.960
[Guest]: to kill. So, it agitates me to think it's not about anti-being anti-Muslim. It's just cruel

02:46:07.560 --> 02:46:13.000
[Guest]: animals. And it's not that we don't have good police officers. We have got hundreds and

02:46:13.000 --> 02:46:17.960
[Guest]: thousands of good policemen out there. They're all quiet. They just do their job and go home.

02:46:18.760 --> 02:46:23.240
[Guest]: It's these thugs who are getting to power because they're satisfying political masters

02:46:23.240 --> 02:46:28.440
[Guest]: and because they become heroes, encounter cops. It's unbelievable.

02:46:29.320 --> 02:46:32.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, in the context of some of them, I'm reminded of Hannah Arendt's

02:46:32.200 --> 02:46:36.120
[Amit Varma]: phrase, the banality of evil. People who look like completely normal,

02:46:36.120 --> 02:46:40.120
[Amit Varma]: Sita Sada, people going around doing all of these things. There are some

02:46:40.680 --> 02:46:45.400
[Amit Varma]: moving stories from this time as well. Like you talk about Vinod Bhatt, for example,

02:46:45.400 --> 02:46:51.640
[Amit Varma]: the officer who is under pressure from the police commissioner A.N. Roy and this K.P.

02:46:51.640 --> 02:46:56.440
[Amit Varma]: Raghuvanshi fellow to file charge sheets against these people. And he doesn't want to because

02:46:56.440 --> 02:47:01.240
[Amit Varma]: he can see that it's all trumped up. And because he doesn't want to, they implicate his wife in

02:47:01.240 --> 02:47:07.960
[Amit Varma]: another case. And eventually he commits suicide in this really bizarre way that while crossing the,

02:47:08.520 --> 02:47:12.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, he's on the railway tracks and a train runs over him and he's got his official car

02:47:12.600 --> 02:47:16.760
[Amit Varma]: waiting. There's no reason for him at all to be on the platform. It's this bizarre thing.

02:47:16.760 --> 02:47:23.400
[Amit Varma]: And you also point out how Manmohan Singh at the time sent a CBI officer he trusted to oversee the

02:47:23.400 --> 02:47:29.160
[Amit Varma]: investigation. And that person, you know, while he was there, saw this Pakistani citizen being

02:47:29.160 --> 02:47:33.320
[Amit Varma]: interrogated there and clearly he had nothing to do with it. And when he went back to Delhi,

02:47:33.320 --> 02:47:39.320
[Amit Varma]: he heard news about how this same Pakistani citizen had now been arrested and implicated

02:47:39.320 --> 02:47:44.920
[Amit Varma]: and all of that in this complete cock and bull story. And by the way, the Pakistani citizen,

02:47:44.920 --> 02:47:49.960
[Amit Varma]: as it happened, had crossed over from Pakistan in Gujarat, where the gentleman called DG Vansara,

02:47:49.960 --> 02:47:55.160
[Amit Varma]: who features in different parts of your book, he's like popping up everywhere, had him sent

02:47:55.160 --> 02:48:00.920
[Amit Varma]: to Bombay. Let's talk about Gujarat now, partly because, you know, while you were speaking,

02:48:00.920 --> 02:48:07.720
[Amit Varma]: it also sort of struck me as incredibly naive to expect the security establishment, for example,

02:48:07.720 --> 02:48:11.800
[Amit Varma]: to care about the truth. The incentives are not about caring for the truth. The incentives are

02:48:11.800 --> 02:48:17.240
[Amit Varma]: about building the kind of narratives that suits them and their political masters. And a classic

02:48:17.240 --> 02:48:25.240
[Amit Varma]: example of that really is what happened in 2002 in Gujarat, especially how the Godhra narrative

02:48:25.240 --> 02:48:31.800
[Amit Varma]: changed, where the Godhra incident happens. And there's enough credible deposition that

02:48:31.800 --> 02:48:36.840
[Amit Varma]: it was not a pre-planned thing. It was just one of those things. It happened, great tragedy.

02:48:36.840 --> 02:48:43.080
[Amit Varma]: And then you have Modi landing up and then alleging that the ISI has caused it and, you know,

02:48:43.080 --> 02:48:49.080
[Amit Varma]: making the decision to take the bodies from Godhra to Ahmedabad and, you know, and everything else

02:48:49.080 --> 02:48:54.280
[Amit Varma]: that subsequently happened. But it is not just the riots. It's just the way that the security

02:48:54.280 --> 02:48:59.320
[Amit Varma]: establishment is used through the years over there in a way that you call the Gujarat model.

02:48:59.320 --> 02:49:05.000
[Guest]: Tell me more about that. I mean, I hope you agree with me that there is no other model in Gujarat.

02:49:05.000 --> 02:49:06.520
[Guest]: Definitely no economic model.

02:49:07.400 --> 02:49:11.880
[Amit Varma]: That's kind of what the results indicate. I mean, it's very clear even from Modi's record

02:49:11.880 --> 02:49:17.160
[Amit Varma]: over the last seven years that in terms of economics, he is as oppressive and autocratic as

02:49:17.160 --> 02:49:22.200
[Amit Varma]: people before him, really. I mean, I often say that he got the top-down economic planning model

02:49:22.200 --> 02:49:27.240
[Amit Varma]: from Nehru and the autocratic impulses from Indira. So it is ironic that he keeps blaming

02:49:27.240 --> 02:49:32.360
[Amit Varma]: those two. I think Indira in particular, or even Sanjay Gandhi is someone who seems a precursor

02:49:32.360 --> 02:49:36.440
[Amit Varma]: to what Modi has become. But anyway, that's a digression.

02:49:37.160 --> 02:49:43.560
[Guest]: So I think to me, the only model that is out of Gujarat is the security architecture. Because

02:49:43.560 --> 02:49:49.320
[Guest]: in many ways, Narendra Modi is a beneficiary of the 9-11 attacks in America. And it's a few

02:49:49.320 --> 02:49:55.080
[Guest]: months after that he becomes the chief minister of Gujarat. And after the Godhra tragedy, which

02:49:55.080 --> 02:50:00.520
[Guest]: actually is one of the worst tragedies of independent India, he lands up there. And

02:50:00.520 --> 02:50:05.720
[Guest]: for purely, I mean, the only reason, only logic I can think is political reasons. He says it's

02:50:05.720 --> 02:50:11.240
[Guest]: conspiracy contrary to what the district collector, local police officers and even watchman told the

02:50:11.240 --> 02:50:17.480
[Guest]: parliament. And he brings in a handpicked officer, Rakesh Shastana, who is now the Delhi Police

02:50:17.480 --> 02:50:24.040
[Guest]: Commission to investigate. His investigation is all centered around conspiracy. And as you know,

02:50:24.040 --> 02:50:29.400
[Guest]: the trial court threw out the conspiracy claims while it convicted some people. The fact is that

02:50:29.400 --> 02:50:40.600
[Guest]: they all acted again with the same callousness towards the victims. There are 55-60 grieving

02:50:40.600 --> 02:50:46.360
[Guest]: families and hundreds of people have lost their dear ones. You owe it to them. See, a police

02:50:46.360 --> 02:50:54.840
[Guest]: officer, a law enforcer, a political leader, at some level, you are also my comfort in my moment

02:50:54.840 --> 02:51:03.000
[Guest]: of grief. It's like doctors. So, in my moment of grief, I want closure. Any grieving person

02:51:03.000 --> 02:51:10.120
[Guest]: wants closure. You never let it happen. You did not provide the closure to those victims of Godhra.

02:51:11.320 --> 02:51:18.680
[Guest]: Instead, you created a political spectacle out of it. And we know what happened to it. I mean,

02:51:18.680 --> 02:51:25.800
[Guest]: the bodies are released from the Godhra district custody to VHP leaders. Which law in this country

02:51:25.800 --> 02:51:32.120
[Guest]: allows dead bodies to be handed over to strangers? Because they were ordered to do that, right?

02:51:33.720 --> 02:51:39.960
[Guest]: And it has been recorded by Justice V.R. Krishnayoga's Citizen Tribunal that it was

02:51:39.960 --> 02:51:44.120
[Guest]: Narendra Modi who ordered the bodies to be released. And the bodies are brought to Ahmedabad

02:51:44.120 --> 02:51:50.200
[Guest]: and it flies up into communal flare-up. And what do we gain? We have thousands of dead families,

02:51:50.200 --> 02:51:54.520
[Guest]: thousands of dead people and thousands grieving, both Hindus and Muslims. Let's forget it,

02:51:54.520 --> 02:52:00.040
[Guest]: Hindu-Muslim binaries. And Modi becomes this strong man and from there he goes on to build

02:52:00.040 --> 02:52:04.680
[Guest]: his so-called Gujarat economic model. But there is no model out there. And over the period that

02:52:04.680 --> 02:52:09.640
[Guest]: he is a chief minister, there are a few patterns which you cannot ignore. One being that there

02:52:09.640 --> 02:52:15.880
[Guest]: have been a spate of fake encounters. This is not my claim. This is not the claim of any activist.

02:52:15.880 --> 02:52:21.400
[Guest]: These are claims and statements made by Gujarat's own police when they were allowed to investigate,

02:52:21.400 --> 02:52:24.840
[Guest]: Gujarat's own judicial offices when they were allowed to investigate,

02:52:24.840 --> 02:52:30.040
[Guest]: Supreme Court monitored committees. They all said that there have been, all of them have been

02:52:30.040 --> 02:52:37.480
[Guest]: fake encounters from Ishrat Jahan encounter to Saurabhudin. In all of these cases,

02:52:37.480 --> 02:52:42.120
[Guest]: what is a terrorist coming for? Terrorist is coming to assassinate Narendra Modi.

02:52:43.080 --> 02:52:50.600
[Guest]: Now was somebody who had control of police trying to create a hero out of Modi or was it

02:52:50.600 --> 02:52:55.320
[Guest]: Modi himself designed this is something that should have been investigated and still needs

02:52:55.320 --> 02:53:01.880
[Guest]: to be investigated. But we still don't know. We don't know what would happen. And he comes to Delhi

02:53:01.880 --> 02:53:08.920
[Guest]: and after he comes to Delhi, you find a same pattern happening across India. Bhima Kauravgaon

02:53:08.920 --> 02:53:13.560
[Guest]: case is not the only case. In fact, I talk about another case where in Ranchi, they try to create

02:53:13.560 --> 02:53:19.320
[Guest]: a similar fake narrative of someone trying to assassinate Narendra Modi. Bhima Kauravgaon case

02:53:19.320 --> 02:53:25.480
[Guest]: is a criminal conspiracy by an arm of the state to frame some of our finest citizens. There is no

02:53:25.480 --> 02:53:30.200
[Guest]: doubt about that. I don't think there is any more dispute about it. Every police officer involved

02:53:30.200 --> 02:53:35.640
[Guest]: in it and any political master who was involved in it, they must all be going behind bars. They

02:53:35.640 --> 02:53:40.680
[Guest]: should all be facing trial if we call ourselves a democracy. Otherwise, we should rename our

02:53:40.680 --> 02:53:46.760
[Guest]: country as a banana republic. Otherwise, we should burn the constitution in the public square there

02:53:46.760 --> 02:53:51.560
[Guest]: and say that this constitution has no values. Bhima Kauravgaon is a very classic case of what

02:53:51.560 --> 02:53:57.560
[Guest]: I am trying to argue. And Gujarat model is the model of security architecture that Indira Gandhi

02:53:57.560 --> 02:54:03.960
[Guest]: perfected and Rajiv Gandhi misused which Narendra Modi has now taken to a different scale to

02:54:03.960 --> 02:54:11.080
[Guest]: challenge and ruin and demolish this democracy. Let's not shy away from being honest that if we

02:54:11.080 --> 02:54:17.000
[Guest]: don't speak up today, our silence is going to ruin the lives of our children. And that is one of the

02:54:17.000 --> 02:54:23.480
[Guest]: reasons why I wrote this book. I really adore my daughter and I hope she and her generation

02:54:23.480 --> 02:54:29.800
[Guest]: has a better future and can live in a meritorious society. A meritorious society is only possible

02:54:29.800 --> 02:54:37.160
[Guest]: if there is mature democracy. And we don't have it. It's the enemies of our emergence as a mature

02:54:37.160 --> 02:54:41.480
[Guest]: democracy, as a liberal democracy are the ones who are ruling this country and who are in the

02:54:41.480 --> 02:54:46.360
[Guest]: police force, in uniforms, in intelligence agencies. They need to be reined in. Otherwise,

02:54:46.360 --> 02:54:50.120
[Guest]: Amit, you and me, we won't even be able to tomorrow sit and discuss like this.

02:54:50.120 --> 02:54:56.600
[Guest]: And mind you, you will see the repercussions of me writing this book over the next few months

02:54:56.600 --> 02:55:01.880
[Guest]: when the same deep state will probably try to finger me. And you know what they've been up to

02:55:01.880 --> 02:55:10.440
[Guest]: in the last few years? It is all recorded that Adani or Ambani and other corporates who are

02:55:10.440 --> 02:55:17.320
[Guest]: Narendra Modi's great pals have all carried out serious breach of laws from over-invoicing of

02:55:17.320 --> 02:55:23.880
[Guest]: coal and electrical machinery, where the fine that the state should receive is 15,000 crore rupees

02:55:25.000 --> 02:55:30.440
[Guest]: or the Reliance Jio's license is forged. Instead of investigating those national

02:55:31.240 --> 02:55:37.080
[Guest]: scandals, the Income Tax and Enforcement Directorate are raiding small-time news startups.

02:55:38.120 --> 02:55:44.200
[Guest]: They are serving notices on journalists. They are coming to offices of our little small-time

02:55:44.200 --> 02:55:49.000
[Guest]: media outfits and telling them, why do you write against the government?

02:55:50.600 --> 02:55:56.280
[Guest]: Amit, my book is not just about Narendra Modi or Indira Gandhi. Amit, you spoke about incentives

02:55:56.280 --> 02:56:01.960
[Guest]: all through the conversation. Is there a bigger incentive than your ability to look into the

02:56:01.960 --> 02:56:08.360
[Guest]: eyes of your children and say that your father or mother was honest today? That I did not give

02:56:08.360 --> 02:56:14.440
[Guest]: into fear? Is there a bigger incentive for a journalist than go home saying that, look,

02:56:14.440 --> 02:56:21.000
[Guest]: I did something today. I wiped the tear of the last Indian. There is no bigger incentive here.

02:56:21.000 --> 02:56:31.160
[Guest]: I do not think that materialistic incentives can match the incentive of being morally honest.

02:56:31.160 --> 02:56:35.480
[Amit Varma]: I think, you know, what would be incentives for me and you would not necessarily be incentives

02:56:35.480 --> 02:56:40.360
[Amit Varma]: for people out there. And what we have also seen there, like you spoke about people being

02:56:40.360 --> 02:56:45.080
[Amit Varma]: silent. And, you know, one possible reason for that is not just the apathy people have because

02:56:45.080 --> 02:56:50.200
[Amit Varma]: they feel they cannot do anything, but also the chilling effect of what the state does to people

02:56:50.200 --> 02:56:54.120
[Amit Varma]: who do speak up. And just for the benefit of my listeners, I just want to point out that in the

02:56:54.120 --> 02:57:01.720
[Amit Varma]: Bhima Koregaon case, as Josie just said, it is now beyond any doubt that they were framed. One

02:57:01.720 --> 02:57:08.440
[Amit Varma]: of the first activists to be arrested was Rona Wilson. Forensic analysis has shown conclusively

02:57:08.440 --> 02:57:13.640
[Amit Varma]: that all the evidence on his computer was actually planted and, you know, it was hacked and planted

02:57:13.640 --> 02:57:19.720
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. And it's just this extremely complex and sophisticated operation, obviously,

02:57:19.720 --> 02:57:25.240
[Amit Varma]: done by an arm of the security agency. Now, I'm not going to keep you much longer. I'm just going

02:57:25.240 --> 02:57:31.320
[Amit Varma]: to end with some final observations and questions because everyone should go out there and read your

02:57:31.320 --> 02:57:37.240
[Amit Varma]: book. Obviously, one conversation can't do justice to so many years of work and such a vast narrative,

02:57:37.240 --> 02:57:42.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, and there are so many arcs in there. There is the arc about how security agencies

02:57:42.040 --> 02:57:46.680
[Amit Varma]: have created their own militant outfits all over the place. They did it in Kashmir,

02:57:46.680 --> 02:57:50.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, Salwa, Jodhum and Chhattisgarh and the kind of havoc that they create,

02:57:50.680 --> 02:57:55.400
[Amit Varma]: sometimes even worse than the terrorists. You've also written about the fascinating story of

02:57:56.120 --> 02:58:01.160
[Amit Varma]: Afzal Guru and the connection with the Vindarsingh that apparently he was asked by the Vindarsingh

02:58:01.160 --> 02:58:06.840
[Amit Varma]: to come to Delhi and to put up these people and, you know, before that he was just an informer and

02:58:06.840 --> 02:58:11.080
[Amit Varma]: you've spoken about how so many informers are later framed themselves and the Vindarsingh,

02:58:11.080 --> 02:58:16.600
[Amit Varma]: of course, was in the news. Firstly, last year or the year before that when, you know, he was

02:58:16.600 --> 02:58:22.520
[Amit Varma]: arrested in Kashmir by his own police carrying two terrorists in his car. And just recently,

02:58:22.520 --> 02:58:26.600
[Amit Varma]: if I remember correctly, there was some news item where, you know, the state put out this

02:58:26.600 --> 02:58:30.520
[Amit Varma]: notice saying that they're not going to pursue the case in national security interests or some

02:58:30.520 --> 02:58:34.760
[Amit Varma]: shit like that, whatever that means. So, is that something you can speak about, by the way?

02:58:34.760 --> 02:58:39.640
[Guest]: What is the Vindarsingh deal? The Vindarsingh has been this notorious,

02:58:39.640 --> 02:58:46.520
[Guest]: like many notorious Kashmir police officers who have been known for being mixed up with,

02:58:47.480 --> 02:58:52.680
[Guest]: see, in the fog of war, you know, a police officer will have to deal with informants,

02:58:52.680 --> 02:58:57.800
[Guest]: militants, etc. And I'm not stating any state secret when I'm saying that Afzal Guru

02:58:57.800 --> 02:59:06.040
[Guest]: was a militant who returned home and wanted to try to lead a normal life but was forced to be

02:59:06.040 --> 02:59:13.240
[Guest]: an informant with BSF and with the police. And he was quite notorious in Sopore where,

02:59:13.240 --> 02:59:17.480
[Guest]: which is a very pro-militant area, he knew that he'll be bummed off by the militants because

02:59:17.480 --> 02:59:22.280
[Guest]: he was betraying far too many militants. So, he decided to leave and come to Delhi and that is

02:59:22.280 --> 02:59:27.240
[Guest]: when he says the Vindarsingh called him up and asked him to come down to Kashmir and one last

02:59:27.240 --> 02:59:33.640
[Guest]: job for him. This claim that Afzal Guru has made in the court, the Vindarsingh has not refuted.

02:59:33.640 --> 02:59:39.080
[Guest]: His allegation was against a uniformed police officer of this country. So, I would go by Afzal

02:59:39.080 --> 02:59:46.040
[Guest]: Guru until the Vindarsingh comes to court and refutes it, right? So, he's asked to, from

02:59:46.040 --> 02:59:50.280
[Guest]: Kashmir, bring these people and drop them to Delhi who are the people who end up attacking

02:59:50.280 --> 02:59:56.600
[Guest]: the parliament. And Afzal Guru at the trial court, in fact, if you know, he did not take

02:59:56.600 --> 03:00:02.920
[Guest]: any legal help. He said, I don't want any lawyers to help because he told someone who was in jail

03:00:02.920 --> 03:00:08.840
[Guest]: with him that he has been promised by the police that after the trial and conviction etc, he'll be

03:00:08.840 --> 03:00:15.320
[Guest]: freed, he'll be a free man. So, the deep state that was at work at the parliament attack is

03:00:15.320 --> 03:00:18.680
[Guest]: something that needs to be investigated. It is not a very simple terrorist attack.

03:00:20.040 --> 03:00:25.320
[Guest]: There was arms of the state which were involved in it. And again, mind you, I am not talking some

03:00:25.320 --> 03:00:31.480
[Guest]: wild conspiracy theory here, Amit. I am talking about for the fate of our children, for the future

03:00:31.480 --> 03:00:36.920
[Guest]: of our children, for the future of this democracy, truth is our greatest defense for any democracy.

03:00:36.920 --> 03:00:41.560
[Guest]: And I can tell you there are some masters out there in the governance structures even today

03:00:41.560 --> 03:00:45.400
[Guest]: who will say, oh, you know, the collective interest of the country should override that

03:00:45.400 --> 03:00:51.240
[Guest]: of the individual. No. An individual empowered with his liberty is the greatest assurance of a

03:00:51.240 --> 03:00:58.360
[Guest]: state. Not the otherwise. There is nobody out there who has the wisdom to decide what is good

03:00:58.360 --> 03:01:05.960
[Guest]: for the state other than that illiterate voter out in that dirty village. Devendra Singh continues

03:01:05.960 --> 03:01:10.040
[Guest]: to do whatever he was doing. Finally, he was arrested when he was again trying to bring some

03:01:10.040 --> 03:01:17.720
[Guest]: terrorists to Delhi. Again, claims of J&K police, not ours. But this case is taken over by NIA for

03:01:17.720 --> 03:01:23.080
[Guest]: whatever reason. And if NIA was to be investigating terror angle or whatever, I do not think anything

03:01:23.080 --> 03:01:28.280
[Guest]: coming. What we know is that the state government has decided to discharge him from government,

03:01:28.280 --> 03:01:35.080
[Guest]: right, to compulsorily retire him and not to pursue the case. Expected because we have heard

03:01:35.080 --> 03:01:41.240
[Guest]: other stories of Devendra Singh s linkages to higher ups. Devendra Singh is not an outlier as

03:01:41.240 --> 03:01:50.200
[Guest]: you say. He is not a lone wolf. He is that visible tip of an iceberg where there are far

03:01:50.200 --> 03:01:54.920
[Guest]: bigger fishes out there in that iceberg. Yeah, visible tip of an iceberg is a good

03:01:54.920 --> 03:01:59.800
[Amit Varma]: way to put it. Though I do not know how fishes get inside icebergs, but I get it.

03:02:00.520 --> 03:02:05.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, another fascinating strand of your book which I would like listeners to read for

03:02:05.880 --> 03:02:11.320
[Amit Varma]: themselves is all about the strand of how the security establishment went easy on Hindu terror

03:02:11.320 --> 03:02:15.640
[Amit Varma]: and on groups like Abhinav Bharat to the extent that, you know, as you mentioned in the book,

03:02:15.640 --> 03:02:20.520
[Amit Varma]: you have been told by people that they might have been a creation of the security establishment

03:02:20.520 --> 03:02:26.600
[Amit Varma]: itself. All very scary stuff. So there is this, you know, excellent quote right at the end of

03:02:26.600 --> 03:02:32.680
[Amit Varma]: your book which I want to read out with the last five words being key. Quote, there is a strange

03:02:32.680 --> 03:02:37.480
[Amit Varma]: pattern in some of these cases. The investigation agency prepares a massive charge sheet running to

03:02:37.480 --> 03:02:42.200
[Amit Varma]: thousands of pages attaching all kinds of evidence that no one will have the time or patience to go

03:02:42.200 --> 03:02:47.320
[Amit Varma]: through in detail. When these cases go to trial, the accused may well be exonerated. But in the

03:02:47.320 --> 03:02:52.360
[Amit Varma]: slow churn of the Indian judiciary, the process is a punishment. Stop quote. And these words,

03:02:52.360 --> 03:02:57.320
[Amit Varma]: of course, the process is the punishment, the old cliche. And this is what we see in Bhima Korega.

03:02:57.320 --> 03:03:03.000
[Amit Varma]: This is what we see repeatedly time and again. So first of all, I got to laud you for your

03:03:03.000 --> 03:03:07.560
[Amit Varma]: idealism and your courage in writing the book. I mean, you know, at the start where you lambasted

03:03:07.560 --> 03:03:11.480
[Amit Varma]: Rakesh Asana and then pointed out that he's a current police commissioner of Delhi where you

03:03:11.480 --> 03:03:17.400
[Amit Varma]: live. I was like, my God, you know, how is this guy doing this? So tell me a little bit about

03:03:17.400 --> 03:03:22.280
[Amit Varma]: your future projects if you wish to talk about them. And also about the other things you do.

03:03:22.280 --> 03:03:26.840
[Amit Varma]: Like earlier, you mentioned you were a multitasker. There are startups. Before we started our

03:03:26.840 --> 03:03:33.960
[Amit Varma]: conversation, you told me you were in my part of town in Mumbai recently because you were meeting

03:03:33.960 --> 03:03:38.840
[Amit Varma]: all kinds of interesting film people for different projects and all of that. So is there something

03:03:38.840 --> 03:03:45.880
[Amit Varma]: you'd like to share with what is coming up for you? And what would you like to tell not just

03:03:45.880 --> 03:03:51.240
[Amit Varma]: investigative journalists, but also people in civil society who feel animated by these problems?

03:03:51.240 --> 03:03:55.720
[Amit Varma]: But they must be thinking that why should I speak out? Why should I risk myself? You know,

03:03:55.720 --> 03:04:01.320
[Amit Varma]: do the practical thing just now. You know, it's a chilling effect at work. Just chill. You know,

03:04:01.320 --> 03:04:07.240
[Amit Varma]: it's a very nice book. I'll recommend it to friends in person. But, you know, why get further

03:04:07.240 --> 03:04:12.200
[Amit Varma]: into this? Let shit play out. Especially if you're elite Hindus and you're thinking that, you know,

03:04:12.200 --> 03:04:17.800
[Amit Varma]: I am not at danger at any moment in time. Let me get on with life. Yes, you know, at an intellectual

03:04:17.800 --> 03:04:22.440
[Amit Varma]: level, this is shocking. But why should I do anything? What would you have to tell them,

03:04:22.440 --> 03:04:30.360
[Guest]: for example? Answering the first part. So I have this media startup where trying to see if I can

03:04:30.360 --> 03:04:35.960
[Guest]: create a scalable model of investigative journalism, which where I can sustain and

03:04:35.960 --> 03:04:41.480
[Guest]: support rigorous investigative journalism, which can be scaled up. Because the existing models

03:04:41.480 --> 03:04:48.280
[Guest]: which are dependent upon subscriptions, advertisement or reader donations are not

03:04:48.280 --> 03:04:53.560
[Guest]: very scalable. So I am trying to convert. I am trying to see if I can convert some of my

03:04:53.560 --> 03:04:58.680
[Guest]: investigative stories or our stories into documentaries, books, scripted series,

03:04:58.680 --> 03:05:01.960
[Guest]: films, etc. We have announced a feature film last week called Fandom Hospital,

03:05:02.600 --> 03:05:07.080
[Guest]: which is where the Malayalam director Mahesh Narayan is making his Bollywood entry,

03:05:07.800 --> 03:05:12.520
[Guest]: and which I am co-producing with Tuss Tales, which is founded by Preeti Sahani.

03:05:12.520 --> 03:05:18.520
[Guest]: She is a producer of Talwar, Raazi, etc. I do have some projects with Vikram Motwane

03:05:18.520 --> 03:05:24.840
[Guest]: and Andhra Krishap, etc. The idea is to see whether I can, we can find partners who would

03:05:24.840 --> 03:05:29.640
[Guest]: want to adopt edgy, real-life investigative stories. But one thing which I made good

03:05:29.640 --> 03:05:34.040
[Guest]: happening is that at the peak of the content revolution that is sweeping the world, there

03:05:34.040 --> 03:05:40.360
[Guest]: is a huge demand for real-life, edgy stories. From Anarchos to When They See Us to Chernobyl

03:05:40.360 --> 03:05:44.840
[Guest]: is all real-life stories. So that is where I am trying to place my journalism and see if I can

03:05:44.840 --> 03:05:52.280
[Guest]: sell. But given the chilling censorship that is sweeping India, I am finding a lot of resistance.

03:05:52.280 --> 03:05:56.600
[Guest]: But that is okay. That is part of life. To the second part of the question,

03:05:56.600 --> 03:06:01.480
[Guest]: which is about you, what you said about the elite, upper caste, Hindus especially.

03:06:03.000 --> 03:06:09.320
[Guest]: See if you let the monster grow. It does not have any religion. Monster has no religion,

03:06:09.320 --> 03:06:15.080
[Guest]: no differentiators. They will come for you. They will come for you in the form of income

03:06:15.080 --> 03:06:20.520
[Guest]: tax notices. They will come for you in the form of police bribes. They will come for you in the

03:06:20.520 --> 03:06:26.120
[Guest]: form of dirty roads. They will come for you in the form of flooded cities. They will come for

03:06:26.120 --> 03:06:32.840
[Guest]: you in the form of pollution. They will come, they will get you. If you quietly sit back

03:06:34.040 --> 03:06:38.920
[Guest]: and think that this will all wash away, because the police is anti-Muslim. No.

03:06:38.920 --> 03:06:40.640
[Guest]: Because the state is anti-Muslim.

03:06:40.640 --> 03:06:41.640
[Guest]: No.

03:06:41.640 --> 03:06:43.160
[Guest]: They are getting you.

03:06:43.160 --> 03:06:48.200
[Guest]: Do you know at least a part of the pollution that we are breathing, air pollution in this

03:06:48.200 --> 03:06:54.520
[Guest]: country is contributed by the poor quality of coal that a group of corrupt corporates

03:06:54.520 --> 03:06:56.840
[Guest]: have imported into India?

03:06:56.840 --> 03:07:01.360
[Guest]: Do you know that you are paying extra charge for electricity because they have overbilled

03:07:01.360 --> 03:07:04.660
[Guest]: for their power generation equipments?

03:07:04.660 --> 03:07:11.480
[Guest]: So at every turn of your life, you are already a victim of this nepotistic state, this corrupt

03:07:11.480 --> 03:07:14.600
[Guest]: state and the security establishment.

03:07:14.600 --> 03:07:15.960
[Guest]: So you have no option.

03:07:15.960 --> 03:07:19.440
[Guest]: Either you speak up, stand up together.

03:07:19.440 --> 03:07:20.440
[Guest]: We don't know.

03:07:20.440 --> 03:07:21.440
[Guest]: We will debate.

03:07:21.440 --> 03:07:22.440
[Guest]: We can disagree.

03:07:22.440 --> 03:07:25.360
[Guest]: You can say that I am too sympathetic towards Muslims.

03:07:25.360 --> 03:07:26.360
[Guest]: I am too...

03:07:26.360 --> 03:07:27.600
[Guest]: You can say anything to me.

03:07:27.600 --> 03:07:30.400
[Guest]: But let's debate rationally, intelligently.

03:07:30.400 --> 03:07:31.800
[Guest]: Let us not be afraid.

03:07:31.800 --> 03:07:39.920
[Guest]: Let us not be so afraid that we will start playing video game visuals as TV news.

03:07:39.920 --> 03:07:46.120
[Guest]: Let us not be so afraid that we will start carrying and discussing fake WhatsApp forwards

03:07:46.120 --> 03:07:47.560
[Guest]: as truth.

03:07:47.560 --> 03:07:55.200
[Guest]: Let us not be so afraid that we snatch away the dreams of our children.

03:07:55.200 --> 03:08:01.000
[Guest]: We intimidate our children to sleep, not letting them dream.

03:08:01.000 --> 03:08:03.000
[Guest]: And those have no religions.

03:08:03.000 --> 03:08:05.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, very wise words.

03:08:05.040 --> 03:08:10.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I've always said that India's core problem is a predatory state that our founders

03:08:10.840 --> 03:08:15.480
[Amit Varma]: designed and that predatory state has already predated upon us and is doing so as we kind

03:08:15.480 --> 03:08:19.080
[Amit Varma]: of are not even aware, you know, the seen and the unseen right there.

03:08:19.080 --> 03:08:24.520
[Amit Varma]: Josie, I'm just filled with even more admiration for you after chatting with you and reading

03:08:24.520 --> 03:08:26.320
[Amit Varma]: The Silent Coup, which is such a wonderful book.

03:08:26.320 --> 03:08:30.920
[Amit Varma]: So thank you so much for your time and your insights and take care, boss.

03:08:30.920 --> 03:08:31.920
[Guest]: Thank you, Amit.

